 {{abbr|THEX|Tree Hash EXchange format.}}\n! [[Transport Layer Security|TLS]]\n! Other\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"background:{{Rh2/bgcolor}}\" colspan=2 | [[BearShare]]\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| -\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"background:{{Rh2/bgcolor}}\" colspan=2 | [[giFT]] (core & plug-ins)\n| {{yes}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|Client mode only, as a dependent leaf on ultrapeers.}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}} {{efn|name=b}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| -\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"background:{{Rh2/bgcolor}}\" colspan=2 | [[GnucDNA]] {{efn|Version 0.9.2.7}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{n/a}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}} {{efn|name=b}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| -\n|-\n! scope=row colspan=2 | [[gtk-gnutella]]\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=d}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|[[gtk-gnutella]] version 0.98.4 and later.}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}} (Dropped)\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[IPv6]], [[Distributed hash table|DHT]], GUESS, [[Gnutella2|G2]]\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"background:{{Rh2/bgcolor}}\" colspan=2 | [[LimeWire]]{{efn|name=h}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=d}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{Yes|GMail or XMPP}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=e}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=g}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[Distributed hash table|DHT]]\n|-\n! scope=row colspan=2 | [[WireShare]]{{efn|name=h}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=d}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{Yes|GMail or XMPP}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=e}}\n| {{yes}} {{efn|name=g}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[Distributed hash table|DHT]]\n|-\n! scope=row style=\"background:{{Rh2/bgcolor}}\" colspan=2 | [[Phex]]\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}{{efn|Via [[SOCKS]] proxy which can tunnel over [[Secure Shell|SSH]].}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| [[I2P]]\n|-\n! scope=row colspan=2 | [[Shareaza]]\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}{{efn|Since version 2.2.4.0}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| [[Gnutella2|G2]], [[BitTorrent (protocol)|BT]], [[eDonkey network|eD2k]], [[IRC]]\n|}\n\n==== Notes ====\n{{notelist-lr}}\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=b|Not high [[outdegree]], so is unusable in its current form.}}\n{{efn|name=d|Via the [[Kademlia]]-based Mojito DHT network supported only by LimeWire and gtk-gnutella (starting with version r15750); this is completely different from [[SHA-1]] searches supported by most gnutella clients.}}\n{{efn|name=e|Port triggering or ''firewall to firewall'' (FW2FW).}}\n{{efn|name=g|Automatic with UPnP, or manual configuration in LimeWire firewall options}}\n{{efn|name=h|As the LimeWire client is no longer available clients that share most of LimeWire's code base, like [[FrostWire]], can provide an alternative.}}\n}}\n<!-- * No features have been recorded for the [[gnutella]] clients [[iMesh]], Symella, [[TrustyFiles]], and [[WinMX]] Music. -->\n* [[Morpheus (software)|Morpheus]] differs significantly and may have completely independent code from the GnucDNA engine.  Morpheus can function as a ''modern'' ultrapeer whereas other GnucDNA clients cannot.\n* [[GnucDNA#Gnucleus|Gnucleus]] and Kiwi Alpha use the [[GnucDNA]] engine.\n* [[BearFlix]], a functionally limited version of the [[BearShare]] 5.2 series, can search only for images or videos and shared videos are limited to a relatively short length.\n* [[giFTcurs]], [[Apollon (software)|Apollon]], [[FilePipe]], [[giFToxic]], [[giFTui]], [[giFTwin32]], [[KCeasy]], [[Poisoned]], and [[Xfactor (software)|Xfactor]] are GUI front-ends for the [[giFT]] engine.\n* [[etomi]] uses outdated [[Shareaza]] networking code.\n* [[MP3 Rocket]], 360Share,  LemonWire, MP3Torpedo, and DexterWire are variants of [[LimeWire]].\n* [[FrostWire]] (up to version 4.21.8) is nearly identical to LimeWire 4.18 but versions greater than 5.00 no longer use gnutella.\n* [[Acquisition (software)|Acquisition]] and [[Cabos]] are custom front-ends overlaying the [[LimeWire]] engine.\n* [[LimeWire Pirate Edition]] (5.6.2) is a resurrected version of the unreleased [[LimeWire]] 5.6.1 alpha, thus has similar features minus automatic updates (with nags) and centralized remote controls to disable core functions like searches and downloads were removed.\n\n== Gnutella2 ==\n{{Main|Gnutella2}}\nThe Gnutella2 protocol (often referred to as G2), despite its name, is not a successor protocol of Gnutella nor related to the original Gnutella project,<ref>[http://www.mp3newswire.net/stories/2003/gnutella2.html Gnutella vs. Gnutella2, Part 2] Thomas Mennecke for [[Slyck.com]], February 25, 2003.</ref> but rather is a completely different protocol that [[fork (software development)|forked]] from the original project and piggybacked on the Gnutella name. A sore point with many Gnutella developers is that the ''Gnutella2'' name conveys an upgrade or superiority, which led to a flame war. Other criticism included the use of the Gnutella network to bootstrap G2 peers and poor documentation of the G2 protocol. Additionally, the more frequent search retries of the [[Shareaza]] client, one of the initial G2 clients, could unnecessarily burden the Gnutella network.<ref>[http://www.slyck.com/news.php?story=100 Gnutella vs. Gnutella2, Part 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305053853/http://www.slyck.com/news.php?story=100 |date=2016-03-05 }} Thomas Mennecke for [[Slyck.com]], February 25, 2003</ref>\n\nBoth protocols have undergone significant changes since the fork in 2002. G2 has advantages and disadvantages compared to Gnutella. An advantage often cited is Gnutella2's hybrid search is more efficient than the original Gnutella's [[query flooding]], which was later replaced by more efficient search methods, starting with Query Routing in 2002, which was proposed in 2001 by Limewire developers.<ref>[http://wortschatz.uni-leipzig.de/~fwitschel/vorlP2P/literatur/search_methods.pdf A comparison of Peer-to-Peer search methods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926110918/http://wortschatz.uni-leipzig.de/~fwitschel/vorlP2P/literatur/search_methods.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }} Dimitrios Tsoumakos, 2003</ref><ref>[http://www.ic.unicamp.br/~celio/peer2peer/gnutella-related/query-routing-protocol.htm Query Routing for the Gnutella Network proposal] Christopher Rohrs, 2001-12-18</ref><ref>[http://www.ic.unicamp.br/~celio/peer2peer/gnutella-related/query-routing-protocol.htm Query Routing for the Gnutella Network 1.0] Christopher Rohrs, 2002-05-16</ref> An advantage for Gnutella is that its users number in the millions,<ref name=\"population\"/> whereas the G2 network is approximately an order of magnitude smaller.<ref>[http://crawler.trillinux.org/ G2 Network Statistics] Population ~200,000 January 2010.</ref>  It is difficult to compare the protocols in their current form; the individual client choice will probably have as much of an effect to an end user on either network.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bitzi]]\n* [[Gnutella crawler]]\n* [[GNUnet]]\n\n== References ==\n{{more citations needed|date=July 2013}}\n{{Reflist}}\n* Dye, Mark. McDonald, Rick. Rufi, Antoon W., 'Network Fundamentals', Cisco Networking Academy, Cisco Press, Ch 3. p91\n* Dye, Mark. McDonald, Rick. Rufi, Antoon W., 'Network Fundamentals', Cisco Networking Academy, Cisco Press, Ch 3. p90\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikibooks|The World of Peer-to-Peer (P2P)/Networks and Protocols/Gnutella}}\n* [http://www.gnutellaforums.com/ Gnutella Forums] Official user support boards\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090331221153/http://wiki.limewire.org/index.php?title=GDF Gnutella Protocol Development Wiki] (on [[Internet Archive]], 2009)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20011124014919/http://gnutella.wego.com/ Gnutella Protocol Development Portal] (on Internet Archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080525005017/http://www.gnutella.com/ Gnutella official website]  (on Internet Archive)\n* [http://gnufu.net GnuFU], ''Gnutella For Users: A description of the inner workings of the gnutella network in User-Friendly Style''\n* [https://www.gnu.org/philosophy/gnutella.html ''Regarding Gnutella'' by GNU]\n* [https://broadband.mpi-sws.org/transparency/bttest.php Glasnost] test Gnutella [[traffic shaping]] ([[Max Planck Institute for Software Systems]])\n\n{{Gnutella}}\n{{File sharing protocols}}\n\n[[Category:Gnutella| ]]\n[[Category:File sharing networks]]\n[[Category:Application layer protocols]]\n[[Category:Hash based data structures]]\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/MP3 Rocket (2nd nomination)closed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnutella"}
{"title_page": "Constantine II, Prince of Armenia", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Constantine of Armenia (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name            =Constantine II\n| title           =Lord of Cilicia / \u201cLord of the Mountains\u201d\n| image           =\n| succession    =[[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Lord of Armenian Cilicia]]\n| reign         =1129/1130\n| predecessor     =[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]\n| successor       =[[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leo I]]\n| spouse         =\n| issue          =\n| house          =[[Rubenids|Roupenians]]\n| father         =[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]\n| mother         =\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = after February 17, 1129\n| death_place =\n| place of burial=\n}}\n\n'''Constantine II'''<ref name='Runciman'>{{cite book | last = Runciman | first = Steven | title = A History of the Crusades \u2013 Volume II.: The Kingdom of Jerusalem and the Frankish East: 1100\u20131187}}</ref> ({{lang-hy|\u053f\u0578\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0564\u056b\u0576 \u0532}}), also '''Kostandin II''',<ref name='Cawley'>{{MLCC |warning=1 |url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ARMENIA.htm#_Toc184469941|title=Lords of the Mountains, Kings of (Cilician) Armenia (Family of Rupen)|title-date=2009-04-01|date=August 2012}}</ref> (unknown<ref name='Cawley'/> \u2013 after February 17, 1129<ref name='Cawley'/>) was the fourth [[King of Cilicia|lord of Armenian Cilicia]]<ref name='Ghazarian'/> or \u201cLord of the Mountains\u201d<ref name='Cawley'/> (1129<ref name='Cawley'/>/1130<ref name='Runciman'/>).\n\nThe ''Chronique Rim\u00e9e de la Petite Arm\u00e9nie'' (\u201cThe Rhymed Chronicle of Armenia Minor\u201d) of Vahram of Edessa records that he was the son of [[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I, lord of Armenian Cilicia]].<ref name='Cawley'/> His mother\u2019s name is not known.<ref name='Cawley'/>\n\nHe died a few months after his father\u2019s death in the course of a palace intrigue.<ref name='Runciman'/> Vahram of Edessa, the historian tells us that he was cast into prison and poisoned to death.<ref name='Ghazarian'>{{cite book | last = Ghazarian | first = Jacob G. | title = The Armenian Kingdom in Cilicia during the Crusades: The Integration of Cilician Armenians with the Latins (1080\u20131093)}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|''After the death of Thoros, his only son and heir was cast into prison by some wicked people, who administered to him a poisonous drug, thus the principality came to [[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leon]], the brother of Thoros (\u2026).''|Vahram of Edessa: ''The Rhymed Chronicle of Armenia Minor''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/vahramschronicle00vahrrich|title=Chronicle|publisher=Internet Archive|work=Text Archive|date=2008-09-10|author=Vahram|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>}}\n\nOther historians (''e.g.'', Jacob G. Ghazarian, Vahan M. Kurkjian) suggest that Thoros I died without a male heir<ref name='Ghazarian'/> and was succeeded by Leon I.<ref name='Kurkjian'>{{cite web|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/27*.html|title=A History of Armenia|publisher=Bill Thayer|work=Website|date=2005-04-05|author=Vahan M. Kurkjian|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*Ghazarian, Jacob G: ''The Armenian Kingdom in Cilicia during the Crusades: The Integration of Cilician Armenians with the Latins (1080\u20131393)''; RoutledgeCurzon (Taylor & Francis Group), 2000, Abingdon; {{ISBN|0-7007-1418-9}}\n*Runciman, Steven: ''A History of the Crusades \u2013 Volume II.: The Kingdom of Jerusalem and the Frankish East: 1100\u20131187''; Cambridge University Press, 1988, Cambridge; {{ISBN|0-521-06162-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/27*.html The Barony of Cilician Armenia] (Kurkjian's History of Armenia, Ch.&nbsp;27)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Rubenid dynasty|House of Roupen]]}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]|title=[[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Lord of Armenian Cilicia]]|years=1129/1130|after=[[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leo I]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Armenian kings}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constantine Ii, Prince Of Armenia}}\n[[Category:1129 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Deaths by poisoning]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:12th-century Armenian people]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of the Rubenid dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Constantine of Armenia (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n| name            =Constantine II\n| title           =Lord of Cilicia / \u201cLord of the Mountains\u201d\n| image           =\n| succession    =[[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Lord of Armenian Cilicia]]\n| reign         =1129/1130\n| predecessor     =[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]\n| successor       =[[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leo I]]\n| spouse         =\n| issue          =\n| house          =[[Rubenids|Roupenians]]\n| father         =[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]\n| mother         =\n| birth_date  =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = after February 17, 1129\n| death_place =\n| place of burial=\n}}\n\n'''Constantine II'''<ref name='Runciman'>{{cite book | last = Runciman | first = Steven | title = A History of the Crusades \u2013 Volume II.: The Kingdom of Jerusalem and the Frankish East: 1100\u20131187}}</ref> ({{lang-hy|\u053f\u0578\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0564\u056b\u0576 \u0532}}), also '''Kostandin II''',<ref name='Cawley'>{{MLCC |warning=1 |url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/ARMENIA.htm#_Toc184469941|title=Lords of the Mountains, Kings of (Cilician) Armenia (Family of Rupen)|title-date=2009-04-01|date=August 2012}}</ref> (unknown<ref name='Cawley'/> \u2013 after February 17, 1129<ref name='Cawley'/>) was the fourth [[King of Cilicia|lord of Armenian Cilicia]]<ref name='Ghazarian'/> or \u201cLord of the Mountains\u201d<ref name='Cawley'/> (1129<ref name='Cawley'/>/1130<ref name='Runciman'/>).\n\nThe ''Chronique Rim\u00e9e de la Petite Arm\u00e9nie'' (\u201cThe Rhymed Chronicle of Armenia Minor\u201d) of Vahram of Edessa records that he was the son of [[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I, lord of Armenian Cilicia]].<ref name='Cawley'/> His mother\u2019s name is not known.<ref name='Cawley'/>\n\nHe died a few months after his father\u2019s death in the course of a palace intrigue.<ref name='Runciman'/> Vahram of Edessa, the historian tells us that he was cast into prison and poisoned to death.<ref name='Ghazarian'>{{cite book | last = Ghazarian | first = Jacob G. | title = The Armenian Kingdom in Cilicia during the Crusades: The Integration of Cilician Armenians with the Latins (1080\u20131093)}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|''After the death of Thoros, his only son and heir vas cast into prison by some wicked people, who administered to him a poisonous drug, thus the principality came to [[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leon]], the brother of Thoros (\u2026).''|Vahram of Edessa: ''The Rhymed Chronicle of Armenia Minor''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/vahramschronicle00vahrrich|title=Chronicle|publisher=Internet Archive|work=Text Archive|date=2008-09-10|author=Vahram|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>}}\n\nOther historians (''e.g.'', Jacob G. Ghazarian, Vahan M. Kurkjian) suggest that Thoros I died without a male heir<ref name='Ghazarian'/> and was succeeded by Leon I.<ref name='Kurkjian'>{{cite web|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/27*.html|title=A History of Armenia|publisher=Bill Thayer|work=Website|date=2005-04-05|author=Vahan M. Kurkjian|accessdate=2009-07-19}}</ref>\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Sources ==\n*Ghazarian, Jacob G: ''The Armenian Kingdom in Cilicia during the Crusades: The Integration of Cilician Armenians with the Latins (1080\u20131393)''; RoutledgeCurzon (Taylor & Francis Group), 2000, Abingdon; {{ISBN|0-7007-1418-9}}\n*Runciman, Steven: ''A History of the Crusades \u2013 Volume II.: The Kingdom of Jerusalem and the Frankish East: 1100\u20131187''; Cambridge University Press, 1988, Cambridge; {{ISBN|0-521-06162-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Asia/Armenia/_Texts/KURARM/27*.html The Barony of Cilician Armenia] (Kurkjian's History of Armenia, Ch.&nbsp;27)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Rubenid dynasty|House of Roupen]]}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Thoros I, Prince of Armenia|Thoros I]]|title=[[Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia|Lord of Armenian Cilicia]]|years=1129/1130|after=[[Leo I, Prince of Armenia|Leo I]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Armenian kings}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Constantine Ii, Prince Of Armenia}}\n[[Category:1129 deaths]]\n[[Category:12th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Deaths by poisoning]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:12th-century Armenian people]]\n[[Category:Monarchs of the Rubenid dynasty]]\n", "name_user": "Hamilcar4532", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantine_II,_Prince_of_Armenia"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy D'Aquisto", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jimmy D'Aquisto\n| native_name        = James L. D'Aquisto\n| native_name_lang   = \n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1935|11|09}}  \n| birth_place   = [[Brooklyn]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1995|04|17|1935|04|17}}  \n| death_place   = [[California]] \n| nationality   = [[United States]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[luthier]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = [[Successor to John D'Angelico]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''James L. D'Aquisto''' ([[Brooklyn]], November 9, 1935 \u2013 [[California]], April 17, 1995) was an [[Italian Americans|Italian\u2013American]] [[luthier]] who concentrated on building and repairing [[archtop guitar]]s. He served as an apprentice to [[John D'Angelico]] beginning in 1952 and later developed his own distinctive style.<ref name=Acoustic>{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia |location= New York |publisher= Chartwell Books |date = 2011 |pages =41\u201344 |format= |isbn= 978-0-7858-3571-4}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJames D'Aquisto was born on November 9, 1935 into a musical Italian family. An aspiring jazz guitarist he visited luthier John D'Angelico's shop in 1951 which lead to him in 1952 becoming his apprentice.<ref name=Acoustic />\n\nAbout his routine, D'Aquisto said,\n\n\"I was making $35 a week. I was like the runner: I'd go to the stores, pick up the tuners, go get the tailpieces from downtown, take the necks to the engraver, all that. I cleaned the windows, swept the floors, everything\u2014we all did that. On Friday we put away the tools and cleaned the shop so when Monday came the place would be spotless.\"\n\n[[File:Jim Hall Trio - Something Special - March 1993 07.jpg|thumb|D'Aquisto guitar played by [[Jim Hall (musician)|Jim Hall]] (\"''[[Jim Hall (musician)#As leader|Something Special]]''\" recording in 1993)]]\nLater, he learned the \"rough work\" of the D'Angelico style.\n\nD'Angelico had a heart attack in 1959 and also parted ways with his long time employee Vincent \"Jimmy\" DiSerio. As a result he closed the business but soon reopened it after D'Aquisto who was unable to find work, convinced him to do so.<ref name=Acoustic /> After several more heart attacks and having also suffered from pneumonia John D'Angelico died on September 1, 1964 at the age of 59. Following D'Angelico's death the last ten of his guitars were finished by D'Aquisto.<ref name=Acoustic /><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url= http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-namm-2015-dangelico-acoustic-guitars-20150123-story.html|title= NAMM 2015: Revived D'Angelico guitar brand shows off new acoustics|date=January 23, 2015|accessdate= April 1, 2015}}</ref> D'Aquisto bought the business but a poor business decision lost him the right to the D\u2019Angelico name.<ref>{{cite web |last= Stern |first= Stephen |title= Jimmy D'Aquisto \u2013 Luthier Extraordinaire | publisher= Frontline magazine |date= Fall 1995 |url= http://www.masterseriesguitars.com/Jimmy%20article.pdf |accessdate= March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD'Aquisto then continued building guitars under his own name. In 1966 he moved to Huntington, Long Island, then to Farmingdale in 1973, and finally Greenport in 1980.<ref name=Acoustic />\n\nHe felt he would die at the same age as his mentor, and this did occur on April 17, 1995 when he was 59.<ref name=\"Barth2006\">{{cite book|last=Barth|first=Joe|title=Voices in Jazz Guitar: Great Performers Talk about Their Approach to Playing| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eMifMzrwYt0C&pg=PA241|year=2006|publisher=Mel Bay|isbn=978-0-7866-7679-8| pages=241\u2013}}</ref>\n\nD'Aquisto's name is on many guitar models from the [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] \"D'Aquisto Elite\" \"D'Aquisto Ultra\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archtop.com/ac_84fendasb.html|title=1984 Fender D'Aquisto Elite|accessdate=September 29, 2006}}</ref> and the [[Hagstr\u00f6m Jimmy]]. His blue \"Centura Deluxe\" was the inspiration for the book ''Blue Guitar''.<ref name=\"Blue\">{{cite book|last1=Vose|first1=Ken|title= Blue Guitar|url=https://archive.org/details/blueguitar0000vose|url-access=registration|date= 1998|publisher= Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco|isbn=0-8118-1912-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Angels\">{{cite book|last1=Schmidt|first1=Paul William|title=Acquired of the Angels: The Lives and Works of Master Guitar Makers John D'Angelico and James L. D'Aquisto|date=1998|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-57886-002-9|edition=2}}</ref> His guitars have sold for tens of thousands of dollars to over $500,000. One of his guitars was the first to be worth a million dollars.<ref name=\"Blue\" /><ref name=\"Guru\">{{cite news|last1=Nager|first1=Larry|title=To Guitarists He's a Guru|work=The Cincinnati Enquirer|date=October 11, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, D'Aquisto was inducted into the [[Long Island Music Hall of Fame]]. His tools and work bench, passed down to him from D'Angelico, were given to the [[National Music Museum]].\n\nIn 2011, guitars by D'Aquisto were included in the 'Guitar Heroes' exhibition at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://blog.metmuseum.org/guitarheroes/ |title= Guitar heroes: Legendary craftsmen from Italy to New York, February 9-July 4, 2011 |publisher= The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York |work= John D'Angelico | accessdate= December 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==D'Aquisto flat top guitars==\n\nD'Aquisto flat top guitars are a group of sixteen guitars<ref name=\"20thCet\">{{cite magazine| last1=Ilowite|first1=P.G.| title=D'Aquisto Flat Tops|magazine=20th Century Guitar |date=1994 |pages=44\u201345, 75 }}</ref> made by D'Aquisto.\n\nHe made sixteen flat top guitars from 1973 to 1984.<ref name=20thCet /> He made two types, a grand auditorium and a dreadnought.<ref name=tsumura>Tsumura A, Guitars The Tsumura Collection. Kodansha International LTD. D'Aquisto Serial Numbers. 1987, 192.</ref> He believed the large oval sound hole produced greater projection than the typical round sound hole.<ref name=olsen>Olsen T, Luthier The D'Aquisto Foundation Help complete the D'Aquisto exhibit at the National Music Museum. Guitar Player. 1978.</ref>\n\nHe numbered his guitars from 101 to 116.<ref name=tsumura /> Number 101 was a non-cutaway auditorium as well as number 111, which he made for Laurie Veneziano and [[Janis Ian]]. Numbers 102 to 110 were his dreadnoughts. From 112 to 115, are some of his most beautiful auditorium guitars and the only flat tops he made with a cutaway. Each is a radiant blond color. He used European spruce tops and European maple back and sides for all his flat tops. Ebony for the fret board, bridge, bridge pins, and headstock overlay. D'Aquisto also made a few nylon-string flat top guitars.\n\n==See also==\n* [[John D'Angelico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.usd.edu/smm/Tours/LillibridgeGallery/DDGWorkshop.html National Music Museum exhibit and history]\n* [http://www.limusichalloffame.org Long Island Hall of Fame]\n* [http://microflexguitarstrings.com/ D'Aquisto Foundation]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Aquisto, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Luthiers]]\n[[Category:Guitar makers]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jimmy D'Aquisto\n| native_name        = James L. D'Aquisto\n| native_name_lang   = \n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1935|11|09}}  \n| birth_place   = [[Brooklyn]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1995|04|17|1935|04|17}}  \n| death_place   = [[California]] \n| nationality   = [[United States]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[luthier]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = [[Successor to John D'Angelico]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''James L. D'Aquisto''' ([[Brooklyn]], November 9, 1935 \u2013 [[California]], April 17, 1995) was an [[Italian Americans|Italian\u2013American]] [[luthier]] who concentrated on building and repairing [[Archtop guitar|archtop guitars]]. He served as an apprentice to [[John D'Angelico]] beginning in 1952 and later developed his own distinctive style.<ref name=Acoustic>{{cite book |last= |first= |title= Acoustic Guitars: The Illustrated Encyclopedia |location= New York |publisher= Chartwell Books |date = 2011 |pages =41\u201344 |format= |isbn= 978-0-7858-3571-4}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJames D'Aquisto was born on November 9, 1935 into a musical Italian family. An aspiring jazz guitarist he visited luthier John D'Angelico's shop in 1951 which lead to him in 1952 becoming his apprentice.<ref name=Acoustic />\n\nAbout his routine, D'Aquisto said, \n\n\"I was making $35 a week. I was like the runner: I'd go to the stores, pick up the tuners, go get the tailpieces from downtown, take the necks to the engraver, all that. I cleaned the windows, swept the floors, everything\u2014we all did that. On Friday we put away the tools and cleaned the shop so when Monday came the place would be spotless.\" \n\n[[File:Jim Hall Trio - Something Special - March 1993 07.jpg|thumb|D'Aquisto guitar played by [[Jim Hall (musician)|Jim Hall]] (\"''[[Jim Hall (musician)#As leader|Something Special]]''\" recording in 1993)]]\nLater, he learned the \"rough work\" of the D'Angelico style. \n\nD'Angelico had a heart attack in 1959 and also parted ways with his long time employee Vincent \"Jimmy\" DiSerio. As a result he closed the business but soon reopened it after D'Aquisto who was unable to find work, convinced him to do so.<ref name=Acoustic /> After several more heart attacks and having also suffered from pneumonia John D'Angelico died on September 1, 1964 at the age of 59. Following D'Angelico's death the last ten of his guitars were finished by D'Aquisto.<ref name=Acoustic /><ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url= http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/envelope/cotown/la-et-ct-namm-2015-dangelico-acoustic-guitars-20150123-story.html|title= NAMM 2015: Revived D'Angelico guitar brand shows off new acoustics|date=January 23, 2015|accessdate= April 1, 2015}}</ref> D'Aquisto bought the business but a poor business decision lost him the right to the D\u2019Angelico name.<ref>{{cite web |last= Stern |first= Stephen |title= Jimmy D'Aquisto \u2013 Luthier Extraordinaire | publisher= Frontline magazine |date= Fall 1995 |url= http://www.masterseriesguitars.com/Jimmy%20article.pdf |accessdate= March 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nD'Aquisto then continued building guitars under his own name. In 1966 he moved to Huntington, Long Island, then to Farmingdale in 1973, and finally Greenport in 1980.<ref name=Acoustic /> \n\nHe felt he would die at the same age as his mentor, and this did occur on April 17, 1995 when he was 59.<ref name=\"Barth2006\">{{cite book|last=Barth|first=Joe|title=Voices in Jazz Guitar: Great Performers Talk about Their Approach to Playing| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eMifMzrwYt0C&pg=PA241|year=2006|publisher=Mel Bay|isbn=978-0-7866-7679-8| pages=241\u2013}}</ref>\n\nD'Aquisto's name is on many guitar models from the [[Fender Musical Instruments Corporation|Fender]] \"D'Aquisto Elite\" \"D'Aquisto Ultra\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archtop.com/ac_84fendasb.html|title=1984 Fender D'Aquisto Elite|accessdate=September 29, 2006}}</ref> and the [[Hagstr\u00f6m Jimmy]]. His blue \"Centura Deluxe\" was the inspiration for the book ''Blue Guitar''.<ref name=\"Blue\">{{cite book|last1=Vose|first1=Ken|title= Blue Guitar|url=https://archive.org/details/blueguitar0000vose|url-access=registration|date= 1998|publisher= Chronicle Books|location=San Francisco|isbn=0-8118-1912-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Angels\">{{cite book|last1=Schmidt|first1=Paul William|title=Acquired of the Angels: The Lives and Works of Master Guitar Makers John D'Angelico and James L. D'Aquisto|date=1998|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-1-57886-002-9|edition=2}}</ref> His guitars have sold for tens of thousands of dollars to over $500,000. One of his guitars was the first to be worth a million dollars.<ref name=\"Blue\" /><ref name=\"Guru\">{{cite news|last1=Nager|first1=Larry|title=To Guitarists He's a Guru|work=The Cincinnati Enquirer|date=October 11, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, D'Aquisto was inducted into the [[Long Island Music Hall of Fame]]. His tools and work bench, passed down to him from D'Angelico, were given to the [[National Music Museum]].\n\nIn 2011, guitars by D'Aquisto were included in the 'Guitar Heroes' exhibition at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://blog.metmuseum.org/guitarheroes/ |title= Guitar heroes: Legendary craftsmen from Italy to New York, February 9-July 4, 2011 |publisher= The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York |work= John D'Angelico | accessdate= December 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==D'Aquisto flat top guitars==\n\nD'Aquisto flat top guitars are a group of sixteen guitars<ref name=\"20thCet\">{{cite magazine| last1=Ilowite|first1=P.G.| title=D'Aquisto Flat Tops|magazine=20th Century Guitar |date=1994 |pages=44\u201345, 75 }}</ref> made by D'Aquisto.\n\nHe made sixteen flat top guitars from 1973 to 1984.<ref name=20thCet /> He made two types, a grand auditorium and a dreadnought.<ref name=tsumura>Tsumura A, Guitars The Tsumura Collection. Kodansha International LTD. D'Aquisto Serial Numbers. 1987, 192.</ref> He believed the large oval sound hole produced greater projection than the typical round sound hole.<ref name=olsen>Olsen T, Luthier The D'Aquisto Foundation Help complete the D'Aquisto exhibit at the National Music Museum. Guitar Player. 1978.</ref> \n\nHe numbered his guitars from 101 to 116.<ref name=tsumura /> Number 101 was a non-cutaway auditorium as well as number 111, which he made for Laurie Veneziano and [[Janis Ian]]. Numbers 102 to 110 were his dreadnoughts. From 112 to 115, are some of his most beautiful auditorium guitars and the only flat tops he made with a cutaway. Each is a radiant blond color. He used European spruce tops and European maple back and sides for all his flat tops. Ebony for the fret board, bridge, bridge pins, and headstock overlay. D'Aquisto also made a few nylon-string flat top guitars.\n\n==See also==\n* [[John D'Angelico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.usd.edu/smm/Tours/LillibridgeGallery/DDGWorkshop.html National Music Museum exhibit and history]\n* [http://www.limusichalloffame.org Long Island Hall of Fame]\n* [http://microflexguitarstrings.com/ D'Aquisto Foundation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:D'Aquisto, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Luthiers]]\n[[Category:Guitar makers]]\n[[Category:American jazz guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_D%27Aquisto"}
{"title_page": "Katherine Johnson", "text_new": "{{For|others with the same or similar name|Katharine Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Katherine Johnson\n| image        = Katherine Johnson 1983.jpg\n| alt          = Katherine Johnson\n| caption      = Katherine Johnson in 1983\n| birth_name   = Creola Katherine Coleman\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1918|08|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|02|24|1918|08|26}}\n| death_place  = [[Newport News, Virginia]], U.S.\n| other_names  = Katherine Goble\n| alma_mater   = [[West Virginia State College]]\n| occupation   = [[Mathematician]]\n| employer     = [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics|NACA]], [[NASA]] 1953\u20131988\n| known_for    = Calculating trajectories for NASA missions\n| spouse       = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|James Goble|1939|1956|end=died}}|{{marriage|Jim Johnson|1959|2019|end=died}}}}\n| children     = 3\n| awards       = {{unbulleted list|[[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] (2015)|[[Silver Snoopy award]] (2016)|[[NASA Group Achievement Award]] (2016)|[[Congressional Gold Medal]] (2019)}}\n}}\n'''Katherine Johnson''' (August 26, 1918 \u2013 February 24, 2020) was an American mathematician whose calculations of [[orbital mechanics]] as a [[NASA]] employee were critical to the success of the first and subsequent U.S. crewed spaceflights.<ref name=\"Smith\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count|title = Katherine Johnson: The Girl Who Loved to Count|date = November 24, 2015|access-date = February 12, 2016|publisher = [[NASA]]|last = Smith|first = Yvette Hi I did ytttt I did a great one and it is so cute I love the cute ones on the way home I am so anding program and the start of the Space Shuttle program, as they did to those first steps on the country's journey into space.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190212013908/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count/|archive-date = February 12, 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> During her 35-year career at NASA and its [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics|predecessor]], she earned a reputation for mastering complex manual calculations and helped pioneer the use of computers to perform the tasks. The space agency noted her \"historical role as one of the first [[African-American]] women to work as a NASA scientist\".<ref name=hftmf /><!--\"African American\" should be in the lead, per Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Biographies#Context; it is a part of her WP:Notability.-->\n\nJohnson's work included calculating trajectories, [[launch window]]s, and emergency return paths for [[Project Mercury]] spaceflights, including those for astronauts [[Alan Shepard]], the first American in space, and [[John Glenn]], the first American in orbit, and rendezvous paths for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] and [[Apollo command module|command module]] on flights to the Moon. Her calculations were also essential to  the beginning of the [[Space Shuttle program]], and she worked on plans for [[Exploration of Mars|a mission to Mars]].\n\nIn 2015, President [[Barack Obama]] awarded Johnson the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]. In 2016, she was presented the [[Silver Snoopy award|Silver Snoopy Award]] by NASA astronaut [[Leland D. Melvin]] and a [[NASA Group Achievement Award]]. She was portrayed by [[Taraji P. Henson]] as a lead character in the 2016 film ''[[Hidden Figures]]''. In 2019, Johnson was awarded the [[Congressional Gold Medal]].\n\n== Early life and education==\nJohnson was born as Creola Katherine Coleman on August 26, 1918, in [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]], to Joylette and Joshua Coleman.<ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.visionaryproject.org/johnsonkatherine/|title = Katherine Johnson&nbsp;\u2013 Oral History|date = |access-date = February 12, 2016|website = National Visionary Leadership Project|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160223212717/http://www.visionaryproject.org/johnsonkatherine/|archive-date = February 23, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> She was the youngest of four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shetterly|first1=Margot Lee|title=The Woman the Mercury Astronauts Couldn't Do Without|url=http://nautil.us/issue/43/Heroes/the-woman-the-mercury-astronauts-couldnt-do-without|access-date=December 8, 2016|work=[[Nautilus (science magazine)|Nautilus]]|date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204125744/http://nautil.us/issue/43/heroes/the-woman-the-mercury-astronauts-couldnt-do-without|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her mother was a teacher and her father was a lumberman, farmer, and handyman, and worked at the [[The Greenbrier|Greenbrier Hotel]].<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"Gutman\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news/20151226/west-virginian-of-the-year-katherine-g-johnson|title = West Virginian of the Year: Katherine G. Johnson|date = December 26, 2015|access-date = February 12, 2016|website = [[Charleston Gazette-Mail]]|last = Gutman|first = David|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170827135853/http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news/20151226/west-virginian-of-the-year-katherine-g-johnson|archive-date = August 27, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nColeman showed strong mathematical abilities from an early age. Because [[Greenbrier County, West Virginia|Greenbrier County]] did not offer public schooling for African-American students past the eighth grade, the Colemans arranged for their children to attend high school in [[Institute, West Virginia]]. This school was on the campus of [[West Virginia State University|West Virginia State College]] (WVSC).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography |title=From Hidden to Modern Figures \u2013 Katherine Johnson Biography |last=Shetterly |first=Margot Lee |date=December 1, 2016 |website=NASA |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908094437/https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson was enrolled when she was ten years old.<ref name=\"NASA feature\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count |title=Katherine Johnson: The Girl Who Loved to Count |editor=Yvette Smith<!--Not stated--> |date=November 24, 2015 |website=NASA |access-date=March 1, 2017 |quote=Fascinated by numbers and smart to boot, for by the time she was 10 years old, she was a high school freshman&nbsp;\u2013 a truly amazing feat in an era when school for African-Americans normally stopped at eighth grade for those who could indulge in that luxury. Katherine skipped several grades to graduate from high school at 14 and from college at 18. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228205427/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count/ |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The family split their time between Institute during the school year and White Sulphur Springs in the summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacegrant.org/programs/service-award/johnson/|title=Johnson|website=National Space Grant Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226170728/https://spacegrant.org/programs/service-award/johnson/|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = left | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?462474-2/national-history-day-katherine-johnson-quiet-triumph-white-mans-world Interview with West Virginia State University President Anthony Jenkins on Johnson's studies and career, October 21, 2019], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nAfter graduating from high school at 14, Johnson enrolled at West Virginia State, a [[historically black college]].<ref name=\"NASA bio\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography|title=Katherine Johnson Biography|last=Loff|first=Sarah|date=November 22, 2016|newspaper=NASA|language=en|access-date=February 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908094437/https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography/|archive-date=September 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As a student, she took every math course offered by the college. Multiple professors mentored her, including the chemist and mathematician [[Angie Turner King]], who had mentored Coleman throughout high school, and [[W. W. Schieffelin Claytor]], the third African-American to receive a Ph.D. in mathematics. Claytor added new mathematics courses just for Johnson.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shetterly|first=Margot Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/hiddenfiguresame0000shet|url-access=registration|title=Hidden Figures: The American Dream and the Untold Story of the Black Women Mathematicians Who Helped Win the Space Race|date=2016-09-06|publisher=William Morrow|isbn=978-0-06-236361-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hiddenfiguresame0000shet/page/24 24]|language=en}}</ref> She graduated ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]'' in 1937, with degrees in mathematics and French, at age 18.<ref name=\"WVGazetteMail\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wvgazettemail.com/article/20151116/GZ01/151119605/1101|title=WV native, NASA mathematician to receive Presidential Medal of Freedom|last=Gutman|first=David|date=November 16, 2015|website=WV Gazette Mail: Charleston Gazette-Mail|access-date=February 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216001223/http://www.wvgazettemail.com/article/20151116/GZ01/151119605/1101|archive-date=February 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NASA feature\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |title=Katherine G. Johnson \u2013 Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2015 |website=West Virginia University |publisher=WVU |access-date=March 1, 2017 |quote=Katherine Johnson graduated from high school at age 14 and from college at 18. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302025622/http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Johnson was a member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtheyard.com/akas/alpha-kappa-alpha-legos/|title=These Two Famous Alpha Kappa Alpha Members Are Getting Their Own Legos|date=August 15, 2017|website=Watch The Yard|language=en-US|access-date=February 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226171037/https://www.watchtheyard.com/akas/alpha-kappa-alpha-legos/|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She took on a teaching job at a black public school in [[Marion, Virginia]].<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /><ref>{{cite news |work=SWVA Today |last=Porter-Nichols |first=Stephanie |date=January 24, 2017 |title=Council honors one-time Marion teacher Katherine Johnson of 'Hidden Figures' |url=http://www.swvatoday.com/news/smyth_county/article_35c83f32-df64-11e6-a8e6-bfcf3ba856af.html |access-date=October 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014092136/https://www.swvatoday.com/news/smyth_county/article_35c83f32-df64-11e6-a8e6-bfcf3ba856af.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1939, after marrying her first husband, James Goble, she left her teaching job and enrolled in a graduate math program. She quit after one year after becoming pregnant and choosing to focus on her family.<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> She was the first African-American woman to attend graduate school at [[West Virginia University]] in [[Morgantown, West Virginia]]. Through WVSC's president, Dr. John W. Davis, she became one of three African-American students,<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> and the only woman, selected to integrate the graduate school after the 1938 United States Supreme Court ruling ''[[Missouri ex rel. Gaines v. Canada]]''. The court ruled that states that provided public higher education to white students also had to provide it to black students, to be satisfied either by establishing black colleges and universities or by admitting black students to previously white-only universities.<ref name=\"Gutman\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/305/337/case.html|title = Missouri ex rel. Gaines v. Canada 305 U.S. 337 (1938)|date = 1938|access-date = February 12, 2016|website = Justia US Supreme Court|last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160217034207/https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/305/337/case.html|archive-date = February 17, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Katherine Johnson at NASA, in 1966.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of Johnson sitting at a desk | Johnson working as a \"computer\" at NASA in 1966]]\nJohnson decided on a career as a research mathematician, although this was a difficult field for African Americans and women to enter. The first jobs she found were in teaching. At a family gathering in 1952, a relative mentioned that the [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]] (NACA) was hiring mathematicians.<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> At the [[Langley Research Center|Langley Memorial Aeronautical Laboratory]], based in [[Hampton, Virginia|Hampton]], Virginia, near [[Langley Field]], NACA hired African-American mathematicians as well as whites for their Guidance and Navigation Department. Johnson accepted a job offer from the agency in June 1953.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />\n\nAccording to an oral history archived by the National Visionary Leadership Project:\n\n<blockquote>At first she [Johnson] worked in a pool of women performing math calculations. Katherine has referred to the women in the pool as virtual \"computers who wore skirts\". Their main job was to read the data from the black boxes of planes and carry out other precise mathematical tasks. Then one day, Katherine (and a colleague) were temporarily assigned to help the all-male flight research team. Katherine's knowledge of [[analytic geometry]] helped make quick allies of male bosses and colleagues to the extent that, \"they forgot to return me to the pool\".  While the racial and gender barriers were always there, Katherine says she ignored them. Katherine was assertive, asking to be included in editorial meetings (where no women had gone before). She simply told people she had done the work and that she belonged.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />\n</blockquote>\n\nFrom 1953 to 1958, Johnson worked as a [[Human computer|computer]],<ref name=\"Jim Hodges\">{{cite web |title=She Was a Computer When Computers Wore Skirts |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/rn_kjohnson.html |first=Jim |last=Hodges |publisher=NASA |work=Langley Research Center |date=August 26, 2008 |access-date=December 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114124545/http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/rn_kjohnson.html |archive-date=November 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> analyzing topics such as gust alleviation for aircraft. Originally assigned to the [[West Area Computers]] section supervised by mathematician [[Dorothy Vaughan]], Johnson was reassigned to the Guidance and Control Division of Langley's Flight Research Division. It was staffed by white male engineers.<ref name=\"buckley\" /> In keeping with state racial segregation laws, and federal workplace segregation introduced under President [[Woodrow Wilson]] in the early 20th&nbsp;century, Johnson and the other African-American women in the computing pool were required to work, eat, and use restrooms that were separate from those of their white peers. Their office was labeled as \"Colored Computers\". In an interview with [[WHRO-TV]], Johnson stated that she \"didn't feel the segregation at NASA, because everybody there was doing research. You had a mission and you worked on it, and it was important to you to do your job&nbsp;... and play bridge at lunch.\" She added: \"I didn't feel any segregation. I knew it was there, but I didn't feel it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyvshollywood.com/video/katherine-johnson-interview-nasa/ |title=Katherine Johnson Interview: NASA's Human Computer |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2016 |website=HistoryvsHollywood.com |publisher=CTF Media |access-date=March 2, 2017 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303050429/http://www.historyvshollywood.com/video/katherine-johnson-interview-nasa/ |archive-date=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNACA disbanded the colored computing pool in 1958 when the agency was superseded by NASA, which adopted digital computers. Although the installation was desegregated,<ref name=\"buckley\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/books/on-being-black-female-math-whizzes-during-the-space-race.html|title=On Being a Black Female Math Whiz During the Space Race|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=September 6, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 6, 2016|page=C1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906030123/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/books/on-being-black-female-math-whizzes-during-the-space-race.html|archive-date=September 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> forms of discrimination were still pervasive. Johnson recalled that era:\n\n<blockquote>We needed to be assertive as women in those days&nbsp;\u2013 assertive and aggressive&nbsp;\u2013 and the degree to which we had to be that way depended on where you were. I had to be. In the early days of NASA women were not allowed to put their names on the reports&nbsp;\u2013 no woman in my division had had her name on a report. I was working with Ted Skopinski and he wanted to leave and go to Houston&nbsp;... but Henry Pearson, our supervisor&nbsp;\u2013 he was not a fan of women&nbsp;\u2013 kept pushing him to finish the report we were working on. Finally, Ted told him, \"Katherine should finish the report, she's done most of the work anyway.\" So Ted left Pearson with no choice; I finished the report and my name went on it, and that was the first time a woman in our division had her name on something.<ref name=\"St Andrews\">Quoted at {{cite web |url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Johnson_Katherine.html |title=Katherine Coleman Goble Johnson |author=J. J. O'Connor |author2=E. F. Robertson |date=February 2020 |website=School of Mathematics & Statistics University of St Andrews, UK |publisher=School of Mathematics & Statistics University of St Andrews, UK |access-date=February 26, 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622080756/http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Johnson_Katherine.html |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live }} This quotation is an excerpt from W. Warren, \"Katherine Coleman Goble Johnson\", in ''Black Women Scientists in the United States'' (Indiana University Press, 1999), pp. 140\u2013147.</ref></blockquote>\n\nFrom 1958 until her retirement in 1986, Johnson worked as an aerospace technologist, moving during her career to the Spacecraft Controls Branch. She calculated the trajectory for the May&nbsp;5, 1961 space flight of [[Alan Shepard]], the first American in space.<ref name=\"Smith\" /> She also calculated the [[launch window]] for his 1961 [[Project Mercury|Mercury mission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/71576/black-female-mathematicians-who-sent-astronauts-space|title=The Black Female Mathematicians Who Sent Astronauts to Space|last=Whitney|first=A. K.|access-date=September 10, 2016|date=February 1, 2016<!--|date=2015-->|website=[[Mental Floss]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705103936/http://mentalfloss.com/article/71576/black-female-mathematicians-who-sent-astronauts-space|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She plotted backup [[navigation]] [[chart]]s for [[astronaut]]s in case of electronic failures.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /> When NASA used electronic computers for the first time to calculate [[John Glenn]]'s orbit around [[Earth]], officials called on Johnson to verify the computer's numbers; Glenn had asked for her specifically and had refused to fly unless Johnson verified the calculations.<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"MakersBio\">{{cite web|title=Makers Profile: Katherine G. Johnson|url=http://www.makers.com/katherine-g-johnson|website=Makers|access-date=May 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105162815/https://www.makers.com/katherine-g-johnson|archive-date=January 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sloat\">{{Cite web|last=Sloat|first=Sarah|title='Hidden Figures' Gives NASA Mathematicians Long Overdue Movie|publisher=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse.com]]|date=August 15, 2016|access-date =January 15, 2017|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/19694-5-facts-about-katherine-johnson-hidden-figure}}</ref> [[FYI (U.S. TV channel)|Biography.com]] states these were \"far more difficult calculations, to account for the gravitational pulls of celestial bodies\".<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/katherine-g-johnson-101016|title=Katherine Johnson Biography|date=October 10, 2016|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=A&E Television Networks|access-date=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831162903/https://www.biography.com/people/katherine-g-johnson-101016|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Author [[Margot Lee Shetterly]] stated, \"So the astronaut who became a hero, looked to this black woman in the still-segregated South at the time as one of the key parts of making sure his mission would be a success.\" She added that, in a time where computing was \"women's work\" and engineering was left to men, \"it really does have to do with us over the course of time sort of not valuing that work that was done by women, however necessary, as much as we might. And it has taken history to get a perspective on that.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/25/495179824/hidden-figures-how-black-women-did-the-math-that-put-men-on-the-moon |title='Hidden Figures': How Black Women Did The Math That Put Men on the Moon |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 25, 2016 |work=[[All Things Considered]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301062054/http://www.npr.org/2016/09/25/495179824/hidden-figures-how-black-women-did-the-math-that-put-men-on-the-moon |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJohnson later worked directly with digital [[computer]]s. Her ability and reputation for accuracy helped to establish confidence in the new technology.<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> In 1961, her work helped to ensure that Alan Shepard's ''[[Freedom 7]]'' Mercury capsule would be found quickly after landing, using the accurate trajectory that had been established.<ref name=businside />\n\n[[File:Katherine Johnson in 2008.jpg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated in a chair looking to her right | Johnson in 2008]]\nShe also helped to calculate the trajectory for the 1969 [[Apollo&nbsp;11]] flight to the Moon.<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"biography.com\" /> During the Moon landing, Johnson was at a meeting in the [[Pocono Mountains]]. She and a few others crowded around a small [[television]] screen watching the first steps on the Moon. In 1970, Johnson worked on the [[Apollo&nbsp;13]] Moon mission. When the mission was aborted, her work on backup procedures and charts helped set a safe path for the crew's return to Earth,<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> creating a one-star observation system that would allow astronauts to determine their location with accuracy. In a 2010 interview, Johnson recalled, \"Everybody was concerned about them getting there. We were concerned about them getting back.\"<ref name=businside>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/katherine-johnson-hidden-figures-nasa-human-computers-2016-8/#johnsons-time-as-a-teacher-hasnt-ever-really-ended-she-strongly-believes-people-need-to-learn-how-to-learn-i-teach-you-what-the-problem-is-how-to-attack-it--if-you-attack-it-properly-youll-get-the-answer-she-said-in-a-2011-interview-28 |title=The unbelievable life of the forgotten genius who turned Americans' space dreams into reality |last=Bartels |first=Meghan |date=August 22, 2016 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=Business Insider Inc. |access-date=March 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303122553/http://www.businessinsider.com/katherine-johnson-hidden-figures-nasa-human-computers-2016-8/#johnsons-time-as-a-teacher-hasnt-ever-really-ended-she-strongly-believes-people-need-to-learn-how-to-learn-i-teach-you-what-the-problem-is-how-to-attack-it--if-you-attack-it-properly-youll-get-the-answer-she-said-in-a-2011-interview-28 |archive-date=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later in her career, Johnson worked on the [[Space Shuttle program]], the Earth Resources Satellite,<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"biography.com\" /> and on plans for a [[Exploration of Mars|mission to Mars]].<ref name=\"Guglielmi\">{{Cite news|last=Guglielmi|first=Jodi|title=Katherine Johnson, Legendary Mathematician and Inspiration for the Upcoming Film Hidden Figures, Turns 98|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=August 26, 2016|access-date=January 15, 2017|url=http://people.com/movies/katherine-johnson-turns-98/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116183513/http://people.com/movies/katherine-johnson-turns-98/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJohnson spent her later years encouraging students to enter the fields of [[science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2020/02/mathematics-pioneer-katherine-johnson-portrayed-in-hidden-figures-dies-at-101.html|title=Mathematics pioneer Katherine Johnson, portrayed in 'Hidden Figures,' dies at 101|agency=Associated Press|date=February 24, 2020|website=[[The Oregonian]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225171953/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2020/02/mathematics-pioneer-katherine-johnson-portrayed-in-hidden-figures-dies-at-101.html|archive-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn 1939, Katherine (then Coleman) married James Francis Goble. They had three daughters: Constance, Joylette, and Katherine. In 1953, she and James moved their family to [[Newport News, Virginia]], to pursue a new job opportunity. In 1956, James Goble died of an inoperable [[brain tumor]]. In 1959, Katherine Goble married James A. \"Jim\" Johnson, a [[United States Army]] officer and veteran of the [[Korean War]]; the pair were married for 60 years until his death in March 2019 at the age of 93.<ref name=\"St Andrews\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: James A. Johnson |url=https://www.ohsmithandsonfuneralhome.com/obituary/james-johnson |accessdate=February 24, 2020|publisher=O.H. Smith & Son Funeral Home}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/science/katherine-johnson-dead.html|title=Katherine Johnson Dies at 101; Mathematician Broke Barriers at NASA|first=Margalit|last=Fox|authorlink=Margalit Fox|date=February 25, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times|page=A1|access-date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224154106/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/science/katherine-johnson-dead.html|archive-date=February 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson, who had six grandchildren and 11 great-grandchildren, lived in [[Hampton, Virginia]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fountain|first=Nigel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/feb/24/katherine-johnson-obituary|title=Katherine Johnson obituary|date=February 24, 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226023231/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/feb/24/katherine-johnson-obituary|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She encouraged her grandchildren and students to pursue careers in science and technology.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/woen-in-stem|title=The Untold History of Women in Science and Technology: Katherine Johnson |website=The White House |access-date=October 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/node/311241\n|archivedate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe was a member of Carver Memorial [[Presbyterian Church (USA)|Presbyterian Church]] for 50 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pres-outlook.org/2017/01/real-life-hidden-figures-mathematician-longtime-presbyterian/|title=Real life 'Hidden Figures' mathematician is longtime Presbyterian|website=The Presbyterian Outlook|first=Gregg|last=Brekke|date=January 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224164531/https://pres-outlook.org/2017/01/real-life-hidden-figures-mathematician-longtime-presbyterian/|archivedate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nJohnson died at a retirement home in Newport News on February 24, 2020, at age 101.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.wtkr.com/news/local-hero-nasa-mathematician-katherine-johnson-dies-at-101|title = Local hero, NASA mathematician Katherine Johnson dies at 101|work = [[WTKR]]|date = February 24, 2020|accessdate = February 24, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200224193445/https://www.wtkr.com/news/local-hero-nasa-mathematician-katherine-johnson-dies-at-101|archive-date = February 24, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\"/> Following her death, [[Jim Bridenstine]], NASA's administrator, described her as \"an American hero\" and stated that \"her pioneering legacy will never be forgotten.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet||first=Jim|last=Bridenstine|author-link=Jim Bridenstine|date=February 24, 2020|user=JimBridenstine|number=1231946829962584065|title=Our @NASA family is sad to learn the news that Katherine Johnson passed away this morning at 101 years old. She was an American hero and her pioneering legacy will never be forgotten. https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honors==\n[[File:Katherine Johnson medal.jpeg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated wearing her Presidential Medal of Freedom | The [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] was awarded to Johnson in 2015.]]\n\nJohnson co-authored 26 scientific papers.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"NASAHistory\">{{cite web|title=Human computers: Katherine G. Johnson|url=http://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/historic/Katherine_Johnson|work=NASA Cultural Resources (CRGIS)|access-date=August 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719141646/http://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/historic/Katherine_Johnson|archive-date=July 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Her social influence as a pioneer in [[Outline of space science|space science]] and [[computing]] is demonstrated by the [[honour|honors]] she received and her status as a [[role model]] for a life in science.<ref name=\"NASAHistory\" /><ref name=\"SCIENCEYEAR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scienceyear.com/text_only/outthere/black_history/johnson.html|title=Black history... Katherine G Johnson (1918 \u2013 retired)\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021221512/http://www.scienceyear.com/text_only/outthere/black_history/johnson.html |archive-date=October 21, 2006|url-status=dead|website=Planet Science|publisher=NESTA}}</ref><ref name=\"THINKQUEST\">{{cite web|url=http://library.thinkquest.org/2907/katherine_johnson.html|title=Katherine G. Johnson: Physicist, Space Scientist, Mathematician|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304132115/http://library.thinkquest.org/2907/katherine_johnson.html |archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=dead|website=ThinkQuest Library|publisher=Oracle}}</ref> Johnson was named West Virginia State College Outstanding Alumnus of the Year in 1999. President [[Barack Obama]] presented her with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], one of 17 Americans so honored on November&nbsp;24, 2015. She was cited as a pioneering example of African-American women in STEM.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33958124/daily_press/|title=Peninsula Officials: Regions Disaster-Ready|newspaper=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|location=Newport News, Virginia|date=November 17, 2015|page=A1|via=Newspapers.com|last1=Ketchum|first1=Sarah J.|access-date=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717170608/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33958124/daily_press/|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> President Obama said at the time, \"Katherine G. Johnson refused to be limited by society's expectations of her gender and race while expanding the boundaries of humanity's reach.\"<ref name=\"NYT\" /> NASA noted her \"historical role as one of the first [[African-American]] women to work as a NASA scientist.\"<ref name=\"hftmf\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WcEDJOWka58|title=Hidden Figures To Modern Figures: Students See SLS Rocket at Michoud|last=|first=|date=November 24, 2016|website=YouTube|publisher=Marshall Space Flight Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn May&nbsp;5, 2016, a new {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building was named the \"Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility\" and formally dedicated at the agency's Langley Research Center in Hampton, Virginia. The facility officially opened its doors on September&nbsp;22, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smTcsodvEqM|title=Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility Ribbon Cutting|date=September 22, 2017|work=NASA Langley Research Center|via=YouTube|access-date=September 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003233559/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smTcsodvEqM|archive-date=October 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson attended this event, which also marked the 55th anniversary of astronaut Alan Shepard's historic rocket launch and splashdown, a success Johnson helped achieve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-dedicates-facility-to-mathematician-presidential-medal-winner|title=NASA Dedicates Facility to Mathematician, Presidential Medal Winner|first=Karen|last=Northon|date=April 28, 2016|access-date=August 1, 2016|id=M16-046|publisher=NASA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730102759/http://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-dedicates-facility-to-mathematician-presidential-medal-winner/|archive-date=July 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At the ceremony, deputy director Lewin said this about Johnson: \"Millions of people around the world watched Shepard's flight, but what they didn't know at the time was that the calculations that got him into space and safely home were done by today's guest of honor, Katherine Johnson\". During the event, Johnson also received a [[Silver Snoopy]] award; often called the astronaut's award, NASA stated it is given to those \"who have made outstanding contributions to flight safety and mission success\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center |title=Katherine Johnson at NASA Langley Research Center |date=August 26, 2016 |website=NASA History |publisher=[[NASA]] |access-date=March 1, 2017 |last1=Loff |first1=Sarah |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302193912/https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center/ |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJohnson was included on the [[BBC]]'s list of [[100 Women (BBC)|100 Women]] of influence worldwide in 2016.<ref name=\"list2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-38012048|title=BBC 100 Women 2016: Who is on the list?|publisher=BBC News|date=November 21, 2016|access-date=November 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223235036/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-38012048|archive-date=December 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2016 video NASA stated, \"Her calculations proved as critical to the success of the Apollo Moon landing program and the start of the Space Shuttle program, as they did to those first steps on the country's journey into space.\"<ref name=\"Smith\" />\n{{external media| float = right| width=230px | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?414833-1/margot-lee-shetterly-discusses-hidden-figures Presentation by Margot Lee Shetterly on ''Hidden Figures'' at the Hampton History Museum, September 8, 2016], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?432540-28/hidden-figures Discussion with Shetterly on ''Hidden Figures'' at the National Book Festival, September 2, 2017], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nThe highly acclaimed film ''[[Hidden Figures]]'', released in December 2016, was based on the [[Hidden Figures (book)|non-fiction book]] of the same title by Margot Lee Shetterly, which was published earlier that year. It follows Johnson and other female African-American mathematicians ([[Mary Jackson (engineer)|Mary Jackson]] and Dorothy Vaughan) who worked at NASA. [[Taraji P. Henson]] plays Johnson in the film.<ref name=\"Sloat\" /> Appearing alongside Henson at the [[89th Academy Awards]], Johnson received a standing ovation from the audience.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/real-life-subject-hidden-figures-receives-standing-ovation/story?id=45755913 |title=Katherine Johnson, real-life subject of 'Hidden Figures' receives standing ovation at Oscars |first=Taylor |last=Maple |date=February 26, 2017 |access-date=February 26, 2017 |website=[[ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227050544/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/real-life-subject-hidden-figures-receives-standing-ovation/story?id=45755913 |archive-date=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an earlier interview, Johnson offered the following comment about the movie: \"It was well-done. The three leading ladies did an excellent job portraying us.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Amina |date=February 26, 2017 |title=Q&A: Our interview with Katherine G. Johnson, the real-life mathematician who inspired 'Hidden Figures' |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-oscars-2017-89th-academy-awards-q-a-our-interview-with-katherine-g-1488161846-htmlstory.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=Los Angeles |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301201003/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-oscars-2017-89th-academy-awards-q-a-our-interview-with-katherine-g-1488161846-htmlstory.html |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a 2016 episode of the [[NBC]] series ''[[Timeless (TV series)|Timeless]],'' titled \"Space Race\", the mathematician is portrayed by Nadine Ellis.<ref>{{cite web |first=Allison |last=Shoemaker |title=Timeless needs to ditch the formula |url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/timeless-needs-ditch-formula-246556 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201123306/http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/timeless-needs-ditch-formula-246556 |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nScience writer [[Maia Weinstock]] developed a prototype [[Lego]] for Women of NASA in 2016 and included Johnson; she declined to have her likeness printed on the final product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/women-nasa-lego-prototype-joins-collection|title=\"Women of NASA\" LEGO Prototype Joins Collection|last1=Brady|first1=Hillary|date=August 27, 2018|publisher=[[Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009013147/https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/women-nasa-lego-prototype-joins-collection|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On May&nbsp;12, 2018, she was awarded an [[honorary doctorate]] by the [[College of William & Mary]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vagazette.com/news/va-vg-wm-commencement-20180516-story.html |title=William and Mary commencement sends graduates out on new adventure |first=Amelia |last=Heymann |work=[[The Virginia Gazette]] |date=May 12, 2018 |access-date=June 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613184433/http://www.vagazette.com/news/va-vg-wm-commencement-20180516-story.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2018, West Virginia State University established a STEM scholarship in honor of Johnson and erected a life-size statue of her on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wvstateu.edu/CampusNews/2018/May/West-Virginia-State-University-to-Honor-Katherine.aspx|title=West Virginia State University to Honor Katherine Johnson with Statue, Scholarship|publisher=WVSU|date=May 31, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613160530/http://www.wvstateu.edu/CampusNews/2018/May/West-Virginia-State-University-to-Honor-Katherine.aspx|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mattel]] announced a [[Barbie]] doll in Johnson's likeness with a NASA identity badge in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-katherine-johnson-barbie-20180306-story.html|title=Katherine Johnson to be included in Barbie 'Inspiring Women' series|last=Petrini|first=Andi|newspaper=Daily Press|access-date=September 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903013353/http://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-katherine-johnson-barbie-20180306-story.html|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Johnson was announced as one of the members of the inaugural class of ''[[Government Executive]]''{{'s}}  Government Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Tom|last1=Shoop|url=https://www.govexec.com/management/2019/08/inaugural-inductees-government-hall-fame-unveiled/159156/|title=Inaugural Inductees Into Government Hall of Fame Unveiled|website=[[Government Executive]]|accessdate=August 16, 2019|date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815155258/https://www.govexec.com/management/2019/08/inaugural-inductees-government-hall-fame-unveiled/159156/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katherine Johnson at the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility.jpg|thumb|alt= Johnson seated on a bench beside a sign in front of the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility.| Katherine Johnson in front of the Computational Research Facility named for her]]\nTwo NASA facilities have been named in her honor. On September&nbsp;22, 2017, NASA opened the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility in Hampton, Virginia.<ref name=\"The_Root\">{{cite news |last=Harriot |first=Michale |title=NASA Dedicates Building To Hidden Figures Heroine Katherine Johnson |publisher=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]] |date=September 24, 2017 |url=http://www.theroot.com/nasa-dedicates-building-to-hidden-figures-heroine-kathe-1818701871 |accessdate=September 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924192530/http://www.theroot.com/nasa-dedicates-building-to-hidden-figures-heroine-kathe-1818701871 |archive-date=September 24, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> NASA renamed the Independent Verification and Validation Facility, in Fairmont, West Virginia, to the [[Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility]] on February&nbsp;22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Gina |title=NASA Honors 'Hidden Figure' Katherine Johnson |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/the-scene/NASA-Renames-Facility-to-Honor-Hidden-Figure-Katherine-Johnson-506249461.html |website=NBC4 Washington |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224093056/https://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/the-scene/NASA-Renames-Facility-to-Honor-Hidden-Figure-Katherine-Johnson-506249461.html |archive-date=February 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Hidden Figures Award Ceremony (NHQ201612010025).jpg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated in a chair holding a NASA Group Achievement Award flanked by a man and a woman | Johnson receiving a [[NASA Group Achievement Award]]]]\n*[[NASA Group Achievement Award]] presented to the Lunar Spacecraft and Operations team&nbsp;\u2013 for pioneering work in the field of navigation supporting the spacecraft that orbited and mapped the Moon in preparation for the [[Apollo program]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />{{When|date=February 2020}}\n* 1971, 1980, 1984, 1985, 1986: NASA Langley Research Center Special Achievement award<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\">{{cite web |title=Katherine G. Johnson: Biography |work=[[Julieanna Richardson#The HistoryMakers|The History Makers]] |url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/katherine-g-johnson-42 |date=February 6, 2012 |access-date=January 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108093434/http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/katherine-g-johnson-42 |archive-date=January 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 1998, Honorary Doctor of Laws, from [[Farmingdale State College|SUNY Farmingdale]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"AAR\" />\n* 1999, West Virginia State College Outstanding Alumnus of the Year<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"AAR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/kathrine-g-johnson-value-nasa|title=Katherine Johnson biography|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001155251/http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/kathrine-g-johnson-value-nasa |archive-date=October 1, 2017|website=African-American Registry|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2006, Honorary Doctor of Science by the [[Capitol Technology University|Capitol College]], Laurel, [[Maryland]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"CC\">[http://www.capitol-college.edu/files/file/PDFs/Media%20and%20Communications/06_07%20Capitol%20Chronicle.pdf \"Live, Learn, Pursue Passion&nbsp;\u2013 NASA Mathematician preps Class of 2006 to find its mission\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624073537/http://www.capitol-college.edu/files/file/PDFs/Media%20and%20Communications/06_07%20Capitol%20Chronicle.pdf |date=June 24, 2010 }}, ''Capitol Chronicle'', Summer 2006, Capitol College (12 pages, PDF format)</ref>\n* 2010, Honorary Doctorate of Science from [[Old Dominion University]], Norfolk, Virginia<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.odu.edu/news/2017/1/mlk_observance_previ|title=MLK Event to Feature 'Hidden Figures' Author Margot Lee Shetterly|website=[[Old Dominion University]]|language=en-us|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417222748/https://www.odu.edu/news/2017/1/mlk_observance_previ|archive-date=April 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2014, De Pizan Honor from National Women's History Museum<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nwhm.org/depizan14/honorees.html |title=De Pizan Honor |website=[[National Women's History Museum]]}}</ref>\n* 2015, NCWIT Pioneer in Tech Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson |url=https://www.ncwit.org/profile/katherine-johnson |work=[[National Center for Women & Information Technology]] |date=2015 |access-date=December 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220160118/https://www.ncwit.org/profile/katherine-johnson |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 2015, [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref>{{cite web|first1=Phil|last1=Helsel|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2015/11/24/obama-honoring-spielberg-streisand-and-more-with-medal-of-freed/21272337/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl3%7Csec1_lnk3%26pLid%3D-40526639|title=Obama honoring Spielberg, Streisand and more with medal of freedom|agency=[[NBC News]]|website=AOL|date=November 24, 2015|access-date=November 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125221354/http://www.aol.com/article/2015/11/24/obama-honoring-spielberg-streisand-and-more-with-medal-of-freed/21272337/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl3%7Csec1_lnk3%26pLid%3D-40526639|archive-date=November 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Silver Snoopy award]] from Leland Melvin<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson at NASA Langley Research Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center |publisher=NASA |date=September 22, 2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107001046/http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center/ |archive-date=November 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]]'s Arthur B.C. Walker II Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson to receive the ASP's new Arthur B.C. Walker II Award |url=https://www.astrosociety.org/society-news/katherine-johnson-to-receive-the-asps-new-arthur-b-c-walker-ii-award/ |work=[[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] |date=2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028151951/https://www.astrosociety.org/society-news/katherine-johnson-to-receive-the-asps-new-arthur-b-c-walker-ii-award/ |archive-date=October 28, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2016, Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters from [[West Virginia University]], Morgantown, West Virginia<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine G. Johnson Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters |url=http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |publisher=West Virginia University |date=September 12, 2016 |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302025622/http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*On December 1, 2016, Johnson received the Langley West Computing Unit [[NASA Group Achievement Award]] at a reception at the [[Virginia Air and Space Center]]. Other awardees included her colleagues, Dorothy Vaughan and Mary Jackson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/hidden-figures-premiere-and-award-ceremony|title=Hidden Figures Premiere and Award Ceremony|last=Loff|first=Sarah|date=2016-12-02|website=NASA|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*2017, [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] (DAR) Medal of Honor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dar.org/national-society/media-center/news-releases/126th-continental-congress-daughters-american-revolution|title=126th Continental Congress Daughters of the American Revolution Convene in Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Daughters of the American Revolution]]|access-date=July 18, 2019|date=June 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718072640/https://www.dar.org/national-society/media-center/news-releases/126th-continental-congress-daughters-american-revolution|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2017 Honorary Doctorate from [[Spelman College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spelman.edu/docs/presidents-office/past-honorary-degree-recipients.pdf?sfvrsn=cecf8c50_14|title=Honorary Degree Recipients|publisher=[[Spelman College]]|access-date=June 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412075423/https://www.spelman.edu/docs/presidents-office/past-honorary-degree-recipients.pdf?sfvrsn=cecf8c50_14|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* May&nbsp;12, 2018, [[Honorary degree|Honorary]] [[Doctor of Science|Doctorate of Science]] from the [[College of William & Mary]], [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], Virginia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/trailblazing-african-american-women-to-be-honored-at-william-mary-commencement.php|title=Trailblazing African-American women to be honored at William & Mary Commencement|publisher=[[College of William & Mary]]|date=March 23, 2018|access-date=June 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511235206/https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/trailblazing-african-american-women-to-be-honored-at-william-mary-commencement.php|archive-date=May 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ulneupo2H0|title=2018 Honorary Degree: Katherine Johnson|publisher=William & Mary|date=May 12, 2018|access-date=June 15, 2019|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226123238/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ulneupo2H0|archive-date=December 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On April&nbsp;29, 2019, the [[University of Johannesburg]] and its Faculty of Science conferred Johnson with the degree of ''Philosophiae Doctor Honoris causa'' for her pioneering role at NASA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itweb.co.za/content/LPwQ57lywXLMNgkj|title=UJ honours 'human computer' Katherine Johnson|last=Malinga|first=Sibahle|date=2019-04-29|website=ITWeb|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uj.ac.za:443/newandevents/Pages/UJ-honours-NASA-pioneer-Katherine-Johnson.aspx|title=UJ honours NASA pioneer and African-American icon Katherine Johnson|last=|first=|date=2019-04-29|website=University of Johannesburg|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*November&nbsp;8, 2019, [[Congressional Gold Medal]]<ref name=\"congress\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1396?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22hr1396%22%5D%7D&r=1&s=1|title=H.R.1396 - Hidden Figures Congressional Gold Medal Act|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=November 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109195154/https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1396%3Fq%3D%257B%2522search%2522:%255B%2522hr1396%2522%255D%257D%26r%3D1%26s%3D1|archive-date=November 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-110819a-hidden-figures-congressional-gold-medal.html|title=NASA's 'hidden figures' to be awarded Congressional Gold Medals|date=November 8, 2019|access-date=February 26, 2020|website=collectSPACE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109012341/http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-110819a-hidden-figures-congressional-gold-medal.html|archive-date=November 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Annie Easley]], mathematician\n*[[List of African-American women in STEM fields]]\n*[[List of West Virginia University alumni]]\n*[[Mathematical Tables Project]], pioneering human computer group\n*[[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Beverly Golemba, ''[https://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/crgis/images/c/c7/Golemba.pdf Human Computers: The Women in Aeronautical Research],'' unpublished manuscript 1994, NASA Langley Archives.\n* Brigham Narins, ''Notable Scientists: From 1900 to the Present'', Gale Group, 2001, {{ISBN|9780787617547}}.\n* {{cite book|last1=Zierdt-Warshaw|first1=Linda|last2=Winkler|first2=Alan|last3=Bernstein|first3=Leonard|title=American Women in Technology: an encyclopedia|date=2000|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=1576070727|edition=|oclc=48139041|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanwomenint0000zier}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Katherine Johnson}}\n*[https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/katherine-johnson-nasa-mathematician-211312769.html Katherine G. Johnson] Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n*{{cite journal |last1=Shetterly |first1=Margot Lee |title=Obituary: Katherine Johnson (1918\u20132020) |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |date=12 March 2020 |volume=579, 341 (2020) |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00749-3 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00749-3 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}\n\n\n{{Virginia Women in History}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Katherine}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:African-American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:African-American scientists]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Presbyterians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:West Area Computers]]\n[[Category:People from Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Scientists from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:West Virginia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:West Virginia University alumni]]\n[[Category:American women computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educators from Virginia]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:African-American centenarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others with the same or similar name|Katharine Johnson (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|American mathematician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}{{Use American English|date = February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Katherine Johnson\n| image        = Katherine Johnson 1983.jpg\n| alt          = Katherine Johnson\n| caption      = Katherine Johnson in 1983\n| birth_name   = Creola Katherine Coleman\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1918|08|26}}\n| birth_place  = [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|02|24|1918|08|26}}\n| death_place  = [[Newport News, Virginia]], U.S.\n| other_names  = Katherine Goble\n| alma_mater   = [[West Virginia State College]]\n| occupation   = [[Mathematician]]\n| employer     = [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics|NACA]], [[NASA]] 1953\u20131988\n| known_for    = Calculating trajectories for NASA missions\n| spouse       = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|James Goble|1939|1956|end=died}}|{{marriage|Jim Johnson|1959|2019|end=died}}}}\n| children     = 3\n| awards       = {{unbulleted list|[[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] (2015)|[[Silver Snoopy award]] (2016)|[[NASA Group Achievement Award]] (2016)|[[Congressional Gold Medal]] (2019)}}\n}}\n'''Katherine Johnson''' (August 26, 1918 \u2013 February 24, 2020) was an American mathematician whose calculations of [[orbital mechanics]] as a [[NASA]] employee were critical to the success of the first and subsequent U.S. crewed spaceflights.<ref name=\"Smith\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count|title = Katherine Johnson: The Girl Who Loved to Count|date = November 24, 2015|access-date = February 12, 2016|publisher = [[NASA]]|last = Smith|first = Yvette|quote = Her calculations proved as critical to the success of the Apollo Moon landing program and the start of the Space Shuttle program, as they did to those first steps on the country's journey into space.|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190212013908/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count/|archive-date = February 12, 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> During her 35-year career at NASA and its [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics|predecessor]], she earned a reputation for mastering complex manual calculations and helped pioneer the use of computers to perform the tasks. The space agency noted her \"historical role as one of the first [[African-American]] women to work as a NASA scientist\".<ref name=hftmf /><!--\"African American\" should be in the lead, per Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Biographies#Context; it is a part of her WP:Notability.-->\n\nJohnson's work included calculating trajectories, [[launch window]]s, and emergency return paths for [[Project Mercury]] spaceflights, including those for astronauts [[Alan Shepard]], the first American in space, and [[John Glenn]], the first American in orbit, and rendezvous paths for the [[Apollo program|Apollo]] [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] and [[Apollo command module|command module]] on flights to the Moon. Her calculations were also essential to  the beginning of the [[Space Shuttle program]], and she worked on plans for [[Exploration of Mars|a mission to Mars]].\n\nIn 2015, President [[Barack Obama]] awarded Johnson the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]. In 2016, she was presented the [[Silver Snoopy award|Silver Snoopy Award]] by NASA astronaut [[Leland D. Melvin]] and a [[NASA Group Achievement Award]]. She was portrayed by [[Taraji P. Henson]] as a lead character in the 2016 film ''[[Hidden Figures]]''. In 2019, Johnson was awarded the [[Congressional Gold Medal]].\n\n== Early life and education==\nJohnson was born as Creola Katherine Coleman on August 26, 1918, in [[White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]], to Joylette and Joshua Coleman.<ref name=\"NYT\"/><ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.visionaryproject.org/johnsonkatherine/|title = Katherine Johnson&nbsp;\u2013 Oral History|date = |access-date = February 12, 2016|website = National Visionary Leadership Project|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160223212717/http://www.visionaryproject.org/johnsonkatherine/|archive-date = February 23, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> She was the youngest of four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shetterly|first1=Margot Lee|title=The Woman the Mercury Astronauts Couldn't Do Without|url=http://nautil.us/issue/43/Heroes/the-woman-the-mercury-astronauts-couldnt-do-without|access-date=December 8, 2016|work=[[Nautilus (science magazine)|Nautilus]]|date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204125744/http://nautil.us/issue/43/heroes/the-woman-the-mercury-astronauts-couldnt-do-without|archive-date=December 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Her mother was a teacher and her father was a lumberman, farmer, and handyman, and worked at the [[The Greenbrier|Greenbrier Hotel]].<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"Gutman\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news/20151226/west-virginian-of-the-year-katherine-g-johnson|title = West Virginian of the Year: Katherine G. Johnson|date = December 26, 2015|access-date = February 12, 2016|website = [[Charleston Gazette-Mail]]|last = Gutman|first = David|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170827135853/http://www.wvgazettemail.com/news/20151226/west-virginian-of-the-year-katherine-g-johnson|archive-date = August 27, 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nColeman showed strong mathematical abilities from an early age. Because [[Greenbrier County, West Virginia|Greenbrier County]] did not offer public schooling for African-American students past the eighth grade, the Colemans arranged for their children to attend high school in [[Institute, West Virginia]]. This school was on the campus of [[West Virginia State University|West Virginia State College]] (WVSC).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography |title=From Hidden to Modern Figures \u2013 Katherine Johnson Biography |last=Shetterly |first=Margot Lee |date=December 1, 2016 |website=NASA |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908094437/https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Johnson was enrolled when she was ten years old.<ref name=\"NASA feature\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count |title=Katherine Johnson: The Girl Who Loved to Count |editor=Yvette Smith<!--Not stated--> |date=November 24, 2015 |website=NASA |access-date=March 1, 2017 |quote=Fascinated by numbers and smart to boot, for by the time she was 10 years old, she was a high school freshman&nbsp;\u2013 a truly amazing feat in an era when school for African-Americans normally stopped at eighth grade for those who could indulge in that luxury. Katherine skipped several grades to graduate from high school at 14 and from college at 18. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228205427/https://www.nasa.gov/feature/katherine-johnson-the-girl-who-loved-to-count/ |archive-date=February 28, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The family split their time between Institute during the school year and White Sulphur Springs in the summer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spacegrant.org/programs/service-award/johnson/|title=Johnson|website=National Space Grant Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226170728/https://spacegrant.org/programs/service-award/johnson/|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{external media| float = left | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?462474-2/national-history-day-katherine-johnson-quiet-triumph-white-mans-world Interview with West Virginia State University President Anthony Jenkins on Johnson's studies and career, October 21, 2019], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nAfter graduating from high school at 14, Johnson enrolled at West Virginia State, a [[historically black college]].<ref name=\"NASA bio\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography|title=Katherine Johnson Biography|last=Loff|first=Sarah|date=November 22, 2016|newspaper=NASA|language=en|access-date=February 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908094437/https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography/|archive-date=September 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> As a student, she took every math course offered by the college. Multiple professors mentored her, including the chemist and mathematician [[Angie Turner King]], who had mentored Coleman throughout high school, and [[W. W. Schieffelin Claytor]], the third African-American to receive a Ph.D. in mathematics. Claytor added new mathematics courses just for Johnson.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Shetterly|first=Margot Lee|url=https://archive.org/details/hiddenfiguresame0000shet|url-access=registration|title=Hidden Figures: The American Dream and the Untold Story of the Black Women Mathematicians Who Helped Win the Space Race|date=2016-09-06|publisher=William Morrow|isbn=978-0-06-236361-9|pages=[https://archive.org/details/hiddenfiguresame0000shet/page/24 24]|language=en}}</ref> She graduated ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]'' in 1937, with degrees in mathematics and French, at age 18.<ref name=\"WVGazetteMail\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.wvgazettemail.com/article/20151116/GZ01/151119605/1101|title=WV native, NASA mathematician to receive Presidential Medal of Freedom|last=Gutman|first=David|date=November 16, 2015|website=WV Gazette Mail: Charleston Gazette-Mail|access-date=February 12, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216001223/http://www.wvgazettemail.com/article/20151116/GZ01/151119605/1101|archive-date=February 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NASA feature\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |title=Katherine G. Johnson \u2013 Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2015 |website=West Virginia University |publisher=WVU |access-date=March 1, 2017 |quote=Katherine Johnson graduated from high school at age 14 and from college at 18. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302025622/http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Johnson was a member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.watchtheyard.com/akas/alpha-kappa-alpha-legos/|title=These Two Famous Alpha Kappa Alpha Members Are Getting Their Own Legos|date=August 15, 2017|website=Watch The Yard|language=en-US|access-date=February 26, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226171037/https://www.watchtheyard.com/akas/alpha-kappa-alpha-legos/|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She took on a teaching job at a black public school in [[Marion, Virginia]].<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /><ref>{{cite news |work=SWVA Today |last=Porter-Nichols |first=Stephanie |date=January 24, 2017 |title=Council honors one-time Marion teacher Katherine Johnson of 'Hidden Figures' |url=http://www.swvatoday.com/news/smyth_county/article_35c83f32-df64-11e6-a8e6-bfcf3ba856af.html |access-date=October 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014092136/https://www.swvatoday.com/news/smyth_county/article_35c83f32-df64-11e6-a8e6-bfcf3ba856af.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1939, after marrying her first husband, James Goble, she left her teaching job and enrolled in a graduate math program. She quit after one year after becoming pregnant and choosing to focus on her family.<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> She was the first African-American woman to attend graduate school at [[West Virginia University]] in [[Morgantown, West Virginia]]. Through WVSC's president, Dr. John W. Davis, she became one of three African-American students,<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> and the only woman, selected to integrate the graduate school after the 1938 United States Supreme Court ruling ''[[Missouri ex rel. Gaines v. Canada]]''. The court ruled that states that provided public higher education to white students also had to provide it to black students, to be satisfied either by establishing black colleges and universities or by admitting black students to previously white-only universities.<ref name=\"Gutman\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/305/337/case.html|title = Missouri ex rel. Gaines v. Canada 305 U.S. 337 (1938)|date = 1938|access-date = February 12, 2016|website = Justia US Supreme Court|last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160217034207/https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/305/337/case.html|archive-date = February 17, 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Katherine Johnson at NASA, in 1966.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of Johnson sitting at a desk | Johnson working as a \"computer\" at NASA in 1966]]\nJohnson decided on a career as a research mathematician, although this was a difficult field for African Americans and women to enter. The first jobs she found were in teaching. At a family gathering in 1952, a relative mentioned that the [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]] (NACA) was hiring mathematicians.<ref name=\"NASA bio\" /> At the [[Langley Research Center|Langley Memorial Aeronautical Laboratory]], based in [[Hampton, Virginia|Hampton]], Virginia, near [[Langley Field]], NACA hired African-American mathematicians as well as whites for their Guidance and Navigation Department. Johnson accepted a job offer from the agency in June 1953.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />\n\nAccording to an oral history archived by the National Visionary Leadership Project:\n\n<blockquote>At first she [Johnson] worked in a pool of women performing math calculations. Katherine has referred to the women in the pool as virtual \"computers who wore skirts\". Their main job was to read the data from the black boxes of planes and carry out other precise mathematical tasks. Then one day, Katherine (and a colleague) were temporarily assigned to help the all-male flight research team. Katherine's knowledge of [[analytic geometry]] helped make quick allies of male bosses and colleagues to the extent that, \"they forgot to return me to the pool\".  While the racial and gender barriers were always there, Katherine says she ignored them. Katherine was assertive, asking to be included in editorial meetings (where no women had gone before). She simply told people she had done the work and that she belonged.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />\n</blockquote>\n\nFrom 1953 to 1958, Johnson worked as a [[Human computer|computer]],<ref name=\"Jim Hodges\">{{cite web |title=She Was a Computer When Computers Wore Skirts |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/rn_kjohnson.html |first=Jim |last=Hodges |publisher=NASA |work=Langley Research Center |date=August 26, 2008 |access-date=December 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114124545/http://www.nasa.gov/centers/langley/news/researchernews/rn_kjohnson.html |archive-date=November 14, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> analyzing topics such as gust alleviation for aircraft. Originally assigned to the [[West Area Computers]] section supervised by mathematician [[Dorothy Vaughan]], Johnson was reassigned to the Guidance and Control Division of Langley's Flight Research Division. It was staffed by white male engineers.<ref name=\"buckley\" /> In keeping with state racial segregation laws, and federal workplace segregation introduced under President [[Woodrow Wilson]] in the early 20th&nbsp;century, Johnson and the other African-American women in the computing pool were required to work, eat, and use restrooms that were separate from those of their white peers. Their office was labeled as \"Colored Computers\". In an interview with [[WHRO-TV]], Johnson stated that she \"didn't feel the segregation at NASA, because everybody there was doing research. You had a mission and you worked on it, and it was important to you to do your job&nbsp;... and play bridge at lunch.\" She added: \"I didn't feel any segregation. I knew it was there, but I didn't feel it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyvshollywood.com/video/katherine-johnson-interview-nasa/ |title=Katherine Johnson Interview: NASA's Human Computer |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2016 |website=HistoryvsHollywood.com |publisher=CTF Media |access-date=March 2, 2017 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303050429/http://www.historyvshollywood.com/video/katherine-johnson-interview-nasa/ |archive-date=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nNACA disbanded the colored computing pool in 1958 when the agency was superseded by NASA, which adopted digital computers. Although the installation was desegregated,<ref name=\"buckley\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/books/on-being-black-female-math-whizzes-during-the-space-race.html|title=On Being a Black Female Math Whiz During the Space Race|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=September 6, 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=September 6, 2016|page=C1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160906030123/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/06/books/on-being-black-female-math-whizzes-during-the-space-race.html|archive-date=September 6, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> forms of discrimination were still pervasive. Johnson recalled that era:\n\n<blockquote>We needed to be assertive as women in those days&nbsp;\u2013 assertive and aggressive&nbsp;\u2013 and the degree to which we had to be that way depended on where you were. I had to be. In the early days of NASA women were not allowed to put their names on the reports&nbsp;\u2013 no woman in my division had had her name on a report. I was working with Ted Skopinski and he wanted to leave and go to Houston&nbsp;... but Henry Pearson, our supervisor&nbsp;\u2013 he was not a fan of women&nbsp;\u2013 kept pushing him to finish the report we were working on. Finally, Ted told him, \"Katherine should finish the report, she's done most of the work anyway.\" So Ted left Pearson with no choice; I finished the report and my name went on it, and that was the first time a woman in our division had her name on something.<ref name=\"St Andrews\">Quoted at {{cite web |url=http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Johnson_Katherine.html |title=Katherine Coleman Goble Johnson |author=J. J. O'Connor |author2=E. F. Robertson |date=February 2020 |website=School of Mathematics & Statistics University of St Andrews, UK |publisher=School of Mathematics & Statistics University of St Andrews, UK |access-date=February 26, 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622080756/http://www-history.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/Biographies/Johnson_Katherine.html |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live }} This quotation is an excerpt from W. Warren, \"Katherine Coleman Goble Johnson\", in ''Black Women Scientists in the United States'' (Indiana University Press, 1999), pp. 140\u2013147.</ref></blockquote>\n\nFrom 1958 until her retirement in 1986, Johnson worked as an aerospace technologist, moving during her career to the Spacecraft Controls Branch. She calculated the trajectory for the May&nbsp;5, 1961 space flight of [[Alan Shepard]], the first American in space.<ref name=\"Smith\" /> She also calculated the [[launch window]] for his 1961 [[Project Mercury|Mercury mission]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/71576/black-female-mathematicians-who-sent-astronauts-space|title=The Black Female Mathematicians Who Sent Astronauts to Space|last=Whitney|first=A. K.|access-date=September 10, 2016|date=February 1, 2016<!--|date=2015-->|website=[[Mental Floss]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705103936/http://mentalfloss.com/article/71576/black-female-mathematicians-who-sent-astronauts-space|archive-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> She plotted backup [[navigation]] [[chart]]s for [[astronaut]]s in case of electronic failures.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /> When NASA used electronic computers for the first time to calculate [[John Glenn]]'s orbit around [[Earth]], officials called on Johnson to verify the computer's numbers; Glenn had asked for her specifically and had refused to fly unless Johnson verified the calculations.<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"MakersBio\">{{cite web|title=Makers Profile: Katherine G. Johnson|url=http://www.makers.com/katherine-g-johnson|website=Makers|access-date=May 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180105162815/https://www.makers.com/katherine-g-johnson|archive-date=January 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Sloat\">{{Cite web|last=Sloat|first=Sarah|title='Hidden Figures' Gives NASA Mathematicians Long Overdue Movie|publisher=[[Inverse (website)|Inverse.com]]|date=August 15, 2016|access-date =January 15, 2017|url=https://www.inverse.com/article/19694-5-facts-about-katherine-johnson-hidden-figure}}</ref> [[FYI (U.S. TV channel)|Biography.com]] states these were \"far more difficult calculations, to account for the gravitational pulls of celestial bodies\".<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/katherine-g-johnson-101016|title=Katherine Johnson Biography|date=October 10, 2016|website=[[Biography.com]]|publisher=A&E Television Networks|access-date=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831162903/https://www.biography.com/people/katherine-g-johnson-101016|archive-date=August 31, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Author [[Margot Lee Shetterly]] stated, \"So the astronaut who became a hero, looked to this black woman in the still-segregated South at the time as one of the key parts of making sure his mission would be a success.\" She added that, in a time where computing was \"women's work\" and engineering was left to men, \"it really does have to do with us over the course of time sort of not valuing that work that was done by women, however necessary, as much as we might. And it has taken history to get a perspective on that.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/25/495179824/hidden-figures-how-black-women-did-the-math-that-put-men-on-the-moon |title='Hidden Figures': How Black Women Did The Math That Put Men on the Moon |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=September 25, 2016 |work=[[All Things Considered]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301062054/http://www.npr.org/2016/09/25/495179824/hidden-figures-how-black-women-did-the-math-that-put-men-on-the-moon |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJohnson later worked directly with digital [[computer]]s. Her ability and reputation for accuracy helped to establish confidence in the new technology.<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> In 1961, her work helped to ensure that Alan Shepard's ''[[Freedom 7]]'' Mercury capsule would be found quickly after landing, using the accurate trajectory that had been established.<ref name=businside />\n\n[[File:Katherine Johnson in 2008.jpg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated in a chair looking to her right | Johnson in 2008]]\nShe also helped to calculate the trajectory for the 1969 [[Apollo&nbsp;11]] flight to the Moon.<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"biography.com\" /> During the Moon landing, Johnson was at a meeting in the [[Pocono Mountains]]. She and a few others crowded around a small [[television]] screen watching the first steps on the Moon. In 1970, Johnson worked on the [[Apollo&nbsp;13]] Moon mission. When the mission was aborted, her work on backup procedures and charts helped set a safe path for the crew's return to Earth,<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> creating a one-star observation system that would allow astronauts to determine their location with accuracy. In a 2010 interview, Johnson recalled, \"Everybody was concerned about them getting there. We were concerned about them getting back.\"<ref name=businside>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/katherine-johnson-hidden-figures-nasa-human-computers-2016-8/#johnsons-time-as-a-teacher-hasnt-ever-really-ended-she-strongly-believes-people-need-to-learn-how-to-learn-i-teach-you-what-the-problem-is-how-to-attack-it--if-you-attack-it-properly-youll-get-the-answer-she-said-in-a-2011-interview-28 |title=The unbelievable life of the forgotten genius who turned Americans' space dreams into reality |last=Bartels |first=Meghan |date=August 22, 2016 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=Business Insider Inc. |access-date=March 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303122553/http://www.businessinsider.com/katherine-johnson-hidden-figures-nasa-human-computers-2016-8/#johnsons-time-as-a-teacher-hasnt-ever-really-ended-she-strongly-believes-people-need-to-learn-how-to-learn-i-teach-you-what-the-problem-is-how-to-attack-it--if-you-attack-it-properly-youll-get-the-answer-she-said-in-a-2011-interview-28 |archive-date=March 3, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later in her career, Johnson worked on the [[Space Shuttle program]], the Earth Resources Satellite,<ref name=\"Smith\" /><ref name=\"biography.com\" /> and on plans for a [[Exploration of Mars|mission to Mars]].<ref name=\"Guglielmi\">{{Cite news|last=Guglielmi|first=Jodi|title=Katherine Johnson, Legendary Mathematician and Inspiration for the Upcoming Film Hidden Figures, Turns 98|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=August 26, 2016|access-date=January 15, 2017|url=http://people.com/movies/katherine-johnson-turns-98/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116183513/http://people.com/movies/katherine-johnson-turns-98/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nJohnson spent her later years encouraging students to enter the fields of [[science, technology, engineering, and mathematics]] (STEM).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2020/02/mathematics-pioneer-katherine-johnson-portrayed-in-hidden-figures-dies-at-101.html|title=Mathematics pioneer Katherine Johnson, portrayed in 'Hidden Figures,' dies at 101|agency=Associated Press|date=February 24, 2020|website=[[The Oregonian]]|url-status=live|access-date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200225171953/https://www.oregonlive.com/history/2020/02/mathematics-pioneer-katherine-johnson-portrayed-in-hidden-figures-dies-at-101.html|archive-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nIn 1939, Katherine (then Coleman) married James Francis Goble. They had three daughters: Constance, Joylette, and Katherine. In 1953, she and James moved their family to [[Newport News, Virginia]], to pursue a new job opportunity. In 1956, James Goble died of an inoperable [[brain tumor]]. In 1959, Katherine Goble married James A. \"Jim\" Johnson, a [[United States Army]] officer and veteran of the [[Korean War]]; the pair were married for 60 years until his death in March 2019 at the age of 93.<ref name=\"St Andrews\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: James A. Johnson |url=https://www.ohsmithandsonfuneralhome.com/obituary/james-johnson |accessdate=February 24, 2020|publisher=O.H. Smith & Son Funeral Home}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/science/katherine-johnson-dead.html|title=Katherine Johnson Dies at 101; Mathematician Broke Barriers at NASA|first=Margalit|last=Fox|authorlink=Margalit Fox|date=February 25, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times|page=A1|access-date=February 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224154106/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/24/science/katherine-johnson-dead.html|archive-date=February 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson, who had six grandchildren and 11 great-grandchildren, lived in [[Hampton, Virginia]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Fountain|first=Nigel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/feb/24/katherine-johnson-obituary|title=Katherine Johnson obituary|date=February 24, 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=February 26, 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226023231/https://www.theguardian.com/science/2020/feb/24/katherine-johnson-obituary|archive-date=February 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She encouraged her grandchildren and students to pursue careers in science and technology.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/woen-in-stem|title=The Untold History of Women in Science and Technology: Katherine Johnson |website=The White House |access-date=October 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/node/311241\n|archivedate=January 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe was a member of Carver Memorial [[Presbyterian Church (USA)|Presbyterian Church]] for 50 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pres-outlook.org/2017/01/real-life-hidden-figures-mathematician-longtime-presbyterian/|title=Real life 'Hidden Figures' mathematician is longtime Presbyterian|website=The Presbyterian Outlook|first=Gregg|last=Brekke|date=January 10, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224164531/https://pres-outlook.org/2017/01/real-life-hidden-figures-mathematician-longtime-presbyterian/|archivedate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nJohnson died at a retirement home in Newport News on February 24, 2020, at age 101.<ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.wtkr.com/news/local-hero-nasa-mathematician-katherine-johnson-dies-at-101|title = Local hero, NASA mathematician Katherine Johnson dies at 101|work = [[WTKR]]|date = February 24, 2020|accessdate = February 24, 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200224193445/https://www.wtkr.com/news/local-hero-nasa-mathematician-katherine-johnson-dies-at-101|archive-date = February 24, 2020|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\"/> Following her death, [[Jim Bridenstine]], NASA's administrator, described her as \"an American hero\" and stated that \"her pioneering legacy will never be forgotten.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet||first=Jim|last=Bridenstine|author-link=Jim Bridenstine|date=February 24, 2020|user=JimBridenstine|number=1231946829962584065|title=Our @NASA family is sad to learn the news that Katherine Johnson passed away this morning at 101 years old. She was an American hero and her pioneering legacy will never be forgotten. https://www.nasa.gov/content/katherine-johnson-biography}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honors==\n[[File:Katherine Johnson medal.jpeg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated wearing her Presidential Medal of Freedom | The [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]] was awarded to Johnson in 2015.]]\n\nJohnson co-authored 26 scientific papers.<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"NASAHistory\">{{cite web|title=Human computers: Katherine G. Johnson|url=http://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/historic/Katherine_Johnson|work=NASA Cultural Resources (CRGIS)|access-date=August 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719141646/http://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/historic/Katherine_Johnson|archive-date=July 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Her social influence as a pioneer in [[Outline of space science|space science]] and [[computing]] is demonstrated by the [[honour|honors]] she received and her status as a [[role model]] for a life in science.<ref name=\"NASAHistory\" /><ref name=\"SCIENCEYEAR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scienceyear.com/text_only/outthere/black_history/johnson.html|title=Black history... Katherine G Johnson (1918 \u2013 retired)\"|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061021221512/http://www.scienceyear.com/text_only/outthere/black_history/johnson.html |archive-date=October 21, 2006|url-status=dead|website=Planet Science|publisher=NESTA}}</ref><ref name=\"THINKQUEST\">{{cite web|url=http://library.thinkquest.org/2907/katherine_johnson.html|title=Katherine G. Johnson: Physicist, Space Scientist, Mathematician|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304132115/http://library.thinkquest.org/2907/katherine_johnson.html |archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=dead|website=ThinkQuest Library|publisher=Oracle}}</ref> Johnson was named West Virginia State College Outstanding Alumnus of the Year in 1999. President [[Barack Obama]] presented her with the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], one of 17 Americans so honored on November&nbsp;24, 2015. She was cited as a pioneering example of African-American women in STEM.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33958124/daily_press/|title=Peninsula Officials: Regions Disaster-Ready|newspaper=[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|location=Newport News, Virginia|date=November 17, 2015|page=A1|via=Newspapers.com|last1=Ketchum|first1=Sarah J.|access-date=July 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717170608/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33958124/daily_press/|archive-date=July 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> President Obama said at the time, \"Katherine G. Johnson refused to be limited by society's expectations of her gender and race while expanding the boundaries of humanity's reach.\"<ref name=\"NYT\" /> NASA noted her \"historical role as one of the first [[African-American]] women to work as a NASA scientist.\"<ref name=\"hftmf\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WcEDJOWka58|title=Hidden Figures To Modern Figures: Students See SLS Rocket at Michoud|last=|first=|date=November 24, 2016|website=YouTube|publisher=Marshall Space Flight Center|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn May&nbsp;5, 2016, a new {{convert|40000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building was named the \"Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility\" and formally dedicated at the agency's Langley Research Center in Hampton, Virginia. The facility officially opened its doors on September&nbsp;22, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smTcsodvEqM|title=Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility Ribbon Cutting|date=September 22, 2017|work=NASA Langley Research Center|via=YouTube|access-date=September 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003233559/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=smTcsodvEqM|archive-date=October 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Johnson attended this event, which also marked the 55th anniversary of astronaut Alan Shepard's historic rocket launch and splashdown, a success Johnson helped achieve.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-dedicates-facility-to-mathematician-presidential-medal-winner|title=NASA Dedicates Facility to Mathematician, Presidential Medal Winner|first=Karen|last=Northon|date=April 28, 2016|access-date=August 1, 2016|id=M16-046|publisher=NASA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730102759/http://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-dedicates-facility-to-mathematician-presidential-medal-winner/|archive-date=July 30, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At the ceremony, deputy director Lewin said this about Johnson: \"Millions of people around the world watched Shepard's flight, but what they didn't know at the time was that the calculations that got him into space and safely home were done by today's guest of honor, Katherine Johnson\". During the event, Johnson also received a [[Silver Snoopy]] award; often called the astronaut's award, NASA stated it is given to those \"who have made outstanding contributions to flight safety and mission success\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center |title=Katherine Johnson at NASA Langley Research Center |date=August 26, 2016 |website=NASA History |publisher=[[NASA]] |access-date=March 1, 2017 |last1=Loff |first1=Sarah |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302193912/https://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center/ |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nJohnson was included on the [[BBC]]'s list of [[100 Women (BBC)|100 Women]] of influence worldwide in 2016.<ref name=\"list2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-38012048|title=BBC 100 Women 2016: Who is on the list?|publisher=BBC News|date=November 21, 2016|access-date=November 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223235036/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-38012048|archive-date=December 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2016 video NASA stated, \"Her calculations proved as critical to the success of the Apollo Moon landing program and the start of the Space Shuttle program, as they did to those first steps on the country's journey into space.\"<ref name=\"Smith\" />\n{{external media| float = right| width=230px | video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?414833-1/margot-lee-shetterly-discusses-hidden-figures Presentation by Margot Lee Shetterly on ''Hidden Figures'' at the Hampton History Museum, September 8, 2016], [[C-SPAN]]| video2 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?432540-28/hidden-figures Discussion with Shetterly on ''Hidden Figures'' at the National Book Festival, September 2, 2017], [[C-SPAN]]}} \nThe highly acclaimed film ''[[Hidden Figures]]'', released in December 2016, was based on the [[Hidden Figures (book)|non-fiction book]] of the same title by Margot Lee Shetterly, which was published earlier that year. It follows Johnson and other female African-American mathematicians ([[Mary Jackson (engineer)|Mary Jackson]] and Dorothy Vaughan) who worked at NASA. [[Taraji P. Henson]] plays Johnson in the film.<ref name=\"Sloat\" /> Appearing alongside Henson at the [[89th Academy Awards]], Johnson received a standing ovation from the audience.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/real-life-subject-hidden-figures-receives-standing-ovation/story?id=45755913 |title=Katherine Johnson, real-life subject of 'Hidden Figures' receives standing ovation at Oscars |first=Taylor |last=Maple |date=February 26, 2017 |access-date=February 26, 2017 |website=[[ABC News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227050544/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/real-life-subject-hidden-figures-receives-standing-ovation/story?id=45755913 |archive-date=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In an earlier interview, Johnson offered the following comment about the movie: \"It was well-done. The three leading ladies did an excellent job portraying us.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Amina |date=February 26, 2017 |title=Q&A: Our interview with Katherine G. Johnson, the real-life mathematician who inspired 'Hidden Figures' |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-oscars-2017-89th-academy-awards-q-a-our-interview-with-katherine-g-1488161846-htmlstory.html |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |location=Los Angeles |access-date=March 1, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301201003/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-oscars-2017-89th-academy-awards-q-a-our-interview-with-katherine-g-1488161846-htmlstory.html |archive-date=March 1, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In a 2016 episode of the [[NBC]] series ''[[Timeless (TV series)|Timeless]],'' titled \"Space Race\", the mathematician is portrayed by Nadine Ellis.<ref>{{cite web |first=Allison |last=Shoemaker |title=Timeless needs to ditch the formula |url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/timeless-needs-ditch-formula-246556 |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=November 29, 2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201123306/http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/timeless-needs-ditch-formula-246556 |archive-date=December 1, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nScience writer [[Maia Weinstock]] developed a prototype [[Lego]] for Women of NASA in 2016 and included Johnson; she declined to have her likeness printed on the final product.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/women-nasa-lego-prototype-joins-collection|title=\"Women of NASA\" LEGO Prototype Joins Collection|last1=Brady|first1=Hillary|date=August 27, 2018|publisher=[[Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009013147/https://airandspace.si.edu/stories/editorial/women-nasa-lego-prototype-joins-collection|archive-date=October 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On May&nbsp;12, 2018, she was awarded an [[honorary doctorate]] by the [[College of William & Mary]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vagazette.com/news/va-vg-wm-commencement-20180516-story.html |title=William and Mary commencement sends graduates out on new adventure |first=Amelia |last=Heymann |work=[[The Virginia Gazette]] |date=May 12, 2018 |access-date=June 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613184433/http://www.vagazette.com/news/va-vg-wm-commencement-20180516-story.html |archive-date=June 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2018, West Virginia State University established a STEM scholarship in honor of Johnson and erected a life-size statue of her on campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wvstateu.edu/CampusNews/2018/May/West-Virginia-State-University-to-Honor-Katherine.aspx|title=West Virginia State University to Honor Katherine Johnson with Statue, Scholarship|publisher=WVSU|date=May 31, 2018|access-date=June 5, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613160530/http://www.wvstateu.edu/CampusNews/2018/May/West-Virginia-State-University-to-Honor-Katherine.aspx|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mattel]] announced a [[Barbie]] doll in Johnson's likeness with a NASA identity badge in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-katherine-johnson-barbie-20180306-story.html|title=Katherine Johnson to be included in Barbie 'Inspiring Women' series|last=Petrini|first=Andi|newspaper=Daily Press|access-date=September 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903013353/http://www.dailypress.com/entertainment/dp-fea-katherine-johnson-barbie-20180306-story.html|archive-date=September 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, Johnson was announced as one of the members of the inaugural class of ''[[Government Executive]]''{{'s}}  Government Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Tom|last1=Shoop|url=https://www.govexec.com/management/2019/08/inaugural-inductees-government-hall-fame-unveiled/159156/|title=Inaugural Inductees Into Government Hall of Fame Unveiled|website=[[Government Executive]]|accessdate=August 16, 2019|date=August 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815155258/https://www.govexec.com/management/2019/08/inaugural-inductees-government-hall-fame-unveiled/159156/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Katherine Johnson at the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility.jpg|thumb|alt= Johnson seated on a bench beside a sign in front of the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility.| Katherine Johnson in front of the Computational Research Facility named for her]]\nTwo NASA facilities have been named in her honor. On September&nbsp;22, 2017, NASA opened the Katherine G. Johnson Computational Research Facility in Hampton, Virginia.<ref name=\"The_Root\">{{cite news |last=Harriot |first=Michale |title=NASA Dedicates Building To Hidden Figures Heroine Katherine Johnson |publisher=[[The Root (magazine)|The Root]] |date=September 24, 2017 |url=http://www.theroot.com/nasa-dedicates-building-to-hidden-figures-heroine-kathe-1818701871 |accessdate=September 24, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924192530/http://www.theroot.com/nasa-dedicates-building-to-hidden-figures-heroine-kathe-1818701871 |archive-date=September 24, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> NASA renamed the Independent Verification and Validation Facility, in Fairmont, West Virginia, to the [[Katherine Johnson Independent Verification and Validation Facility]] on February&nbsp;22, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Gina |title=NASA Honors 'Hidden Figure' Katherine Johnson |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/the-scene/NASA-Renames-Facility-to-Honor-Hidden-Figure-Katherine-Johnson-506249461.html |website=NBC4 Washington |accessdate=February 25, 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224093056/https://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/the-scene/NASA-Renames-Facility-to-Honor-Hidden-Figure-Katherine-Johnson-506249461.html |archive-date=February 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n[[File:Hidden Figures Award Ceremony (NHQ201612010025).jpg|thumb|alt=Johnson seated in a chair holding a NASA Group Achievement Award flanked by a man and a woman | Johnson receiving a [[NASA Group Achievement Award]]]]\n*[[NASA Group Achievement Award]] presented to the Lunar Spacecraft and Operations team&nbsp;\u2013 for pioneering work in the field of navigation supporting the spacecraft that orbited and mapped the Moon in preparation for the [[Apollo program]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" />{{When|date=February 2020}}\n* 1971, 1980, 1984, 1985, 1986: NASA Langley Research Center Special Achievement award<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\">{{cite web |title=Katherine G. Johnson: Biography |work=[[Julieanna Richardson#The HistoryMakers|The History Makers]] |url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/katherine-g-johnson-42 |date=February 6, 2012 |access-date=January 7, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108093434/http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/katherine-g-johnson-42 |archive-date=January 8, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 1998, Honorary Doctor of Laws, from [[Farmingdale State College|SUNY Farmingdale]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"AAR\" />\n* 1999, West Virginia State College Outstanding Alumnus of the Year<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"AAR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/kathrine-g-johnson-value-nasa|title=Katherine Johnson biography|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001155251/http://www.aaregistry.org/historic_events/view/kathrine-g-johnson-value-nasa |archive-date=October 1, 2017|website=African-American Registry|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 2006, Honorary Doctor of Science by the [[Capitol Technology University|Capitol College]], Laurel, [[Maryland]]<ref name=\"Katherine Johnson - Oral History\" /><ref name=\"CC\">[http://www.capitol-college.edu/files/file/PDFs/Media%20and%20Communications/06_07%20Capitol%20Chronicle.pdf \"Live, Learn, Pursue Passion&nbsp;\u2013 NASA Mathematician preps Class of 2006 to find its mission\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100624073537/http://www.capitol-college.edu/files/file/PDFs/Media%20and%20Communications/06_07%20Capitol%20Chronicle.pdf |date=June 24, 2010 }}, ''Capitol Chronicle'', Summer 2006, Capitol College (12 pages, PDF format)</ref>\n* 2010, Honorary Doctorate of Science from [[Old Dominion University]], Norfolk, Virginia<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.odu.edu/news/2017/1/mlk_observance_previ|title=MLK Event to Feature 'Hidden Figures' Author Margot Lee Shetterly|website=[[Old Dominion University]]|language=en-us|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417222748/https://www.odu.edu/news/2017/1/mlk_observance_previ|archive-date=April 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2014, De Pizan Honor from National Women's History Museum<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nwhm.org/depizan14/honorees.html |title=De Pizan Honor |website=[[National Women's History Museum]]}}</ref>\n* 2015, NCWIT Pioneer in Tech Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson |url=https://www.ncwit.org/profile/katherine-johnson |work=[[National Center for Women & Information Technology]] |date=2015 |access-date=December 7, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220160118/https://www.ncwit.org/profile/katherine-johnson |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 2015, [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]]<ref>{{cite web|first1=Phil|last1=Helsel|url=http://www.aol.com/article/2015/11/24/obama-honoring-spielberg-streisand-and-more-with-medal-of-freed/21272337/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl3%7Csec1_lnk3%26pLid%3D-40526639|title=Obama honoring Spielberg, Streisand and more with medal of freedom|agency=[[NBC News]]|website=AOL|date=November 24, 2015|access-date=November 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125221354/http://www.aol.com/article/2015/11/24/obama-honoring-spielberg-streisand-and-more-with-medal-of-freed/21272337/?icid=maing-grid7%7Chtmlws-sb-bb%7Cdl3%7Csec1_lnk3%26pLid%3D-40526639|archive-date=November 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Silver Snoopy award]] from Leland Melvin<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson at NASA Langley Research Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center |publisher=NASA |date=September 22, 2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107001046/http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/katherine-johnson-at-nasa-langley-research-center/ |archive-date=November 7, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]]'s Arthur B.C. Walker II Award<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine Johnson to receive the ASP's new Arthur B.C. Walker II Award |url=https://www.astrosociety.org/society-news/katherine-johnson-to-receive-the-asps-new-arthur-b-c-walker-ii-award/ |work=[[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] |date=2016 |access-date=December 5, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028151951/https://www.astrosociety.org/society-news/katherine-johnson-to-receive-the-asps-new-arthur-b-c-walker-ii-award/ |archive-date=October 28, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2016, Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters from [[West Virginia University]], Morgantown, West Virginia<ref>{{cite web |title=Katherine G. Johnson Presidential Honorary Doctorate of Humane Letters |url=http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |publisher=West Virginia University |date=September 12, 2016 |access-date=January 10, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302025622/http://honorarydegrees.wvu.edu/katherine-g-johnson |archive-date=March 2, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*On December 1, 2016, Johnson received the Langley West Computing Unit [[NASA Group Achievement Award]] at a reception at the [[Virginia Air and Space Center]]. Other awardees included her colleagues, Dorothy Vaughan and Mary Jackson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nasa.gov/image-feature/hidden-figures-premiere-and-award-ceremony|title=Hidden Figures Premiere and Award Ceremony|last=Loff|first=Sarah|date=2016-12-02|website=NASA|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*2017, [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] (DAR) Medal of Honor<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dar.org/national-society/media-center/news-releases/126th-continental-congress-daughters-american-revolution|title=126th Continental Congress Daughters of the American Revolution Convene in Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[Daughters of the American Revolution]]|access-date=July 18, 2019|date=June 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718072640/https://www.dar.org/national-society/media-center/news-releases/126th-continental-congress-daughters-american-revolution|archive-date=July 18, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 2017 Honorary Doctorate from [[Spelman College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spelman.edu/docs/presidents-office/past-honorary-degree-recipients.pdf?sfvrsn=cecf8c50_14|title=Honorary Degree Recipients|publisher=[[Spelman College]]|access-date=June 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412075423/https://www.spelman.edu/docs/presidents-office/past-honorary-degree-recipients.pdf?sfvrsn=cecf8c50_14|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* May&nbsp;12, 2018, [[Honorary degree|Honorary]] [[Doctor of Science|Doctorate of Science]] from the [[College of William & Mary]], [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], Virginia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/trailblazing-african-american-women-to-be-honored-at-william-mary-commencement.php|title=Trailblazing African-American women to be honored at William & Mary Commencement|publisher=[[College of William & Mary]]|date=March 23, 2018|access-date=June 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511235206/https://www.wm.edu/news/stories/2018/trailblazing-african-american-women-to-be-honored-at-william-mary-commencement.php|archive-date=May 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ulneupo2H0|title=2018 Honorary Degree: Katherine Johnson|publisher=William & Mary|date=May 12, 2018|access-date=June 15, 2019|via=YouTube|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191226123238/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ulneupo2H0|archive-date=December 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On April&nbsp;29, 2019, the [[University of Johannesburg]] and its Faculty of Science conferred Johnson with the degree of ''Philosophiae Doctor Honoris causa'' for her pioneering role at NASA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itweb.co.za/content/LPwQ57lywXLMNgkj|title=UJ honours 'human computer' Katherine Johnson|last=Malinga|first=Sibahle|date=2019-04-29|website=ITWeb|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uj.ac.za:443/newandevents/Pages/UJ-honours-NASA-pioneer-Katherine-Johnson.aspx|title=UJ honours NASA pioneer and African-American icon Katherine Johnson|last=|first=|date=2019-04-29|website=University of Johannesburg|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*November&nbsp;8, 2019, [[Congressional Gold Medal]]<ref name=\"congress\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1396?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22hr1396%22%5D%7D&r=1&s=1|title=H.R.1396 - Hidden Figures Congressional Gold Medal Act|website=Congress.gov|accessdate=November 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109195154/https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/1396%3Fq%3D%257B%2522search%2522:%255B%2522hr1396%2522%255D%257D%26r%3D1%26s%3D1|archive-date=November 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-110819a-hidden-figures-congressional-gold-medal.html|title=NASA's 'hidden figures' to be awarded Congressional Gold Medals|date=November 8, 2019|access-date=February 26, 2020|website=collectSPACE|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109012341/http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-110819a-hidden-figures-congressional-gold-medal.html|archive-date=November 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Annie Easley]], mathematician\n*[[List of African-American women in STEM fields]]\n*[[List of West Virginia University alumni]]\n*[[Mathematical Tables Project]], pioneering human computer group\n*[[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Beverly Golemba, ''[https://crgis.ndc.nasa.gov/crgis/images/c/c7/Golemba.pdf Human Computers: The Women in Aeronautical Research],'' unpublished manuscript 1994, NASA Langley Archives.\n* Brigham Narins, ''Notable Scientists: From 1900 to the Present'', Gale Group, 2001, {{ISBN|9780787617547}}.\n* {{cite book|last1=Zierdt-Warshaw|first1=Linda|last2=Winkler|first2=Alan|last3=Bernstein|first3=Leonard|title=American Women in Technology: an encyclopedia|date=2000|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=1576070727|edition=|oclc=48139041|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/americanwomenint0000zier}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Katherine Johnson}}\n*[https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/katherine-johnson-nasa-mathematician-211312769.html Katherine G. Johnson] Video produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n*{{cite journal |last1=Shetterly |first1=Margot Lee |title=Obituary: Katherine Johnson (1918\u20132020) |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |date=12 March 2020 |volume=579, 341 (2020) |doi=10.1038/d41586-020-00749-3 |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00749-3 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}\n\n\n{{Virginia Women in History}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Johnson, Katherine}}\n[[Category:1918 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:African-American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:African-American scientists]]\n[[Category:American computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Presbyterians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:American women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Educators from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:West Area Computers]]\n[[Category:People from Hampton, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from White Sulphur Springs, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Scientists from West Virginia]]\n[[Category:West Virginia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:West Virginia University alumni]]\n[[Category:American women computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Congressional Gold Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Presidential Medal of Freedom recipients]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educators from Virginia]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:African-American centenarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Women centenarians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n", "name_user": "2600:4040:12cc:9f00:88f2:81c5:5904:ece7", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katherine_Johnson"}
{"title_page": "University of Bristol", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Bristol University|the university in Anaheim, California|Bristol University (California)|the university in Bristol, Tennessee|Bristol University (Tennessee)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name             = University of Bristol\n| image_name       = University_of_Bristol_crest.jpg\n| image_size       = 150px\n| latin_name       = Universitas Bristolliensis\n| motto            = {{lang-la|Vim promovet insitam}}\n| mottoeng         = [Learning] promotes one's innate power (from [[Horace]], ''Ode 4.4'')<ref name=\"arms\" />\n| established      = 1595 - Merchant Venturers School<br />1876 - [[University College, Bristol]]<br />1909 - received [[royal charter]]\n|type              = [[public university|Public]] [[red brick university|red brick]] [[research university]]\n| endowment        = \u00a372.2m {{small|(as of 31 July 2018)}}<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\"/>\n|budget = [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]642.7 million {{small|(2017-18)}}<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\"/>\n| chancellor       = [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]]<ref name=\"Bristolwebsitechancellor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/chancellor.html|title=Bristol University|work=Chancellor's biography|accessdate=13 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607210701/http://bristol.ac.uk/university/chancellor.html|archivedate=7 June 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| vice_chancellor  = [[Hugh Brady (academic)|Hugh Brady]]\n| head_label       = Visitor\n| head             = [[Lord President of the Council|The Lord President of the Council]] ''[[ex officio]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page49.asp |title=Institutions for which the President of the Council acts as Visitor |accessdate=20 December 2007 |publisher=Privy Council Office |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121215029/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page49.asp |archivedate=21 November 2007 }}</ref>\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| city             = [[Bristol]]\n| country          = England\n| coor             = {{Coord|51|27|23|N|02|36|16|W|display=inline,title|type:edu}}\n| campus           = Urban\n|free_label        = Students' Union\n|free              = [[University of Bristol Union]]\n| colours          = {{color box|#b01c2e}} Pantone 187<ref name=\"vis-ident\"/>\n| website          = [http://www.bristol.ac.uk/ bristol.ac.uk]\n| logo             = [[File:University of Bristol logo.svg|250px]]\n| staff            = 6,199<ref name=\"UoBFigures\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/ |title=University of Bristol Facts & Figures |accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref>\n| affiliations     = [[Russell Group]]<br /> [[Coimbra Group]]<br /> [[Worldwide Universities Network]]<br />[[Universities UK]]<br/>[[Partnership of a European Group of Aeronautics and Space Universities|PEGASUS]]<br />[[SETsquared]]<br />[[GW4]] <br /> [[Sutton 13]] <br />\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Bristol''' is a [[Red brick university|red brick]] [[research university]] in [[Bristol]], England.<ref name=\"BristolwebsiteMap\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/maps/precinct.html|title=Maps and Guides|work=The University precinct map|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> It received its [[royal charter]] in 1909,<ref name=\"Bristolwebsite\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/acts.html|title=The University of Bristol Acts|work=The University of Bristol Act 1909|accessdate=13 May 2007}}</ref> although it can trace its roots to a [[Society of Merchant Venturers|Merchant Venturers]]' school founded in 1595 and [[University College, Bristol]], which had been in existence since 1876.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/history/|title=Bristol University History |work=History of the University|accessdate=13 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nBristol is organised into [[University of Bristol#Academic structure|six academic faculties]] composed of multiple schools and departments running over 200 undergraduate courses, largely in the [[Tyndalls Park]] area of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/study/undergraduate/study-at-bristol/our-degrees/|title=About our courses - Study at Bristol - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref> The university had a total income of \u00a3642.7 million in 2017-18, of which \u00a3164.0 million was from research grants and contracts.<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\">{{cite web | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/media-library/sites/finance/documents/annual-report-financial-statements-2018.pdf | title = Financial Statements for the Year to 31 July 2018 | accessdate = 2 December 2018 | publisher = University of Bristol| page = 42}}</ref> It is the largest independent employer in Bristol.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/| title = Key Facts and Figures| accessdate =12 January 2014| year = 2014| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Bristol is ranked 49th by the [[QS World University Rankings]] 2020, and is ranked in the top 10 of UK universities in 2020 by [[QS World University Rankings|QS World University rankings]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020|title=QS World University Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=QS Top Universities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|Times Higher Education]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings|date=2019-08-20|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> and [[Academic Ranking of World Universities|ARWU]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/arwu2019.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2019 {{!}} Academic Ranking of World Universities 2019 {{!}} Top 1000 universities {{!}} Shanghai Ranking - 2019|website=www.shanghairanking.com|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> The University of Bristol was the second most targeted university by the UK's top 100 employers, according to the Graduate Market in 2019 report produced by High Fliers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAn extremely selective institution, it has an average of 6.4 (Sciences faculty) to 13.1 (Medicine & Dentistry Faculty) applicants for each undergraduate place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/|title=Facts and figures - About the University - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref>  It was ranked 9th in the UK among multi-faculty institutions for the quality (GPA) of its research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/Attachments/2014/12/17/k/a/s/over-14-01.pdf|title=Research Excellence Framework results 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and for its Research Power in the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]].<ref>{{cite news|title=REF 2014 results|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/ng-interactive/2014/dec/18/university-research-excellence-framework-2014-full-rankings|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nCurrent academics include 21 fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]], 13 fellows of the [[British Academy]], 13 fellows of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] and 44 fellows of the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Nobel Prizes and Fellowships|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=2 May 2015|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/distinctions}}</ref> The university has been associated with 13 Nobel laureates throughout its history, including [[Paul Dirac]], [[William Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]], [[Cecil Frank Powell]], [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]], [[Dorothy Hodgkin]], [[Hans Albrecht Bethe]], [[Max Delbr\u00fcck]], [[Gerhard Herzberg]], [[Sir Nevill Francis Mott]], [[Sir Paul Nurse]], [[Harold Pinter]], [[Jean-Marie Gustave Le Cl\u00e9zio]] and most recently, 2015 Economics Nobel Prize winner [[Angus Deaton]].\n\nBristol is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of research-intensive British universities,<ref>{{cite web|title=Russell Group Our Universities|url=http://www.russellgroup.ac.uk/our-universities/|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> the European-wide [[Coimbra Group]]<ref name=\"CoimbraGroup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coimbra-group.eu/index.php?page=members|title=The Coimbra Group|work=List of Coimbra Group Members|accessdate=14 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502062025/http://www.coimbra-group.eu/index.php?page=members|archivedate=2 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[Worldwide Universities Network]], of which the university's previous vice-chancellor, [[Eric Thomas (academic)|Eric Thomas]], was chairman from 2005 to 2007.<ref name=\"WUN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wun.ac.uk/|title=The Worldwide Universities Network|work=List of WUN Group Members|accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref> In addition, the university holds an [[Erasmus Programme|Erasmus Charter]], sending more than 500 students per year to partner institutions in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/global/partnerships/|title=Our research impact - Research - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of the University of Bristol}}\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe earliest antecedent of the university was the engineering department of the [[Merchant Venturers' Technical College]] (founded as a school as early as 1595) which became the engineering faculty of Bristol University.<ref>{{cite web|author=United Kingdom |url=http://www.merchantventurers.com/charitable-activities/education.html |title=Education \u2013 The Society of Merchant Venturers, Bristol UK |publisher=Merchantventurers.com |accessdate=5 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829092557/http://merchantventurers.com/charitable-activities/education.html |archivedate=29 August 2009 }}</ref> The university was also preceded by [[Bristol Medical School]] (1833) and [[University College, Bristol]], founded in 1876,<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> where its first lecture was attended by only 99 students.<ref>{{cite news | title = University of Bristol |work=The Guardian  | date = 1 May 2007 | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/universityguide/profile/story/0,,478329,00.html | location=London}}</ref> The university was able to apply for a [[royal charter]] due to the financial support of the [[W. D. & H. O. Wills|Wills]], [[Fry family (chocolate)|Fry]] and Colston families, who made their fortunes in tobacco plantations, chocolate, and (via [[Edward Colston]]) the transatlantic slave trade, respectively. A 2018 study commissioned by the university estimated 85% of the philanthropic funds used for the institution's foundation was directly connected with the transatlantic slave trade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/university/history/past-matters/|title=Past Matters: the University of Bristol and transatlantic slavery|work=University of Bristol|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe royal charter was gained in May 1909, with 288 undergraduates and 400 other students entering the university in October 1909. [[Henry Overton Wills III]] became its first chancellor.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> The University College was the first such institution in the country to [[Mixed-sex education|admit women on the same basis as men]].<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> However, women were forbidden to take examinations in medicine until 1906.<ref name=\"archives-hub\">{{cite web|title=Papers of the University of Bristol |publisher=Archives Hub |accessdate=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/news/03121903.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229151955/http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/03121903.html|archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Historical development ===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#ffffoo; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\nThere shall be from henceforth for ever in Our said City of Bristol a University...\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]], Charter of Incorporation of the University of Bristol, 4 December 1909<ref name=\"charter\">{{cite web | title = Charter of Incorporation | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/charter.html|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070930183415/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/charter.html |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref>\n|}\nSince the founding of the university itself in 1909, it has grown considerably and is now one of the largest employers in the local area, although it is smaller by student numbers than the nearby [[University of the West of England]].<ref name=\"HESA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls |title=Table 0a \u2013 All students by institution, mode of study, level of study, gender and domicile 2006/07 |accessdate=5 April 2008 |format=[[Microsoft Excel]] spreadsheet |publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709132444/http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls |archivedate= 9 July 2013 }}</ref> Bristol does not have a campus but is spread over a considerable geographic area. Most of its activities, however, are concentrated in the area of the city centre, referred to as the \"University Precinct\". It is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of research-led UK universities, the [[Coimbra Group]] of leading European universities and the [[Worldwide Universities Network]] (WUN).\n\n==== Early years ====\n[[File:university of bristol tower after cleaning arp.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Wills Memorial Building]] (Schools of Law and Earth Sciences) on [[Park Street, Bristol]]. The tower was cleaned in 2006\u20132007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2006/875.html|publisher= Bristol University | title=Wills Tower set for new glory|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>]]\nAfter the founding of the University College in 1876, Government support began in 1889. After mergers with the Bristol Medical School in 1893 and the Merchant Venturers' Technical College in 1909,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol |accessdate=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.history-ontheweb.co.uk/uni/bristol.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213091650/http://www.history-ontheweb.co.uk/uni/bristol.htm |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref> this funding allowed the opening of a new medical school and an engineering school\u2014two subjects that remain among the university's greatest strengths. In 1908, gifts from the [[Fry Family (Chocolate)|Fry]] and Wills families, particularly \u00a3100,000 from [[Henry Overton Wills III]] (\u00a36m in today's money), were provided to endow a University for Bristol and the West of England, provided that a [[royal charter]] could be obtained within two years. In December 1909, the King granted such a charter and erected the University of Bristol.<ref name=\"charter\" /> Henry Wills became its first [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]] and [[Conwy Lloyd Morgan]] the first vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"past-officers\">{{cite web | title = Bristol University \u2013 Former Officers | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =22 June 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/formerofficers.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927233714/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/formerofficers.html |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref> Wills died in 1911 and in tribute his sons [[George Alfred Wills|George]] and [[Henry Herbert Wills|Harry]] built the [[Wills Memorial Building]], starting in 1913 and finally finishing in 1925.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wills Memorial Building |url=http://www.bristol-link.co.uk/history/wills-memorial-building.htm |publisher=Bristol Link |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Today, it houses parts of the academic provision for [[earth sciences]] and law, and graduation ceremonies are held in its Great Hall. The Wills Memorial Building is a Grade II* listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=University Tower and Wills Memorial Building and attached front walls and lamps |accessdate=6 December 2007 |num=1218203 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1920, George Wills bought the [[Victoria Rooms (Bristol)|Victoria Rooms]] and endowed them to the university as a [[Students' Union]].<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" />\nThe building now houses the Department of Music and is a Grade II* listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Victoria Rooms and attached railings and gates |accessdate=6 December 2007 |num=1202480 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:King's College London Students Evacuated To Bristol, England, 1940 D433.jpg|thumbnail|left|Evacuated [[King's College London]] students at the University of Bristol in 1940]]\nAt the point of foundation, the university was required to provide for the local community. This mission was behind the creation of the Department of Extra-Mural Adult Education in 1924 to provide courses to the local community. This mission continues today; a new admissions policy specifically caters to the 'BS' [[UK postcodes|postcode]] area of [[Bristol]].<ref name=\"admit-policy\">{{cite web|title=Undergraduate admissions principles and procedures (Home/EU students)|publisher=Bristol University|accessdate=8 August 2013|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/governance/policies/admissions/home-overseas.html}}</ref>\n\nAmong the famous names associated with Bristol in this early period is [[Paul Dirac]], who graduated in 1921 with a degree in engineering, before obtaining a second degree in mathematics in 1923 from Cambridge. For his subsequent pioneering work on quantum mechanics, he was awarded the 1933 Nobel Prize for Physics.<ref>{{cite web | title = Notable alumni \u2013 Faculty of Engineering | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url =http://www.alumni.bristol.ac.uk/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?&pid=280&srcid=190}}</ref> Later in the 1920s, the H.H. Wills Physics Laboratory was opened by [[Ernest Rutherford]].<ref>{{cite web | title = History of the Department | publisher = Department of Physics, University of Bristol | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.phy.bristol.ac.uk/history.html}}</ref> It has since housed several Nobel Prize winners: [[Cecil Frank Powell]] (1950);<ref>{{cite web | title = The Nobel Prize in Physics 1950 | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1950/}}</ref> [[Hans Albrecht Bethe]] (1967);<ref>{{cite web | title = Hans Bethe \u2013 Biography | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1967/bethe-bio.html}}</ref> and Sir [[Nevill Francis Mott]] (1977).<ref>{{cite web | title = Sir Nevill F. Mott | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1977/mott-bio.html}}</ref> The Laboratory stands on the same site today, close to the [[Bristol Grammar School]] and the city museum.\n\n[[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]] became the university's third chancellor in 1929, serving the university in that capacity until 1965.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> He succeeded [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Richard Haldane]] who had held the office from 1912 following the death of Henry Wills.<ref name=\"archives-hub\" /><ref name=\"past-officers\" />\n\nDuring World War II, the Wills Memorial was bombed, destroying the Great Hall and the organ it housed,<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> along with 7,000 books removed from [[King's College London]] for safe keeping.  It has since been restored to its former glory, complete with oak panelled walls and a new organ.\n\n==== Post-war development ====\n\nIn 1946, the university established the first drama department in the country.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> In the same year, Bristol began offering special entrance [[exam]]s and [[Grant (money)|grants]] to aid the resettlement of servicemen returning home. Student numbers continued to increase, and the Faculty of Engineering eventually needed the new premises that were to become Queen's Building in 1955. This substantial building housed all of the university's engineers until 1996, when the department of [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Department of Computer Science, University of Bristol|Department of Computer Science]] moved over the road into the new Merchant Venturers' Building to make space for these rapidly expanding fields. Today, Queen's Building caters for most of the teaching needs of the Faculty and provides academic space for the \"heavy\" engineering subjects ([[civil engineering|civil]], [[mechanical engineering|mechanical]], and [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace]]).\n\nWith unprecedented growth in the 1960s, particularly in undergraduate numbers, the Students' Union eventually acquired larger premises in a new building in the [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] area of the city, in 1965. This building was more spacious than the Victoria Rooms, which were now given over to the Department of Music. The [[University of Bristol Union|new Union]] provides many practice and performance rooms, some specialist rooms, as well as three bars: Bar 100; the Mandela (also known as AR2) and the Avon Gorge. Whilst spacious, the Union building is thought by many to be ugly<ref>{{cite web | title = The Students' Union | publisher = University of Bristol Union | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/union/altprospectus/unilife/union |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126124416/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/union/altprospectus/unilife/union |archivedate = 26 November 2007}}</ref> and out of character compared to the architecture of the rest of the Clifton area, having been mentioned in a [[BBC]] poll to find the worst architectural eyesores in Britain.<ref>{{cite news | title = What is the worst eyesore in the UK? |work=BBC News | date = 21 November 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/3266673.stm}}</ref> The university has proposed relocating the Union to a more central location as part of its development 'masterplan'.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Bristol Strategic Masterplan | publisher = University of Bristol | page = 64 | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Bursar/masterplan06/1masterplan.pdf |date=July 2006 }}</ref> More recently, plans for redevelopment of the current building have been proposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ubu.org.uk/build |title=Building Project \u2013 A Better Building for the Students' Union |publisher=Ubu.org.uk |accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe 1960s were a time of considerable student activism in the United Kingdom, and Bristol was no exception. In 1968, many students marched in support of the [[Anderson Report (British Education)|Anderson Report]], which called for higher student grants. This discontent culminated in an 11-day sit-in at the Senate House (the administrative headquarters of the university).<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> A series of chancellors and vice-chancellors led the university through these decades, with [[Henry Somerset, 10th Duke of Beaufort]] taking over from Churchill as chancellor in 1965 before being succeeded by [[Dorothy Hodgkin]] in 1970 who spent the next 18 years in the office.<ref name=\"past-officers\" />\n\nAs the age of mass higher education dawned, Bristol continued to build its student numbers. The various undergraduate residences were repeatedly expanded and, more recently, some postgraduate residences have been constructed. These more recent ventures have been funded (and are run) by external companies in agreement with the university.\n\nSince 1988, there have been only three further chancellors; Sir [[Jeremy Morse]], then chairman of [[Lloyds Bank (historic)|Lloyds Bank]] who handed over in 2003 to [[Brenda Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond|Brenda Hale]], the first female [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary|Law Lord]].<ref name=\"archives-hub\" /><ref name=\"past-officers\" /> [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]] succeeded Lady Hale as Chancellor on 1 January 2017.\n\n[[File:Victoria Rooms (750px).jpg|thumb|The Victoria Rooms, housing the School of Music]]\nOne of the few [[Centre for Deaf Studies, Bristol|Centres for Deaf Studies]] in the United Kingdom was established in Bristol in 1981, followed in 1988 by the Norah Fry Centre for research into learning difficulties. Also in 1988, and again in 2004,<ref>{{cite news| title = Students' union breaks from NUS| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/3463995.stm|work=BBC News| date = 5 February 2004| accessdate =20 December 2007}}</ref> the Students' Union AGM voted to disaffiliate from the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] (NUS). On both occasions, however, the subsequent referendum of all students reversed that decision and Bristol remains affiliated to the NUS.\n\nIn 2002, the university was involved in an argument over press intrusion after details of then-prime minister [[Tony Blair]]'s son's application to university were published in national newspapers.\n\nAs the number of postgraduate students has grown (particularly the numbers pursuing taught master's degrees), there eventually became a need for separate representation on university bodies and the Postgraduate Union (PGU) was established in 2000.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.pgu.org.uk/yourpgu/| title = General introduction of the PGU| accessdate =20 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol Postgraduate Union|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227191758/http://www.pgu.org.uk/yourpgu/ |archivedate = 27 December 2007}}</ref>\nUniversities are increasingly expected to exploit the intellectual property generated by their research activities and, in 2000, Bristol established the Research and Enterprise Division (RED) to further this cause (particularly for technology-based businesses). In 2001, the university signed a 25-year research funding deal with IP2IPO, an intellectual property commercialisation company.<ref>{{cite news | title = Bristol signs commercial research funding deal |work=The Guardian  | author = Donald MacLeod | date = 5 December 2005 | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/businessofresearch/story/0,,1658169,00.html | location=London}}</ref> In 2007, research activities were expanded further with the opening of the Advanced Composites Centre for Innovation and Science (ACCIS) and The Bristol Institute for Public Affairs (BIPA).\n\nIn 2002, the university opened the new Centre for Sports, Exercise and Health in the heart of the university precinct.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/about/| title = Bristol University \u2013 Centre for Sport, Exercise &amp; Health \u2013 About us| accessdate = 20 December 2007| date = 2 October 2007| publisher = University of Bristol| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071030093119/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/about/| archivedate = 30 October 2007| df = dmy-all}}</ref> At a cost, local residents are also able to use the facilities.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/community| title = Bristol University \u2013 Centre for Sport, Exercise &amp; Health \u2013 community programmes| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 28 September 2007| publisher = University of Bristol|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126122458/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/community |archivedate = 26 November 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Bristol University from Cabot Tower.jpg|thumb|left|Most of the buildings here are used by the university. The [[Wills Memorial Building]] is left of centre. Viewed from the [[Cabot Tower (Bristol)|Cabot Tower]] on Brandon Hill]]\nExpansion of teaching and research activities continues. In 2004, the Faculty of Engineering completed work on the Bristol Laboratory for Advanced Dynamics Engineering (BLADE). This \u00a318.5m project<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/gallery/places/blade.html| title = Places \u2013 BLADE| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 20 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181805/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/gallery/places/blade.html |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref> is intended to further the study of dynamics and is the most advanced such facility in Europe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Saouma |first1=Victor |last2=Sivaselvan |first2=Mettupalayam |title=Hybrid Simulation: Theory, Implementation and Applications |date=2014 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=9781482288612 |page=217 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=HUtZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=Bristol+Laboratory+for+Advanced+Dynamics+Engineering+(BLADE)+advanced+Europe#v=onepage&q=Bristol%20Laboratory%20for%20Advanced%20Dynamics%20Engineering%20(BLADE)%20advanced%20Europe&f=false}}</ref> It was built as an extension to the Queen's Building and was officially opened by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] in March 2005.\n\nIn January 2005, the School of Chemistry was awarded \u00a34.5m by the [[Higher Education Funding Council for England]] to create Bristol ChemLabS: a Centre for Excellence in Teaching & Learning (CETL),<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.chm.bristol.ac.uk/whatsnew/cetl.htm| title = CETL \u2013 A\u00a314M Boost for Teaching and Learning in Bristol Chemistry \u2013 27/01/05| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 14 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref> with an additional \u00a3350k announced for the capital part of the project in February 2006. Bristol ChemLabS stands for Bristol Chemical Laboratory Sciences; it is the only chemistry CETL in the UK.\n\nSeptember 2009 saw the opening of the university's [[Centre for Nanoscience and Quantum Information]]. This \u00a311 million building is known as the quietest building in the world{{clarify|date=March 2020}} and has other technologically sophisticated features such as self-cleaning glass. Advanced research into quantum computing, nanotechnology, materials and other disciplines are being undertaken in the building.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2009/6531.html| title = 'Quietest' building in the world opens today | accessdate =15 September 2011| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a plan to significantly redevelop the centre of the University Precinct in the coming years.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Bursar/masterplan.html| title = University of Bristol Masterplan| accessdate =20 December 2007| last = Bowden| first = Chris| date = 10 September 2007| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref> The first step began in September 2011, with the start of construction of a state-of-the-art Life Sciences building.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2011/7931.html| title = New \u00a350 million University building to transform a key area of Bristol | accessdate =21 October 2011| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 while building work was underway in the [[Fry Building]],<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Bristol: Fry Building|url=http://www.wilkinsoneyre.com/projects/university-of-bristol-fry-building|publisher=WilkinsonEyre|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Work to create \u00a333 million mathematics building gets underway|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2016/march/fry-building.html|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> the building caught fire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bristol University fire: Live updates as Fry building undergoing major refurb goes up in flames with smoke seen across city|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/park-street-fire-live-updates-1021777|accessdate=6 January 2018|work=Bristol Post|date=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol University fire: Crews tackle campus blaze|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-42591375|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2003 admissions controversy ====\n\n{{Main|University of Bristol admissions controversy}}\n\nThe university has been regarded as being [[elitist]] by some commentators,<ref>{{cite news|title =Elite uni aims to broaden its appeal|work=BBC News|accessdate =12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/1768564.stm | date=18 January 2002\n}}</ref> taking 41% of its undergraduate students from non-state schools, according to the most recent 2009/2010 figures, despite the fact that such pupils make up just 7% of the population<ref>{{cite web |title=Understated |publisher=Etan Smallman: Epigram Online |accessdate=12 December 2007 |url=http://www.epigram.org.uk/view.php?id=1583 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215155/http://www.epigram.org.uk/view.php?id=1583 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and 18% of 16+ year old pupils across the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isc.co.uk/FactsFigures_PupilNumbers.htm |title=ISC Pupil Numbers \u2013 Independent Schools Council |publisher=Isc.co.uk |accessdate=21 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118083844/http://www.isc.co.uk/FactsFigures_PupilNumbers.htm |archivedate=18 January 2012 }}</ref> The intake of state school pupils at Bristol is lower than many Oxbridge colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/oxford-drops-below-cambridge-on-state-school-entrants/2012321.article|title=Oxford drops below Cambridge on state school entrants|date=27 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The high ratio of undergraduates from non-state school has led to some tension at the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetartpaper.com/articles/view/369 |title=The sad side of Bristol Uni |publisher=Thetartpaper.com |accessdate=28 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719012104/http://www.thetartpaper.com/articles/view/369 |archivedate=19 July 2009 }}</ref> In late February and early March 2003, Bristol became embroiled in a row about admissions policies, with some private schools threatening a boycott<ref>{{cite news|title=Private schools 'boycott' Bristol\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/2818263.stm | date=4 March 2003}}</ref> based on their claims that, in an effort to improve equality of access, the university was discriminating against their students. These claims were hotly denied by the university.<ref>{{cite news| title =Bristol remains firm on admissions\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/3014108.stm | date=23 June 2003}}</ref>\nIn August 2005, following a large-scale survey, the [[Independent Schools Council]] publicly acknowledged that there was no evidence of bias against applicants from the schools it represented.<ref>{{cite news|title='No bias' against private pupils\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4161100.stm | date=17 August 2005}}</ref>\nThe university has a new admissions policy,<ref name=\"admit-policy\" /> which lays out in considerable detail the basis on which any greater or lesser weight may be given to particular parts of an applicant's backgrounds&nbsp;\u2013 in particular, what account may be taken of which school the applicant hails from. This new policy also encourages greater participation from locally resident applicants.\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:QEH Prize Day 2004.JPG|thumb|200px|The Great Hall of the [[Wills Memorial Building]], here used for an award ceremony for the [[Queen Elizabeth's Hospital]]]]\n<!-- [[File:Willsmemorial.JPG|thumb|right|200px|The armorials on the [[Wills Memorial Building]] and some of the grotesques, the later designed by [[Jean Hahn]] which portray some of the then university staff.<ref>Carleton (1984), p130</ref>]] -->\nSome of the University of Bristol's buildings date to its pre-charter days when it was [[University College Bristol]]. These buildings were designed by [[Charles Hansom]], the younger brother of [[Joseph Hansom]], Joseph being the inventor of the [[Hansom Cab]]. These buildings suffered being built in stages due to financial pressure. George Oatley added to them a tower in memory of Albert Fry which can still be seen on University Road. The first large scale building project the University of Bristol undertook on gaining a charter was the Wills Memorial Building which it was hoped would be a symbol of academic permanence for the university and a memorial to the chief benefactor of the university, [[Henry Overton Wills]]. It was requested to the architect [[George Oatley]] that the building be built to last at least 400 years but the site purchased, at the top of [[Park Street, Bristol|Park Street]] suffered from an awkward slope and a desirability to link the building with the Museum and Art Gallery situated adjacent to the plot. The architecture critic [[Roger Gill (architecture critic)|Roger Gill]] has stated that the building is \"remarkable in size\" but noted that the \"ambience of a medieval University was strangely lacking\". He goes on to criticise the building as a \"sham\" and a \"folly\".<ref>Carleton (1984), p129</ref> The armorials on the Founder's Window represent all of the interests present at the founding of the University of Bristol including the Wills and Fry families. The [[Tyndalls Park]] Estate and [[Royal Fort House]] were also purchased from the trustees of the Tyndall family allowing the university to expand. Many Departments in the Faculty of Arts are housed in large Victorian houses which have been converted for teaching.<ref>Higher Education Quality Council (1993), p2</ref>\n\n[[Goldney gardens]] entered the property of the University of Bristol through [[George Alfred Wills|George Wills]] who had hoped to build an all-male hall of residence there. This was prevented due to the moral objection of the then warden of Clifton Hall House who objected to the idea of male and female residences being in such close proximity. University records show that Miss Starvey was prepared to resign over the issue and that she had the support of the then Chancellor [[Conwy Lloyd Morgan]].<ref>Carleton (1984), p132</ref> Eventually land was purchased in [[Stoke Bishop]] allowing [[Wills Hall]] to be bought, allowing the building of what has been described as a \"quasi-[[Oxbridge]]\" hall, to which was added the Dame Monica Wills Chapel by George Wills' widow after his death. [[File:Goldney2.jpg|thumb|200px|The Gardens of Goldney Hall were acquired by the Wills family]]Burwalls, a mansion house on the other side of the [[Avon Gorge]], was used as a halls of residence in the past and was a home of [[Sir George Oatley]]. The building is now used to house the Centre for Continuing Education.<ref name=\"burwalls\">{{cite web | title =Burwalls Centre for Continuing Education| publisher = University of Bristol |accessdate =16 June 2008 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/burwalls/}}</ref>\n\nMany of the more modern buildings, including Senate House and the newer parts of the HH Wills Physics Laboratory, were designed by [[Ralph Brentnall]] after funds from the University Grants Committee. He is also responsible for the extension to the Wills Memorial Building library which was completed to such standard that few now realise that is an extension to the original building.<ref>Carleton (1984), p138</ref> Brentnall oversaw the rebuilding of the Great Hall of the Wills Memorial Building after it was partly destroyed during the [[Bristol Blitz]] of World War II. The buildings of St Michael's Hill were rebuilt using hundreds of old photographs to recreate the original houses. The flats at Goldney Hall were designed by Michael Grice and received an award from the Civic Trust for their design.<ref>Carleton (1984), p139</ref> Bristol University owns some of the best examples of Georgian architecture in the city, the best examples being [[Royal Fort House]], [[Clifton Hill House]] and [[Goldney Hall]] despite some additions.<ref>Carleton (1984), p141</ref> The Victoria Rooms which house the Music Department were designed by [[Charles Dyer (architect)|Charles Dyer]] and is seen as a good example of a Greek revival movement in British architecture. The [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] of the building depicts a scene from ''The Advent of Morning'' designed by [[Jabez Tyley]].<ref>Carleton (1984), p136</ref> Its major feature was a large organ which has since been destroyed by fire.\n\nIn November 2016, the university announced that it plans to build a \u00a3300 million Temple Quarter Campus for c. 5,000 students, next to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station]] within [[Bristol Temple Quarter Enterprise Zone]]. The new campus, which will include a [[business school]], digital research facilities and a student village, is expected to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/bristol-university-to-take-over-royal-mail-sorting-offices-by-temple-meads-for-new-300m-campus/story-29935566-detail/story.html |newspaper=[[Bristol Post]] |title=Bristol University to take over old sorting office by Temple Meads for new \u00a3300m campus |last=Yong |first=Michael |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=29 November 2016 }}</ref> For the existing campus, there are plans to remodel Tyndall Avenue, pedestrianise the surrounding area and build a new library and resource hub.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/media-library/sites/university/documents/governance/policies/university-strategy.pdf |title= Brochure |website= www.bristol.ac.uk|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation and governance ==\n\n{{Main|Governance of the University of Bristol}}\nIn common with most UK universities, Bristol is headed formally by the [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]], currently [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]] and led on a day-to-day basis by the [[vice-chancellor]], currently [[Hugh R. Brady|Hugh Brady]], who is the academic leader and chief executive. There are four pro vice-chancellors and three ceremonial pro-chancellors.<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|title=Governance: How the University is run|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/governance\n}}</ref> The chancellor may hold office for up to ten years and the pro-chancellors for up to three, unless the University Court determines otherwise,<ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 3 \u2013 The Chancellor | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 15 March 2000 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat3.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 4 \u2013 The Pro-Chancellors | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat4.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000416/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat4.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> but the vice-chancellor and pro-vice-chancellors have no term limits.<ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 5 \u2013 The Vice-Chancellor | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 15 March 2000 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat5.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000417/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat5.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 6 \u2013 The Pro Vice-Chancellors | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 24 February 2004 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat6.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000422/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat6.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The vice-chancellor is supported by a deputy vice-chancellor.\n\nResponsibility for running the university is held at an executive level by the vice-chancellor, but the council is the only body that can recommend changes to the university's statutes and charter,<ref name=\"council\">{{cite web| title=Council|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/council/\n}}</ref> with the exception of academic ordinances. These can only be made with the consent of the senate, the chief academic body in the university which also holds responsibility for teaching and learning, examinations and research and enterprise.<ref name=\"council\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Senate | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/senate/}}</ref> The chancellor and pro chancellors are nominated by council and appointed formally by court, whose additional powers are now limited to these appointments and a few others, including some lay members of council.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statute 13 \u2013 Powers of Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 7 May 2005 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat13.html\n}}</ref> Finally, Convocation, the body of all staff, ceremonial officers and graduates of the university, returns 100 members to court and one member to council,<ref name=\"gov\" /> but is otherwise principally a forum for discussion and to ensure graduates stay in touch with the university.\n\nThe university is made up of a number of schools and departments organised into six faculties:<ref>{{cite web | title = Academic Departments and Research Centres by Faculty | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =10 August 2007| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/index/faculties/}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wills memorial library.JPG|thumb|right|The Wills Memorial Library of Law and Earth Sciences]]\n\n=== Faculty of Arts ===\n* School of Arts\n** Anthropology and Archaeology\n** Film and Television\n** Music\n** Philosophy\n** Theatre (see also the [[University of Bristol Theatre Collection]])\n* School of Humanities\n** Classics and Ancient History\n** English\n** History (Historical Studies)\n** History of Art (Historical Studies)\n** Religion and Theology\n* School of Modern Languages\n** French\n** German\n** Hispanic, Portuguese and Latin American Studies\n** Italian\n** Russian\n* Centre for English Language and Foundation Studies\n* Centre for Innovation\n\n=== Faculty of Engineering ===\n* School of Computer Science, Electrical and Electronic Engineering, and Engineering Mathematics\n** Computer Science\n** Electrical & Electronic Engineering\n** Engineering Mathematics\n* School of Civil, Aerospace and Mechanical Engineering\n** Aerospace Engineering\n** Civil Engineering\n** Mechanical Engineering\n\n[[File:UniversityofBristolEngineering.JPG|thumb|Faculty of Engineering Queen's Building]]\n\n=== Faculty of Life Sciences ===\n* School of Biological Sciences\n* School of Biochemistry\n* School of Cellular and Molecular Medicine\n* School of Physiology, Pharmacology and Neuroscience\n* School of Psychological Science\n\n[[File:University of Bristol, School of Chemistry.jpg|thumb|right|School of Chemistry]]\n\n=== Faculty of Science ===\n* School of Chemistry\n* School of Earth Sciences\n* School of Geographical Sciences\n* School of Mathematics\n* School of Physics\n** Interface Analysis Centre\n** Centre for Nanoscience & Quantum Information\n\n=== Faculty of Health Sciences ===\n* Bristol Dental School\n* Bristol Medical School\n** Population Health Sciences\n** Translational Health Sciences\n* Bristol Veterinary School\n* Centre for Health Sciences Education\n** Centre for Applied Anatomy\n** Master's in Teaching and Learning for Health Professionals\n\n=== Faculty of Social Sciences and Law ===\n* School of Education\n* School for Policy Studies\n* School of Economics, Finance and Management\n** Accounting and Finance\n** Centre for Market and Public Organisation\n** Economics\n** Management\n* School of Sociology, Politics and International Studies\n* University of Bristol Law School\n\n=== Academic dress ===\n{{Main|Academic dress of the University of Bristol}}\n[[File:UOB Masters hood.jpg|thumb|upright|Master's hood at the University of Bristol]]\nThe university specifies a mix of Cambridge and Oxford [[academic dress]]. For the most part, it uses Oxford-style gowns and Cambridge-style hoods, which are required to be 'university red'<ref name=\"costume\">{{cite web | title = Regulations for Academic and Official Costume | publisher = University of Bristol Regulations for Academic and Official Costume |accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/regscostume.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126123449/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/regscostume.html |archivedate = 26 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> (see the logo at the top of the page).\n\n=== Logo and arms ===\n[[File:UniversityofBristollogo2.jpg|thumb|upright|University coat of arms]]\nIn 2004, the university unveiled its new crest. The icons in the crest are the sun for the Wills family, the dolphin for Colston, the horse for Fry and the ship-and-castle from the medieval seal of the City of Bristol, as also used in the coat of arms. The shape of the whole crest represents the open book of learning.<ref name=\"vis-ident\">{{cite web | title =  University of Bristol logo | publisher =  University of Bristol | accessdate =  2007-12-03 | url =  http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/logo.html | url-status =  dead | archiveurl =  https://web.archive.org/web/20071013010817/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/logo.html | archivedate =  13 October 2007 | df =  dmy-all }}</ref> This crest has replaced the university [[Coat of arms|arms]] shown, but the arms continue to be used where there is a specific historical or ceremonial requirement. The arms comprise:\n<center>\n''argent on a cross quadrate gules the arms of the City of Bristol between in pale and a sun in splendour (for Wills) and an open book proper, leaved and clasped or, and inscribed with the words Nisi quia Dominus, and in fesse to the sinister a dolphin embowed (for Colston), and to the dexter a horse courant (for Fry), both of the third.''\n</center>\nThe inscription on the book is the [[Latin]] opening of the 124th Psalm, ''\"If the Lord Himself had not (been on our side...)\"''.<ref name=\"arms\">{{cite web | title = The University Arms | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/arms.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927234000/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/arms.html | archivedate = 27 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Academic profile ==\n\n=== Admissions ===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ UCAS Admission Statistics\n!\n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|43,355\n|43,930\n|43,465\n|40,425\n|39,680\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate (%)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: B78 University of Bristol|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144926/download?token=Pkxxg1hu|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|71.3\n|69.4\n|67.3\n|70.6\n|61.8\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|5,790\n|5,530\n|5,385\n|5,165\n|4,810\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield (%)''']]\n|18.7\n|18.1\n|18.4\n|18.1\n|19.6\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|7.49\n|7.94\n|8.07\n|7.83\n|8.25\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">New [[UCAS Tariff]] system from 2016</ref>\n|n/a\n|184\n|485\n|476\n|486\n|}\nBristol had the 8th highest average entry qualification for undergraduates of any UK university in 2015, with new students averaging 485 [[UCAS Tariff|UCAS points]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards|website=Complete University Guide|title=University League Table 2018|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> equivalent to just above AAAaa in [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A-level]] grades. Competition for places is high with an average 7.7 applications per place according to the 2014 Sunday Times League Tables, making it the joint 11th most competitive university in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/table/year/2014/type/derived/id/111|title=The Times and The Sunday Times - Education - Table UniversityGuide|last=HitCreative|website=st.hitcreative.com}}</ref> The university gives offers of admission to 67.3% of its applicants, the 8th lowest amongst the [[Russell Group]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Which elite universities have the highest offer rates |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2016/10/19/which-elite-universities-have-the-highest-offer-rates/|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2017 ''Times'' and ''Sunday Times'' Good University Guide, approximately 40% of Bristol's undergraduates come from independent schools.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://extras.thetimes.co.uk/gooduniversityguide/institutions/ |title=The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide 2017|work=[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|The Good University Guide]] | location=London | accessdate=16 August 2016}}{{paywall}}</ref> In the 2016-17 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 78:5:17 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 55:45.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings and reputation===\n\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_W       = 74\n| QS_W         = 49\n| THE_W        = 87\n| LEIDEN_W     = 37\n| LINE_1       = 0\n| Complete     = 16\n| The_Guardian = 23\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 15\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Silver\n}}\nBristol is ranked in the top 10 universities in the UK in various university rankings including: QS World University Rankings, ARWU and Times Higher Education University Rankings.<ref name=\"Old school 'key to student place'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7003253.stm|title=Old school 'key to student place'|publisher=BBC |accessdate=31 January 2009 | date=20 September 2007}}</ref> Internationally, the 2020 [[QS World University Rankings]] placed Bristol at 49th overall in the world and 9th in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020|title=QS World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|website=|publisher=Topuniversities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> The 2020 QS World University Rankings for Graduate Employability also placed Bristol at 58th in the world and 9th in the UK in terms of reputation with employers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/employability-rankings/2020|title=Graduate Employability Rankings 2020|last=|first=|date=2019-09-10|website=Top Universities|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Bristol was chosen as the ninth best university in the UK for the quality of graduates according to recruiters from the UK's major companies.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/best-uk-universities-chosen-major-employers | location=London | work=Times Higher Education | title=The best UK universities chosen by major employers | date=12 November 2015}}</ref> The [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|Times Higher Education World University Ranking]] placed Bristol at 87th globally and 10th in the UK in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title=Times Higher Education World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|date=|work=Times Higher Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> Another international ranking, the [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]] [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]], placed Bristol 64th globally and 8th in the UK in 2019.<ref name=\"AWRU 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/arwu2019.html|title=AWRU 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> Bristol is ranked 47th in the world (and 6th in the UK) in the 2016 ''[[Round University Ranking]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roundranking.com/ranking.html|title=Round University Rankings 2016|publisher=RUR Rankings Agency|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref> The 2017 ''U.S. News & World Report'' ranks Bristol 76th in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/rankings?page=8 |title=U.S. News and World Report Best Global Universities Rankings 2017 |magazine=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref> In 2019, it ranked 120th among the universities around the world by ''[[SCImago Institutions Rankings]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?sector=Higher%20educ.&country=all|title=SCImago Institutions Rankings - Higher Education - All Regions and Countries - 2019 - Overall Rank|website=www.scimagoir.com}}</ref>\n\nWithin the UK, Bristol was ranked 10th overall in ''The Sunday Times'' 10-year (1998\u20132007) average ranking of British universities based on consistent league table performance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|title=University ranking based on performance over 10 years|work=The Times|accessdate=28 April 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414064446/http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|archivedate=14 April 2008|year=2007|location=London|df=dmy}}</ref> and is a member of the '[[Sutton Trust#Sutton Trust 13|Sutton 13]]' of top ranked Universities in the UK. According to data published in ''[[The Times|The Sunday Times]]'', Bristol has the sixth-highest percentage of \"good honours\" of any UK university.<ref>{{cite news|title=University league table|publisher =The Sunday Time|accessdate=21 December 2014|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/University_Guide/ | location=London | date=30 July 2014}}</ref> In the 2010 Centre for Higher Education's Development's Excellence Rankings, Bristol is one of only four UK universities (Oxford, UCL and Manchester) to be rated Excellent in all seven departments.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.excellenceranking.org/eusid/EUSID?module=Ort&do=show&id=12 |title=The Best European Universities |work=Die Zeit |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106004156/http://www.excellenceranking.org/eusid/EUSID?module=Ort&do=show&id=12 |archive-date=6 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The University of Bristol was the second most targeted university by the UK's top 100 employers, according to the Graduate Market in 2019 report produced by High Fliers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2019/january/high-fliers-report.html|title=January: University of Bristol is 2nd most-targeted university by employers {{!}} News {{!}} University of Bristol|last=Bristol|first=University of|website=www.bristol.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Geography Department, University of Bristol - geograph.org.uk - 201159.jpg|thumb|upright|left|School of Geographical Sciences]]\nThe following courses offered by the University of Bristol managed to reach top 5 in ''The Times'' ranking (2008): [[Department of Computer Science, University of Bristol|Computer Science]] (3rd); Electrical and Electronic Engineering(3rd); Civil Engineering(5th); Biological Sciences(3rd); Mathematics (3rd), and Psychology (4th). Furthermore, the [[QS World University Rankings]] place Bristol in the world's top 100 universities for all subject areas in 2011: Arts and Humanities (57th), Natural Sciences (40th), Engineering & IT (83rd), Social Sciences (65th) and Life Sciences (70th).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/university-bristol/wur |title=QS World University Subject Rankings for the University of Bristol |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829070204/http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/university-bristol/wur |archivedate=29 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A further breakdown of the QS World University Natural Sciences Ranking shows the following: Earth Sciences (25th),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/earth |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045139/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/earth |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mathematics (35th),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/mathematics |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045207/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/mathematics |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Environmental Sciences (39th),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/environmental-sciences|title=QS World University Rankings|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045144/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/environmental-sciences|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Physics (41st),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/physics |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522070542/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/physics |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Chemistry (48th).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/chemistry|title=QS World University Rankings|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522052050/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/chemistry|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bristol is particularly strong in the field of social sciences, particularly in economics, finance and management, and was rated fourth in the 2008 Guardian University Guide for Business and Management Studies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/efm/news/2008/16.html |title=Bristol University &#124; Bristol Ranked Fourth |publisher=Bristol.ac.uk |accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref> In 2011, ''The Guardian'' also ranked Bristol as third in the UK for geography, just behind second place Oxford<ref>{{cite news|title=Guardian University Rankings 2011 (Geography and Environmental Studies)|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2010/jun/04/university-guide-geography-and-environmental-studies|publisher=The Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=23 April 2011|location=London|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> and ranked Bristol as 1st in the UK for Music.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2011/may/17/university-guide-music |title=University guide 2012: Music |work=The Guardian  |date= 17 May 2011|accessdate=21 January 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[File:University of Bristol buildings.JPG|thumb|Royal Fort and the Physics department]]\nIn The Complete University Guide 2013, Bristol ranked fifth for German,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=German|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 German;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> fourth for Russian,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Russian+%26+East+European+Languages|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Russian & East European Languages;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> third for mechanical and civil engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Mechanical+Engineering|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Mechanical Engineering;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> third for music<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Music|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Music;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate= 24 January 2013|location= Bristol}}</ref> and second for drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Drama%2c+Dance+%26+Cinematics |title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Drama, Dance & Cinematics;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nBristol is also known for its research strength, having 15 departments gaining the top grade of 5* in the 2001 [[Research Assessment Exercise]]. Overall, 36 out of 46 departments rated gained the top two ratings of 5 or 5*, and 76% of all the academic staff working in departments scored these top two levels.<ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Research Assessment Exercise Results |publisher=Higher Education and Research Opportunities |accessdate=21 December 2007 |url=http://195.194.167.103/Results/all/all.xls |format=xls |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070315214410/http://195.194.167.103/Results/all/all.xls |archivedate=15 March 2007 }}</ref> In terms of teaching strength, Bristol had an average Teaching Quality Assessment score of 22.05/24 before the TQA was abolished.<ref>{{cite web | title = HEFCE TQA/QAA SUBJECT REVIEW RESULTS TABLE 1993\u2013present | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/tsu/ext_quality/qaa/qaaresults.html}}</ref> Bristol's drop-out rate is also lower than the benchmark set by HEFCE of no more than 3.1%.<ref>{{cite news | title = University dropout rate |work=BBC News | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 19 July 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/6906012.stm}}</ref>\n\n=== Degrees ===\nBristol awards a range of [[academic degree]]s spanning bachelor's and master's degrees as well as junior doctorates and [[higher doctorate]]s. The [[post-nominal letters|postnominals]] awarded are the [[British degree abbreviations|degree abbreviations]] used commonly among British universities. The university is part of the [[Engineering Doctorate]] scheme,<ref>{{cite web | title = Engineering Doctorate Centre Details | publisher = Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council | accessdate =18 July 2006 | url=http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/PostgraduateTraining/EngineeringDoctorates/CentreDetailsAndContacts.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060207094218/http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/PostgraduateTraining/EngineeringDoctorates/CentreDetailsAndContacts.htm |archivedate = 7 February 2006}}</ref> and awards the Eng. D. in [[systems engineering]], [[engineering management]], [[aerospace engineering]] and [[non-destructive evaluation]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for the Degree of Engineering Doctorate (Eng. D.) | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 August 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/engd.html}}</ref>\n\nBristol notably does not award by title any bachelor's degrees in music, which is available for study but awarded BA.(although it does award MMus and DMus), nor any degree in [[divinity]], since divinity is not available for study (students of theology are awarded a BA). Similarly, the university does not award BLitt (Bachelor of Letters), although it does award both MLitt and [[Doctor of Letters|DLitt]]. In regulations, the university does not name MD or [[Doctor of Dental Surgery|DDS]] as [[higher doctorate]]s, although they are in many universities<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for Dissertations for Doctoral and Masters Degrees... | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate=6 August 2007 | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/universitycalendar/regs/regulations/docmasters/dissregs.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050307060331/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/universitycalendar/regs/regulations/docmasters/dissregs.html|archivedate=7 March 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref> as these degrees are normally accredited professional doctorates.\n\nThe degrees of DLitt, DSc, DEng, [[Doctor of Laws|LLD]] and DMus, whilst having regulations specifying the grounds for award,<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for the Degrees of Doctor of Letters, Doctor of Science, Doctor of Engineering and Doctor of Laws | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 August 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/dlittdscdenglld.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070903184022/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/dlittdscdenglld.html |archivedate = 3 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> are most often conferred as honorary degrees (''in honoris causa'').<ref>{{cite web | title=Honorary Graduates | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate=6 August 2007 | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/hongrads.html}}</ref> Those used most commonly are the DLitt, DSc and LLD, with the [[Master of Arts|MA]] (and occasionally the MLitt) also sometimes conferred honorarily for distinction in the local area or within the University.\n\n== Student life ==\n\n=== Students' Union ===\n[[File:070327 ukbris ubu01.jpg|thumb|right|[[University of Bristol Union]] building]]\n{{Main|University of Bristol Students' Union}}\n\nThe [[University of Bristol Students' Union]] (Bristol SU) located on Queen's Road in the Richmond Building is a founding member of the National Union of Students and is amongst the oldest [[students' union]]s in England. The union oversees three media outlets: UBTV, the Bristol University Radio Station ([[BURST]]) and the student newspaper ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]''. There is also a local branch of ''[[The Tab]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/bristol|title=The Tab - University of Bristol - the latest news, guides and comment|website=University of Bristol}}</ref> The Union is responsible for representing students' academic interests through elections of student representatives and democratic events. The Union is also responsible for the organisation of the annual Welcome Fair, the co-ordination of Bristol Student Community Action, which organises volunteering projects in the local community, and the organisation of entertainment events and over 400<ref>{{cite web | title = BSU Societies | publisher = University of Bristol Union | accessdate = 24 April 2015 | url = http://www.bristolsu.org.uk/activities/societies/atoz/ | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150904065202/http://www.bristolsu.org.uk/activities/societies/atoz/ | archivedate = 4 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> student groups, societies and clubs. Previous presidents have included [[Sue Lawley]] and former [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Lembit \u00d6pik]]. There is a separate union for postgraduate students, as well as an athletic union, which is a member of the [[British Universities & Colleges Sport]].<ref>{{cite web | title = BUSA Members | publisher = BUSA | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.busa.org.uk/fl/members.asp | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612212139/http://www.busa.org.uk/fl/members.asp | archivedate = 12 June 2007}}</ref> In distinction to the \"[[blue (university sport)|blues]]\" awarded for sporting excellence at Oxford and Cambridge, Bristol's most successful athletes are awarded \"reds\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Bristol Reds | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/high-performance/bristol-reds.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Halls of residence ===\n{{Main|Halls of residence at the University of Bristol}}\n\n[[File:Wills Hall, University of Bristol.JPG|thumb|[[Wills Hall]]]]\n\nAccommodation for students is primarily in the central precinct of the university and two areas of Bristol: [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] and [[Stoke Bishop]], known respectively as the West and North Villages.<ref name=\"prosp\">{{cite web | title = Accommodation Office | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =12 January 2014 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accommodation/}}</ref>\n\nIn Stoke Bishop, [[Wills Hall]] on the edge of the [[The Downs (Bristol)|Clifton Downs]] was the first to be opened, in 1929, by the then chancellor, Winston Churchill. Its original [[quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]] layout has been expanded twice, in 1962 and 1990.<ref name=\"prosp\" /> [[Churchill Hall]], named for the chancellor, followed in 1956, then [[Badock Hall]] in 1964.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Badock Hall Prospectus | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Badock/prospectus.shtml | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20050504043639/http://bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Badock/prospectus.shtml | archive-date = 4 May 2005 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> At the time of Badock Hall's establishment, some of the buildings were called [[Hiatt Baker Hall]], but two years later, Hiatt Baker moved to its own site and is now the largest hall in the university.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Hiatt Baker Hall History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/hiattbaker/history/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080607171646/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/hiattbaker/history/ | archive-date = 7 June 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The first self-catering hall in Stoke Bishop was [[University Hall (Bristol)|University Hall]], established in 1971 with expansion in 1992.<ref name=\"prosp\" />\n\n[[File:Goldney1.jpg|thumb|[[Goldney Hall]]]]\nIn Clifton, [[Goldney Hall]] was built first in the early 18th century by the wealthy merchant [[Goldney family]] and eventually became part of the university in 1956.<ref>{{cite web | title = Goldney Hall History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Goldney/history.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070707143643/http://bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Goldney/history.htm | archive-date = 7 July 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It is a popular location for filming, with ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia (TV miniseries)|The Chronicles of Narnia]]'', ''[[The House of Eliott]]'' and ''[[Truly, Madly, Deeply]]'', as well as episodes of ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' and ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', being filmed there.<ref>{{cite web |title=Open day for Bristol's well-known garden |url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/Depts/Info-Office/news/archive/goldney.htm |publisher=University of Bristol |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> The [[Grotto at Goldney House|Grotto]] in the grounds is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Grotto approximately 85 metres south of Goldney House, Clifton Hill, Bristol |accessdate=21 December 2007 |num=1202104 }}</ref> [[Clifton Hill House]] is another Grade I listed building now used as student accommodation in Clifton. The original building was constructed between 1745 and 1750 by [[Isaac Ware]], and has been used by the university since its earliest days in 1909.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{NHLE|desc=Clifton Hill House and attached front walls, Clifton Hill, Bristol |accessdate=21 December 2007 |num=1280480 }}</ref> [[Manor Hall]] comprises five separate buildings, the principal of which was erected from 1927\u20131932 to the design of [[George Oatley]] following a donation from [[Henry Herbert Wills]]. Manor Hall houses the largest and most dated rooms, some dating back to the early 20th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accommodation/undergraduate/residences/manor/|title=Manor Hall {{!}} Accommodation Office {{!}} University of Bristol|last=Bristol|first=University of|website=www.bristol.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> One of its annexes, Manor House, has recently been refurbished and officially 'reopened' in 1999.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Manor Hall and Sinclair House History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Manor/new/history.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070705113326/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Manor/new/history.htm | archive-date = 5 July 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[File:CliftonHillHouse.JPG|thumb|[[Clifton Hill House]]]]\n\nOn the central precinct sits The Hawthorns, a student house accommodating 115 undergraduate students.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Hawthorns webpage | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/studenthouses/sths/haw/facts.html | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =13 July 2011}}</ref> The house started life as a collection of villas built somewhere between 1888 and 1924<ref>Bristol Record Office: Volume 19, Folio 74 and Volume 22, Folio 34</ref> that were later converted, bit by bit, into a hotel by John Dingle.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Bristol Supplementary Planning Document Number 11 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/estates/documents/masterplan/masterplan-appendix11.pdf | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 13 July 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120111155720/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/estates/documents/masterplan/masterplan-appendix11.pdf | archivedate = 11 January 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The Hawthorns also houses conferencing facilities, the staff refectory and bar, the Accommodation Office and the Student Houses Office. 33 Colston Street was opened in the city centre in October 2011 after the University acquired the property in 2009.<ref name=\"prosp\" /> Several of the residences in the central precinct are more recent and have been built and are managed by third-party organisations under exclusivity arrangements with the University. These include New Bridewell House, opened in 2016, which is in the former police HQ, it includes en-suite bedrooms and studios and is operated by Fresh Student Housing, Unite House and Chantry Court, opened in 2000 and 2003 respectively by the [[UNITE Group]],<ref>{{cite web | title = UNITE House in Bristol | publisher = UNITE Group plc | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1UNITE|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224080516/http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1UNITE |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Chantry Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/chantry.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022103531/http://bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/chantry.html | archivedate = 22 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Chantry Court in Bristol | publisher = UNITE Group plc | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1CHANT|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224080507/http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1CHANT |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> as well as Dean's Court (2001, postgraduates only) and Woodland Court (2005), both run by the Dominion Housing Group.<ref>{{cite web | title = Dean's Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/dc.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022103536/http://bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/dc.html | archivedate = 22 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Woodland Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/woodland.html}}</ref>\n\nAll of the main halls elect groups of students to the [[Junior Common Room#Bristol|Junior Common Room]] to organise the halls social calendar for the next year. Residents of student houses, private accommodation and students living at home become members of Orbital&nbsp;\u2013 a society organising social events for students throughout the year.<ref name=\"prosp\" />\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of University of Bristol people}}\n\n=== Academics ===\nCurrent academics at the University of Bristol include 21 fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]], 13 fellows of the [[British Academy]], 13 fellows of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] and 44 fellows of the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Nobel Prizes and Fellowships|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=2 October 2011|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/distinctions}}</ref> These include, Sir [[Michael Berry (physicist)|Michael Berry]], one of the discoverers of [[quantum mechanics]]' \"[[geometric phase]]\",<ref>{{cite web | title = Michael Berry | publisher = HP Labs | accessdate =29 December 2007 | url = http://www.hpl.hp.com/news/lectures/Abstracts/MichaelBerry.htm}}</ref> [[John Rarity]] international expert on [[quantum optics]], [[quantum cryptography]] and quantum communication, [[David May (computer scientist)|David May]], computer scientist and lead architect for the [[transputer]],<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | surname = MAY | othernames = Prof. (Michael) David | id = U27080 | volume = 2015 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> [[Mark Horton (archaeologist)|Mark Horton]], a British maritime and historical archaeologist.\n\nAcademics in computer science include, [[Dave Cliff (computer scientist)|David Cliff]], inventor of the seminal \"ZIP\" trading algorithm, [[Peter Flach]], [[Mike Fraser (computer scientist)|Mike Fraser]], Professor of Human-computer interaction, [[Julian Gough (scientist)|Julian Gough]] and  [[Nigel Smart (cryptographer)|Nigel Smart]].\n\nMarine [[ecologist]] Dr Rose Crichton is currently working at Bristol. Rose's PhD thesis on [[Gammaridea]] helped to raise awareness of the effects of climate change on marine crustaceans. Dr Crichton is director of the Bristol Fish Project.<ref>{{cite web | title = Dr Rose Crichton|publisher=Bristol Fish Project|accessdate=6 October 2019|url=https://bristolfish.org/about/core-team/dr-rose-crichton/}}</ref>\n\nPast academics of the university include, [[Patricia Broadfoot]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Gloucestershire]], [[Nigel Thrift]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Warwick]], and [[Wendy Larner]], Provost of [[Victoria University of Wellington]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Patricia Broadfoot |publisher=University of Gloucestershire |accessdate=29 December 2007 |url=http://www.glos.ac.uk/council/patricia-broadfoot.cfm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020005514/http://www.glos.ac.uk/council/patricia-broadfoot.cfm |archivedate=20 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = About the Vice-Chancellor | accessdate =29 December 2007 | publisher = University of Warwick | url = http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/about/management/vc|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072647/http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/about/management/vc |archivedate = 15 December 2007}}</ref> [[Anthony Epstein]], co-discoverer of the [[Epstein-Barr virus]], was Professor of [[Pathology]] at the university from 1968\u20131982,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Honorary Fellowship for Professor Sir Anthony Epstein | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =29 December 2007 | date = 18 July 2006 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2006/1030.html}}</ref> Sir [[John Lennard-Jones]], discoverer of the [[Lennard-Jones potential]] in physics<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lennard-Jones, J. E. | title = Cohesion | journal = Proceedings of the Physical Society | year = 1931 | volume = 43 | pages = 461\u2013482 | doi = 10.1088/0959-5309/43/5/301 | issue = 5|bibcode = 1931PPS....43..461L}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = H. Jones | title = Notes on Work at the University of Bristol, 1930-7 | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, Series A | year = 1931 | volume = 371 | pages = 52\u201355 | issue = 1744| doi = 10.1098/rspa.1980.0056 }}</ref> and [[Alfred Marshall]], one of the University College's principals and influential economist in the latter part of the 19th century.<ref>{{cite web | title = Alfred Marshall | publisher = Economy Professor | accessdate =29 December 2007 | url = http://www.economyprofessor.com/theorists/alfredmarshall.php}}</ref> Mathematicians and philosophers [[Rohit Parikh]] and [[Brian Rotman]] lectured in the mathematics department, and philosopher of science [[Paul Feyerabend]] taught in the Department of Philosophy.\n\nThe University of Bristol is associated with three [[Ig Nobel Prizes]], an award for unusual or trivial achievements in scientific research. Sir [[Michael Berry (physicist)|Michael Berry]] shared the award (with [[Andre Geim]], a Nobel Laureate) for using [[magnets]] to levitate a frog.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Berry | first1 = M. V. | authorlink1 = Michael Berry (physicist)| last2 = Geim | first2 = A. K. | authorlink2 = Andre Geim| title = Of flying frogs and levitrons | journal = European Journal of Physics | volume = 18 | issue = 4 | pages = 307 | year = 1997 | doi = 10.1088/0143-0807/18/4/012| url = http://www.physics.bristol.ac.uk/people/berry_mv/the_papers/Berry285.pdf|bibcode = 1997EJPh...18..307B }}</ref> Gareth Jones also shared an Ig Nobel prize for scientifically documenting [[fellatio]] in [[fruit bat]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Tan | first1 = M. | last2 = Jones | first2 = G. | last3 = Zhu | first3 = G. | last4 = Ye | first4 = J. | last5 = Hong | first5 = T. | last6 = Zhou | first6 = S. | last7 = Zhang | first7 = S. | last8 = Zhang | first8 = L. | editor1-last = Hosken | editor1-first = David | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0007595 | title = Fellatio by fruit bats prolongs copulation time | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 4 | issue = 10 | pages = e7595 | year = 2009 | pmid =  19862320| pmc =2762080 | bibcode = 2009PLoSO...4.7595T }}</ref> Dr. Len Fisher was awarded the 1999 prize for physics for calculating the optimal way to dunk a biscuit.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Fisher | first1 = L. | title = Physics takes the biscuit | journal = Nature | volume = 397 | issue = 6719 | pages = 469 | year = 1999 | doi = 10.1038/17203 | bibcode = 1999Natur.397..469F }}</ref>\n\n=== Alumni ===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:JonathanEvans.jpg|[[Jonathan Evans (MI5 officer)|Jonathan Evans]], former Head of [[MI5]]\nFile:Alastair Stewart 31.08.07.jpg|[[Alastair Stewart]], TV journalist\nFile:Derren Victor Brown.jpg|[[Derren Brown]], illusionist\nFile:Simon Pegg 01.jpg|[[Simon Pegg]], actor and writer\nFile:David Walliams.JPG|[[David Walliams]], comedian\n</gallery>\n\nBristol alumnus [[Paul Dirac]] went on to win the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1933 for his contribution to the formulation of quantum mechanics and is considered one of the most significant physicists of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Dirac (1902 - 1984) |url=https://www.physicsoftheuniverse.com/scientists_dirac.html |publisher=The Physics of the Universe |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Other notable scientists include [[Dani Rabaiotti]], an environmental scientist and science communicator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zsl.org/science/users/daniella-rabaiotti|title=Daniella Rabaiotti|website=Zoological Society of London (ZSL)|language=en|access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref> [[Eliahu Nissim]] was a Professor of Aeronautical Engineering, and the President of the [[Open University of Israel]].\n\nOther notable [[alumnus|alumni]] include writers [[Dick King-Smith]], [[Sarah Kane]], Olivier award-winning playwright [[Laura Wade]], [[Angela Carter]], [[Dorothy Simpson]], [[David Gibbins]] and [[David Nicholls (writer)|David Nicholls]], author of the novel ''[[Starter for Ten (novel)|Starter for Ten]]'', turned into a screenplay set in the University of Bristol.<ref>{{cite web|title =Starter for Ten|publisher=BBC Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2006/06/26/starter_feature.shtml}}</ref> [[Mark Simmons (author)|Mark Simmons]], author of business books, [[Will Hutton]], economist, author, commentator.\n\nIn entertainment and current affairs former students include, journalist and McMafia author [[Misha Glenny]], [[James Landale]], BBC News Chief Political Correspondent who founded the university independent newspaper ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]'', author and journalist [[Julie Myerson]], [[William Lewis (journalist)|William Lewis]], editor-in-chief of the Telegraph Media Group, [[Derren Brown]], illusionist, [[Sue Lawley]], Radio 4 presenter, [[Alastair Stewart]], newsreader and [[Dominic Waghorn]], [[Sky News]] US Correspondent. [[Susanna Reid]], [[ITV Breakfast]] anchor studied Politics, Philosophy and Law at the university between 1989 and 1992 and was also editor of the student newspaper, ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]''.\n\nIn comedy, [[Matt Lucas]] and [[David Walliams]],<ref>{{cite web | title =Notable alumni| publisher = Bristol University| accessdate =21 December 2007| url=http://www.alumni.bristol.ac.uk/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=190&srcid=238}}</ref> [[Simon Pegg]], [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]], creator of the controversial ''[[Brass Eye]]'' and [[Jon Richardson (entertainer)|Jon Richardson]]. Other comedy stars include [[Chris Langham]], of [[The Thick of It]] fame, standup comic [[Marcus Brigstocke]] and [[Jamie Demetriou]], creator and writer of [[Stath Lets Flats]].\n\nNotable alumni from the Film and Television Production department include film directors [[Mick Jackson (director)|Mick Jackson]], [[Michael Winterbottom]], [[Marc Evans]], [[Christopher Smith (director)|Christopher Smith]], [[Alex Cox]], [[Peter Webber]] and [[Maddie Moate]].\n\nOther alumni include, [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], musician [[James Blunt]], former Liberal Democrat MP [[Lembit \u00d6pik]] was President of Bristol University Students' Union during his time. [[Jonathan Evans, Baron Evans of Weardale|Sir Jonathan Evans]]  former head of MI5, [[Anne McClain]], member of the 2013 NASA Astronaut Class<ref>{{YouTube|Aj6HTM33pBY}}</ref> and [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]], [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] from October 2012 to January 2017 amongst many others.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[CHOMBEC]]\n* [[Education in Bristol]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n*[[University of Bristol Theatre Collection]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last= Carleton |first= Don |date= 1984 |title= University for Bristol: A History in Text and Pictures |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-200-3 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Delany |first= Rosalind |date= 2002 |title= How Did This Garden Grow?: The History of the Botanic Gardens of the University of Bristol |publisher= Friends of Bristol University Botanic Garden |isbn= 0-9543504-0-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Crossley Evans |first= M. J. |date= 1994 |title= A History of Wills Hall University of Bristol |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-421-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Whittingham |first= Sarah |date= 2003 |title= Wills Memorial Building |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-541-X }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|University of Bristol}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.bristol.ac.uk/}}\n* [https://www.bristolsu.org.uk/ Bristol SU] (Students' Union)\n\n{{University of Bristol|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Universities and colleges in South West England}}\n{{Education in Bristol}}\n{{Worldwide Universities Network}}\n{{Coimbra Group}}\n{{Russell Group}}\n{{CDIO}}\n}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bristol, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of Bristol|University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1909]]\n[[Category:Russell Group]]\n[[Category:1909 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:HSA Foundation members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Bristol University|the university in Anaheim, California|Bristol University (California)|the university in Bristol, Tennessee|Bristol University (Tennessee)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name             = University of Bristol\n| image_name       = University_of_Bristol_crest.jpg\n| image_size       = 150px\n| latin_name       = Universitas Bristolliensis\n| motto            = {{lang-la|Vim promovet insitam}}\n| mottoeng         = [Learning] promotes one's innate power (from [[Horace]], ''Ode 4.4'')<ref name=\"arms\" />\n| established      = 1595 - Merchant Venturers School<br />1876 - [[University College, Bristol]]<br />1909 - received [[royal charter]]\n|type              = [[public university|Public]] [[red brick university|red brick]] [[research university]]\n| endowment        = \u00a372.2m {{small|(as of 31 July 2018)}}<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\"/>\n|budget = [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]642.7 million {{small|(2017-18)}}<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\"/>\n| chancellor       = [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]]<ref name=\"Bristolwebsitechancellor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/chancellor.html|title=Bristol University|work=Chancellor's biography|accessdate=13 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607210701/http://bristol.ac.uk/university/chancellor.html|archivedate=7 June 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| vice_chancellor  = [[Hugh Brady (academic)|Hugh Brady]]\n| head_label       = Visitor\n| head             = [[Lord President of the Council|The Lord President of the Council]] ''[[ex officio]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page49.asp |title=Institutions for which the President of the Council acts as Visitor |accessdate=20 December 2007 |publisher=Privy Council Office |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071121215029/http://www.privy-council.org.uk/output/Page49.asp |archivedate=21 November 2007 }}</ref>\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0112}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| city             = [[Bristol]]\n| country          = England\n| coor             = {{Coord|51|27|23|N|02|36|16|W|display=inline,title|type:edu}}\n| campus           = Urban\n|free_label        = Students' Union\n|free              = [[University of Bristol Union]]\n| colours          = {{color box|#b01c2e}} Pantone 187<ref name=\"vis-ident\"/>\n| website          = [http://www.bristol.ac.uk/ bristol.ac.uk]\n| logo             = [[File:University of Bristol logo.svg|250px]]\n| staff            = 6,199<ref name=\"UoBFigures\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/ |title=University of Bristol Facts & Figures |accessdate=2 May 2015}}</ref>\n| affiliations     = [[Russell Group]]<br /> [[Coimbra Group]]<br /> [[Worldwide Universities Network]]<br />[[Universities UK]]<br/>[[Partnership of a European Group of Aeronautics and Space Universities|PEGASUS]]<br />[[SETsquared]]<br />[[GW4]] <br /> [[Sutton 13]] <br />\n}}\n\nThe '''University of Bristol''' is a [[Red brick university|red brick]] [[research university]] in [[Bristol]], England.<ref name=\"BristolwebsiteMap\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/maps/precinct.html|title=Maps and Guides|work=The University precinct map|accessdate=28 April 2008}}</ref> It received its [[royal charter]] in 1909,<ref name=\"Bristolwebsite\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/acts.html|title=The University of Bristol Acts|work=The University of Bristol Act 1909|accessdate=13 May 2007}}</ref> although it can trace its roots to a [[Society of Merchant Venturers|Merchant Venturers]]' school founded in 1595 and [[University College, Bristol]], which had been in existence since 1876.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/history/|title=Bristol University History |work=History of the University|accessdate=13 May 2007}}</ref>\n\nBristol is organised into [[University of Bristol#Academic structure|six academic faculties]] composed of multiple schools and departments running over 200 undergraduate courses, largely in the [[Tyndalls Park]] area of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/study/undergraduate/study-at-bristol/our-degrees/|title=About our courses - Study at Bristol - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref> The university had a total income of \u00a3642.7 million in 2017-18, of which \u00a3164.0 million was from research grants and contracts.<ref name=\"Bristol Financial Statement 17/18\">{{cite web | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/media-library/sites/finance/documents/annual-report-financial-statements-2018.pdf | title = Financial Statements for the Year to 31 July 2018 | accessdate = 2 December 2018 | publisher = University of Bristol| page = 42}}</ref> It is the largest independent employer in Bristol.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/| title = Key Facts and Figures| accessdate =12 January 2014| year = 2014| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Bristol is ranked 49th by the [[QS World University Rankings]] 2020, and is ranked in the top 10 of UK universities in 2020 by [[QS World University Rankings|QS World University rankings]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020|title=QS World University Rankings|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=QS Top Universities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|Times Higher Education]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings|date=2019-08-20|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> and [[Academic Ranking of World Universities|ARWU]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/arwu2019.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2019 {{!}} Academic Ranking of World Universities 2019 {{!}} Top 1000 universities {{!}} Shanghai Ranking - 2019|website=www.shanghairanking.com|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref> The University of Bristol was the second most targeted university by the UK's top 100 employers, according to the Graduate Market in 2019 report produced by High Fliers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAn extremely selective institution, it has an average of 6.4 (Sciences faculty) to 13.1 (Medicine & Dentistry Faculty) applicants for each undergraduate place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/facts/|title=Facts and figures - About the University - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref>  It was ranked 9th in the UK among multi-faculty institutions for the quality (GPA) of its research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/Attachments/2014/12/17/k/a/s/over-14-01.pdf|title=Research Excellence Framework results 2014|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and for its Research Power in the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]].<ref>{{cite news|title=REF 2014 results|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/ng-interactive/2014/dec/18/university-research-excellence-framework-2014-full-rankings|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nCurrent academics include 21 fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]], 13 fellows of the [[British Academy]], 13 fellows of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] and 44 fellows of the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Nobel Prizes and Fellowships|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=2 May 2015|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/distinctions}}</ref> The university has been associated with 13 Nobel laureates throughout its history, including [[Paul Dirac]], [[William Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]], [[Cecil Frank Powell]], [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]], [[Dorothy Hodgkin]], [[Hans Albrecht Bethe]], [[Max Delbr\u00fcck]], [[Gerhard Herzberg]], [[Sir Nevill Francis Mott]], [[Sir Paul Nurse]], [[Harold Pinter]], [[Jean-Marie Gustave Le Cl\u00e9zio]] and most recently, 2015 Economics Nobel Prize winner [[Angus Deaton]].\n\nBristol is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of research-intensive British universities,<ref>{{cite web|title=Russell Group Our Universities|url=http://www.russellgroup.ac.uk/our-universities/|accessdate=27 January 2012}}</ref> the European-wide [[Coimbra Group]]<ref name=\"CoimbraGroup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coimbra-group.eu/index.php?page=members|title=The Coimbra Group|work=List of Coimbra Group Members|accessdate=14 May 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502062025/http://www.coimbra-group.eu/index.php?page=members|archivedate=2 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the [[Worldwide Universities Network]], of which the university's previous vice-chancellor, [[Eric Thomas (academic)|Eric Thomas]], was chairman from 2005 to 2007.<ref name=\"WUN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wun.ac.uk/|title=The Worldwide Universities Network|work=List of WUN Group Members|accessdate=14 May 2007}}</ref> In addition, the university holds an [[Erasmus Programme|Erasmus Charter]], sending more than 500 students per year to partner institutions in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/global/partnerships/|title=Our research impact - Research - University of Bristol|first=University of|last=Bristol|website=www.bristol.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of the University of Bristol}}\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe earliest antecedent of the university was the engineering department of the [[Merchant Venturers' Technical College]] (founded as a school as early as 1595) which became the engineering faculty of Bristol University.<ref>{{cite web|author=United Kingdom |url=http://www.merchantventurers.com/charitable-activities/education.html |title=Education \u2013 The Society of Merchant Venturers, Bristol UK |publisher=Merchantventurers.com |accessdate=5 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090829092557/http://merchantventurers.com/charitable-activities/education.html |archivedate=29 August 2009 }}</ref> The university was also preceded by [[Bristol Medical School]] (1833) and [[University College, Bristol]], founded in 1876,<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> where its first lecture was attended by only 99 students.<ref>{{cite news | title = University of Bristol |work=The Guardian  | date = 1 May 2007 | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/universityguide/profile/story/0,,478329,00.html | location=London}}</ref> The university was able to apply for a [[royal charter]] due to the financial support of the [[W. D. & H. O. Wills|Wills]], [[Fry family (chocolate)|Fry]] and Colston families, who made their fortunes in tobacco plantations, chocolate, and (via [[Edward Colston]]) the transatlantic slave trade, respectively. A 2018 study commissioned by the university estimated 85% of the philanthropic funds used for the institution's foundation was directly connected with the transatlantic slave trade.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/university/history/past-matters/|title=Past Matters: the University of Bristol and transatlantic slavery|work=University of Bristol|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe royal charter was gained in May 1909, with 288 undergraduates and 400 other students entering the university in October 1909. [[Henry Overton Wills III]] became its first chancellor.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> The University College was the first such institution in the country to [[Mixed-sex education|admit women on the same basis as men]].<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> However, women were forbidden to take examinations in medicine until 1906.<ref name=\"archives-hub\">{{cite web|title=Papers of the University of Bristol |publisher=Archives Hub |accessdate=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.archiveshub.ac.uk/news/03121903.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229151955/http://archiveshub.ac.uk/features/03121903.html|archivedate=29 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Historical development ===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em; font-size: 85%; background:#ffffoo; color:black; width:23em; max-width: 25%;\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" |\nThere shall be from henceforth for ever in Our said City of Bristol a University...\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\" | [[Edward VII of the United Kingdom|King Edward VII]], Charter of Incorporation of the University of Bristol, 4 December 1909<ref name=\"charter\">{{cite web | title = Charter of Incorporation | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/charter.html|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070930183415/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/charter.html |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref>\n|}\nSince the founding of the university itself in 1909, it has grown considerably and is now one of the largest employers in the local area, although it is smaller by student numbers than the nearby [[University of the West of England]].<ref name=\"HESA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls |title=Table 0a \u2013 All students by institution, mode of study, level of study, gender and domicile 2006/07 |accessdate=5 April 2008 |format=[[Microsoft Excel]] spreadsheet |publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130709132444/http://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/dataTables/studentsAndQualifiers/download/institution0607.xls |archivedate= 9 July 2013 }}</ref> Bristol does not have a campus but is spread over a considerable geographic area. Most of its activities, however, are concentrated in the area of the city centre, referred to as the \"University Precinct\". It is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of research-led UK universities, the [[Coimbra Group]] of leading European universities and the [[Worldwide Universities Network]] (WUN).\n\n==== Early years ====\n[[File:university of bristol tower after cleaning arp.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Wills Memorial Building]] (Schools of Law and Earth Sciences) on [[Park Street, Bristol]]. The tower was cleaned in 2006\u20132007.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2006/875.html|publisher= Bristol University | title=Wills Tower set for new glory|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>]]\nAfter the founding of the University College in 1876, Government support began in 1889. After mergers with the Bristol Medical School in 1893 and the Merchant Venturers' Technical College in 1909,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol |accessdate=6 December 2007 |url=http://www.history-ontheweb.co.uk/uni/bristol.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213091650/http://www.history-ontheweb.co.uk/uni/bristol.htm |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref> this funding allowed the opening of a new medical school and an engineering school\u2014two subjects that remain among the university's greatest strengths. In 1908, gifts from the [[Fry Family (Chocolate)|Fry]] and Wills families, particularly \u00a3100,000 from [[Henry Overton Wills III]] (\u00a36m in today's money), were provided to endow a University for Bristol and the West of England, provided that a [[royal charter]] could be obtained within two years. In December 1909, the King granted such a charter and erected the University of Bristol.<ref name=\"charter\" /> Henry Wills became its first [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]] and [[Conwy Lloyd Morgan]] the first vice-chancellor.<ref name=\"past-officers\">{{cite web | title = Bristol University \u2013 Former Officers | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =22 June 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/formerofficers.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927233714/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/formerofficers.html |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref> Wills died in 1911 and in tribute his sons [[George Alfred Wills|George]] and [[Henry Herbert Wills|Harry]] built the [[Wills Memorial Building]], starting in 1913 and finally finishing in 1925.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wills Memorial Building |url=http://www.bristol-link.co.uk/history/wills-memorial-building.htm |publisher=Bristol Link |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Today, it houses parts of the academic provision for [[earth sciences]] and law, and graduation ceremonies are held in its Great Hall. The Wills Memorial Building is a Grade II* listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=University Tower and Wills Memorial Building and attached front walls and lamps |accessdate=6 December 2007 |num=1218203 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1920, George Wills bought the [[Victoria Rooms (Bristol)|Victoria Rooms]] and endowed them to the university as a [[Students' Union]].<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" />\nThe building now houses the Department of Music and is a Grade II* listed building.<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Victoria Rooms and attached railings and gates |accessdate=6 December 2007 |num=1202480 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:King's College London Students Evacuated To Bristol, England, 1940 D433.jpg|thumbnail|left|Evacuated [[King's College London]] students at the University of Bristol in 1940]]\nAt the point of foundation, the university was required to provide for the local community. This mission was behind the creation of the Department of Extra-Mural Adult Education in 1924 to provide courses to the local community. This mission continues today; a new admissions policy specifically caters to the 'BS' [[UK postcodes|postcode]] area of [[Bristol]].<ref name=\"admit-policy\">{{cite web|title=Undergraduate admissions principles and procedures (Home/EU students)|publisher=Bristol University|accessdate=8 August 2013|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/governance/policies/admissions/home-overseas.html}}</ref>\n\nAmong the famous names associated with Bristol in this early period is [[Paul Dirac]], who graduated in 1921 with a degree in engineering, before obtaining a second degree in mathematics in 1923 from Cambridge. For his subsequent pioneering work on quantum mechanics, he was awarded the 1933 Nobel Prize for Physics.<ref>{{cite web | title = Notable alumni \u2013 Faculty of Engineering | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url =http://www.alumni.bristol.ac.uk/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?&pid=280&srcid=190}}</ref> Later in the 1920s, the H.H. Wills Physics Laboratory was opened by [[Ernest Rutherford]].<ref>{{cite web | title = History of the Department | publisher = Department of Physics, University of Bristol | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.phy.bristol.ac.uk/history.html}}</ref> It has since housed several Nobel Prize winners: [[Cecil Frank Powell]] (1950);<ref>{{cite web | title = The Nobel Prize in Physics 1950 | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1950/}}</ref> [[Hans Albrecht Bethe]] (1967);<ref>{{cite web | title = Hans Bethe \u2013 Biography | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1967/bethe-bio.html}}</ref> and Sir [[Nevill Francis Mott]] (1977).<ref>{{cite web | title = Sir Nevill F. Mott | publisher = The Nobel Foundation | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1977/mott-bio.html}}</ref> The Laboratory stands on the same site today, close to the [[Bristol Grammar School]] and the city museum.\n\n[[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]] became the university's third chancellor in 1929, serving the university in that capacity until 1965.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> He succeeded [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Richard Haldane]] who had held the office from 1912 following the death of Henry Wills.<ref name=\"archives-hub\" /><ref name=\"past-officers\" />\n\nDuring World War II, the Wills Memorial was bombed, destroying the Great Hall and the organ it housed,<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> along with 7,000 books removed from [[King's College London]] for safe keeping.  It has since been restored to its former glory, complete with oak panelled walls and a new organ.\n\n==== Post-war development ====\n\nIn 1946, the university established the first drama department in the country.<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> In the same year, Bristol began offering special entrance [[exam]]s and [[Grant (money)|grants]] to aid the resettlement of servicemen returning home. Student numbers continued to increase, and the Faculty of Engineering eventually needed the new premises that were to become Queen's Building in 1955. This substantial building housed all of the university's engineers until 1996, when the department of [[Electrical Engineering]] and [[Department of Computer Science, University of Bristol|Department of Computer Science]] moved over the road into the new Merchant Venturers' Building to make space for these rapidly expanding fields. Today, Queen's Building caters for most of the teaching needs of the Faculty and provides academic space for the \"heavy\" engineering subjects ([[civil engineering|civil]], [[mechanical engineering|mechanical]], and [[Aerospace engineering|aerospace]]).\n\nWith unprecedented growth in the 1960s, particularly in undergraduate numbers, the Students' Union eventually acquired larger premises in a new building in the [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] area of the city, in 1965. This building was more spacious than the Victoria Rooms, which were now given over to the Department of Music. The [[University of Bristol Union|new Union]] provides many practice and performance rooms, some specialist rooms, as well as three bars: Bar 100; the Mandela (also known as AR2) and the Avon Gorge. Whilst spacious, the Union building is thought by many to be ugly<ref>{{cite web | title = The Students' Union | publisher = University of Bristol Union | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/union/altprospectus/unilife/union |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126124416/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/union/altprospectus/unilife/union |archivedate = 26 November 2007}}</ref> and out of character compared to the architecture of the rest of the Clifton area, having been mentioned in a [[BBC]] poll to find the worst architectural eyesores in Britain.<ref>{{cite news | title = What is the worst eyesore in the UK? |work=BBC News | date = 21 November 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/talking_point/3266673.stm}}</ref> The university has proposed relocating the Union to a more central location as part of its development 'masterplan'.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Bristol Strategic Masterplan | publisher = University of Bristol | page = 64 | accessdate =6 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Bursar/masterplan06/1masterplan.pdf |date=July 2006 }}</ref> More recently, plans for redevelopment of the current building have been proposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ubu.org.uk/build |title=Building Project \u2013 A Better Building for the Students' Union |publisher=Ubu.org.uk |accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe 1960s were a time of considerable student activism in the United Kingdom, and Bristol was no exception. In 1968, many students marched in support of the [[Anderson Report (British Education)|Anderson Report]], which called for higher student grants. This discontent culminated in an 11-day sit-in at the Senate House (the administrative headquarters of the university).<ref name=\"BristolUniversityHistory\" /> A series of chancellors and vice-chancellors led the university through these decades, with [[Henry Somerset, 10th Duke of Beaufort]] taking over from Churchill as chancellor in 1965 before being succeeded by [[Dorothy Hodgkin]] in 1970 who spent the next 18 years in the office.<ref name=\"past-officers\" />\n\nAs the age of mass higher education dawned, Bristol continued to build its student numbers. The various undergraduate residences were repeatedly expanded and, more recently, some postgraduate residences have been constructed. These more recent ventures have been funded (and are run) by external companies in agreement with the university.\n\nSince 1988, there have been only three further chancellors; Sir [[Jeremy Morse]], then chairman of [[Lloyds Bank (historic)|Lloyds Bank]] who handed over in 2003 to [[Brenda Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond|Brenda Hale]], the first female [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary|Law Lord]].<ref name=\"archives-hub\" /><ref name=\"past-officers\" /> [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]] succeeded Lady Hale as Chancellor on 1 January 2017.\n\n[[File:Victoria Rooms (750px).jpg|thumb|The Victoria Rooms, housing the School of Music]]\nOne of the few [[Centre for Deaf Studies, Bristol|Centres for Deaf Studies]] in the United Kingdom was established in Bristol in 1981, followed in 1988 by the Norah Fry Centre for research into learning difficulties. Also in 1988, and again in 2004,<ref>{{cite news| title = Students' union breaks from NUS| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/3463995.stm|work=BBC News| date = 5 February 2004| accessdate =20 December 2007}}</ref> the Students' Union AGM voted to disaffiliate from the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] (NUS). On both occasions, however, the subsequent referendum of all students reversed that decision and Bristol remains affiliated to the NUS.\n\nIn 2002, the university was involved in an argument over press intrusion after details of then-prime minister [[Tony Blair]]'s son's application to university were published in national newspapers.\n\nAs the number of postgraduate students has grown (particularly the numbers pursuing taught master's degrees), there eventually became a need for separate representation on university bodies and the Postgraduate Union (PGU) was established in 2000.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.pgu.org.uk/yourpgu/| title = General introduction of the PGU| accessdate =20 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol Postgraduate Union|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071227191758/http://www.pgu.org.uk/yourpgu/ |archivedate = 27 December 2007}}</ref>\nUniversities are increasingly expected to exploit the intellectual property generated by their research activities and, in 2000, Bristol established the Research and Enterprise Division (RED) to further this cause (particularly for technology-based businesses). In 2001, the university signed a 25-year research funding deal with IP2IPO, an intellectual property commercialisation company.<ref>{{cite news | title = Bristol signs commercial research funding deal |work=The Guardian  | author = Donald MacLeod | date = 5 December 2005 | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/businessofresearch/story/0,,1658169,00.html | location=London}}</ref> In 2007, research activities were expanded further with the opening of the Advanced Composites Centre for Innovation and Science (ACCIS) and The Bristol Institute for Public Affairs (BIPA).\n\nIn 2002, the university opened the new Centre for Sports, Exercise and Health in the heart of the university precinct.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/about/| title = Bristol University \u2013 Centre for Sport, Exercise &amp; Health \u2013 About us| accessdate = 20 December 2007| date = 2 October 2007| publisher = University of Bristol| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071030093119/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/about/| archivedate = 30 October 2007| df = dmy-all}}</ref> At a cost, local residents are also able to use the facilities.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/community| title = Bristol University \u2013 Centre for Sport, Exercise &amp; Health \u2013 community programmes| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 28 September 2007| publisher = University of Bristol|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126122458/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/community |archivedate = 26 November 2007}}</ref>\n[[File:Bristol University from Cabot Tower.jpg|thumb|left|Most of the buildings here are used by the university. The [[Wills Memorial Building]] is left of centre. Viewed from the [[Cabot Tower (Bristol)|Cabot Tower]] on Brandon Hill]]\nExpansion of teaching and research activities continues. In 2004, the Faculty of Engineering completed work on the Bristol Laboratory for Advanced Dynamics Engineering (BLADE). This \u00a318.5m project<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/gallery/places/blade.html| title = Places \u2013 BLADE| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 20 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181805/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/gallery/places/blade.html |archivedate = 30 September 2007}}</ref> is intended to further the study of dynamics and is the most advanced such facility in Europe.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Saouma |first1=Victor |last2=Sivaselvan |first2=Mettupalayam |title=Hybrid Simulation: Theory, Implementation and Applications |date=2014 |publisher=CRC Press |isbn=9781482288612 |page=217 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=HUtZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=Bristol+Laboratory+for+Advanced+Dynamics+Engineering+(BLADE)+advanced+Europe#v=onepage&q=Bristol%20Laboratory%20for%20Advanced%20Dynamics%20Engineering%20(BLADE)%20advanced%20Europe&f=false}}</ref> It was built as an extension to the Queen's Building and was officially opened by [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] in March 2005.\n\nIn January 2005, the School of Chemistry was awarded \u00a34.5m by the [[Higher Education Funding Council for England]] to create Bristol ChemLabS: a Centre for Excellence in Teaching & Learning (CETL),<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.chm.bristol.ac.uk/whatsnew/cetl.htm| title = CETL \u2013 A\u00a314M Boost for Teaching and Learning in Bristol Chemistry \u2013 27/01/05| accessdate =20 December 2007| date = 14 December 2007| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref> with an additional \u00a3350k announced for the capital part of the project in February 2006. Bristol ChemLabS stands for Bristol Chemical Laboratory Sciences; it is the only chemistry CETL in the UK.\n\nSeptember 2009 saw the opening of the university's [[Centre for Nanoscience and Quantum Information]]. This \u00a311 million building is known as the quietest building in the world{{clarify|date=March 2020}} and has other technologically sophisticated features such as self-cleaning glass. Advanced research into quantum computing, nanotechnology, materials and other disciplines are being undertaken in the building.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2009/6531.html| title = 'Quietest' building in the world opens today | accessdate =15 September 2011| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a plan to significantly redevelop the centre of the University Precinct in the coming years.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Bursar/masterplan.html| title = University of Bristol Masterplan| accessdate =20 December 2007| last = Bowden| first = Chris| date = 10 September 2007| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref> The first step began in September 2011, with the start of construction of a state-of-the-art Life Sciences building.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2011/7931.html| title = New \u00a350 million University building to transform a key area of Bristol | accessdate =21 October 2011| publisher = University of Bristol}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 while building work was underway in the [[Fry Building]],<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Bristol: Fry Building|url=http://www.wilkinsoneyre.com/projects/university-of-bristol-fry-building|publisher=WilkinsonEyre|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Work to create \u00a333 million mathematics building gets underway|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2016/march/fry-building.html|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref> the building caught fire.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bristol University fire: Live updates as Fry building undergoing major refurb goes up in flames with smoke seen across city|url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/news/bristol-news/park-street-fire-live-updates-1021777|accessdate=6 January 2018|work=Bristol Post|date=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bristol University fire: Crews tackle campus blaze|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-bristol-42591375|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2003 admissions controversy ====\n\n{{Main|University of Bristol admissions controversy}}\n\nThe university has been regarded as being [[elitist]] by some commentators,<ref>{{cite news|title =Elite uni aims to broaden its appeal|work=BBC News|accessdate =12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/1768564.stm | date=18 January 2002\n}}</ref> taking 41% of its undergraduate students from non-state schools, according to the most recent 2009/2010 figures, despite the fact that such pupils make up just 7% of the population<ref>{{cite web |title=Understated |publisher=Etan Smallman: Epigram Online |accessdate=12 December 2007 |url=http://www.epigram.org.uk/view.php?id=1583 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215155/http://www.epigram.org.uk/view.php?id=1583 |archivedate=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> and 18% of 16+ year old pupils across the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isc.co.uk/FactsFigures_PupilNumbers.htm |title=ISC Pupil Numbers \u2013 Independent Schools Council |publisher=Isc.co.uk |accessdate=21 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118083844/http://www.isc.co.uk/FactsFigures_PupilNumbers.htm |archivedate=18 January 2012 }}</ref> The intake of state school pupils at Bristol is lower than many Oxbridge colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/oxford-drops-below-cambridge-on-state-school-entrants/2012321.article|title=Oxford drops below Cambridge on state school entrants|date=27 March 2014|publisher=}}</ref> The high ratio of undergraduates from non-state school has led to some tension at the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetartpaper.com/articles/view/369 |title=The sad side of Bristol Uni |publisher=Thetartpaper.com |accessdate=28 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719012104/http://www.thetartpaper.com/articles/view/369 |archivedate=19 July 2009 }}</ref> In late February and early March 2003, Bristol became embroiled in a row about admissions policies, with some private schools threatening a boycott<ref>{{cite news|title=Private schools 'boycott' Bristol\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/2818263.stm | date=4 March 2003}}</ref> based on their claims that, in an effort to improve equality of access, the university was discriminating against their students. These claims were hotly denied by the university.<ref>{{cite news| title =Bristol remains firm on admissions\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/bristol/3014108.stm | date=23 June 2003}}</ref>\nIn August 2005, following a large-scale survey, the [[Independent Schools Council]] publicly acknowledged that there was no evidence of bias against applicants from the schools it represented.<ref>{{cite news|title='No bias' against private pupils\n| work = BBC News|accessdate=12 December 2007|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4161100.stm | date=17 August 2005}}</ref>\nThe university has a new admissions policy,<ref name=\"admit-policy\" /> which lays out in considerable detail the basis on which any greater or lesser weight may be given to particular parts of an applicant's backgrounds&nbsp;\u2013 in particular, what account may be taken of which school the applicant hails from. This new policy also encourages greater participation from locally resident applicants.\n\n== Campus ==\n[[File:QEH Prize Day 2004.JPG|thumb|200px|The Great Hall of the [[Wills Memorial Building]], here used for an award ceremony for the [[Queen Elizabeth's Hospital]]]]\n<!-- [[File:Willsmemorial.JPG|thumb|right|200px|The armorials on the [[Wills Memorial Building]] and some of the grotesques, the later designed by [[Jean Hahn]] which portray some of the then university staff.<ref>Carleton (1984), p130</ref>]] -->\nSome of the University of Bristol's buildings date to its pre-charter days when it was [[University College Bristol]]. These buildings were designed by [[Charles Hansom]], the younger brother of [[Joseph Hansom]], Joseph being the inventor of the [[Hansom Cab]]. These buildings suffered being built in stages due to financial pressure. George Oatley added to them a tower in memory of Albert Fry which can still be seen on University Road. The first large scale building project the University of Bristol undertook on gaining a charter was the Wills Memorial Building which it was hoped would be a symbol of academic permanence for the university and a memorial to the chief benefactor of the university, [[Henry Overton Wills]]. It was requested to the architect [[George Oatley]] that the building be built to last at least 400 years but the site purchased, at the top of [[Park Street, Bristol|Park Street]] suffered from an awkward slope and a desirability to link the building with the Museum and Art Gallery situated adjacent to the plot. The architecture critic [[Roger Gill (architecture critic)|Roger Gill]] has stated that the building is \"remarkable in size\" but noted that the \"ambience of a medieval University was strangely lacking\". He goes on to criticise the building as a \"sham\" and a \"folly\".<ref>Carleton (1984), p129</ref> The armorials on the Founder's Window represent all of the interests present at the founding of the University of Bristol including the Wills and Fry families. The [[Tyndalls Park]] Estate and [[Royal Fort House]] were also purchased from the trustees of the Tyndall family allowing the university to expand. Many Departments in the Faculty of Arts are housed in large Victorian houses which have been converted for teaching.<ref>Higher Education Quality Council (1993), p2</ref>\n\n[[Goldney gardens]] entered the property of the University of Bristol through [[George Alfred Wills|George Wills]] who had hoped to build an all-male hall of residence there. This was prevented due to the moral objection of the then warden of Clifton Hall House who objected to the idea of male and female residences being in such close proximity. University records show that Miss Starvey was prepared to resign over the issue and that she had the support of the then Chancellor [[Conwy Lloyd Morgan]].<ref>Carleton (1984), p132</ref> Eventually land was purchased in [[Stoke Bishop]] allowing [[Wills Hall]] to be bought, allowing the building of what has been described as a \"quasi-[[Oxbridge]]\" hall, to which was added the Dame Monica Wills Chapel by George Wills' widow after his death. [[File:Goldney2.jpg|thumb|200px|The Gardens of Goldney Hall were acquired by the Wills family]]Burwalls, a mansion house on the other side of the [[Avon Gorge]], was used as a halls of residence in the past and was a home of [[Sir George Oatley]]. The building is now used to house the Centre for Continuing Education.<ref name=\"burwalls\">{{cite web | title =Burwalls Centre for Continuing Education| publisher = University of Bristol |accessdate =16 June 2008 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/burwalls/}}</ref>\n\nMany of the more modern buildings, including Senate House and the newer parts of the HH Wills Physics Laboratory, were designed by [[Ralph Brentnall]] after funds from the University Grants Committee. He is also responsible for the extension to the Wills Memorial Building library which was completed to such standard that few now realise that is an extension to the original building.<ref>Carleton (1984), p138</ref> Brentnall oversaw the rebuilding of the Great Hall of the Wills Memorial Building after it was partly destroyed during the [[Bristol Blitz]] of World War II. The buildings of St Michael's Hill were rebuilt using hundreds of old photographs to recreate the original houses. The flats at Goldney Hall were designed by Michael Grice and received an award from the Civic Trust for their design.<ref>Carleton (1984), p139</ref> Bristol University owns some of the best examples of Georgian architecture in the city, the best examples being [[Royal Fort House]], [[Clifton Hill House]] and [[Goldney Hall]] despite some additions.<ref>Carleton (1984), p141</ref> The Victoria Rooms which house the Music Department were designed by [[Charles Dyer (architect)|Charles Dyer]] and is seen as a good example of a Greek revival movement in British architecture. The [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] of the building depicts a scene from ''The Advent of Morning'' designed by [[Jabez Tyley]].<ref>Carleton (1984), p136</ref> Its major feature was a large organ which has since been destroyed by fire.\n\nIn November 2016, the university announced that it plans to build a \u00a3300 million Temple Quarter Campus for c. 5,000 students, next to [[Bristol Temple Meads railway station]] within [[Bristol Temple Quarter Enterprise Zone]]. The new campus, which will include a [[business school]], digital research facilities and a student village, is expected to open in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/bristol-university-to-take-over-royal-mail-sorting-offices-by-temple-meads-for-new-300m-campus/story-29935566-detail/story.html |newspaper=[[Bristol Post]] |title=Bristol University to take over old sorting office by Temple Meads for new \u00a3300m campus |last=Yong |first=Michael |date=29 November 2016 |accessdate=29 November 2016 }}</ref> For the existing campus, there are plans to remodel Tyndall Avenue, pedestrianise the surrounding area and build a new library and resource hub.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/media-library/sites/university/documents/governance/policies/university-strategy.pdf |title= Brochure |website= www.bristol.ac.uk|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\n== Organisation and governance ==\n\n{{Main|Governance of the University of Bristol}}\nIn common with most UK universities, Bristol is headed formally by the [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]], currently [[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]] and led on a day-to-day basis by the [[vice-chancellor]], currently [[Hugh R. Brady|Hugh Brady]], who is the academic leader and chief executive. There are four pro vice-chancellors and three ceremonial pro-chancellors.<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|title=Governance: How the University is run|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/governance\n}}</ref> The chancellor may hold office for up to ten years and the pro-chancellors for up to three, unless the University Court determines otherwise,<ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 3 \u2013 The Chancellor | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 15 March 2000 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat3.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 4 \u2013 The Pro-Chancellors | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat4.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000416/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat4.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> but the vice-chancellor and pro-vice-chancellors have no term limits.<ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 5 \u2013 The Vice-Chancellor | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 15 March 2000 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat5.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000417/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat5.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Statute 6 \u2013 The Pro Vice-Chancellors | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 24 February 2004 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat6.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527000422/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat6.html |archivedate = 27 May 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The vice-chancellor is supported by a deputy vice-chancellor.\n\nResponsibility for running the university is held at an executive level by the vice-chancellor, but the council is the only body that can recommend changes to the university's statutes and charter,<ref name=\"council\">{{cite web| title=Council|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/council/\n}}</ref> with the exception of academic ordinances. These can only be made with the consent of the senate, the chief academic body in the university which also holds responsibility for teaching and learning, examinations and research and enterprise.<ref name=\"council\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Senate | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/senate/}}</ref> The chancellor and pro chancellors are nominated by council and appointed formally by court, whose additional powers are now limited to these appointments and a few others, including some lay members of council.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statute 13 \u2013 Powers of Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 7 May 2005 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/statutes/stat13.html\n}}</ref> Finally, Convocation, the body of all staff, ceremonial officers and graduates of the university, returns 100 members to court and one member to council,<ref name=\"gov\" /> but is otherwise principally a forum for discussion and to ensure graduates stay in touch with the university.\n\nThe university is made up of a number of schools and departments organised into six faculties:<ref>{{cite web | title = Academic Departments and Research Centres by Faculty | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =10 August 2007| url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/index/faculties/}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wills memorial library.JPG|thumb|right|The Wills Memorial Library of Law and Earth Sciences]]\n\n=== Faculty of Arts ===\n* School of Arts\n** Anthropology and Archaeology\n** Film and Television\n** Music\n** Philosophy\n** Theatre (see also the [[University of Bristol Theatre Collection]])\n* School of Humanities\n** Classics and Ancient History\n** English\n** History (Historical Studies)\n** History of Art (Historical Studies)\n** Religion and Theology\n* School of Modern Languages\n** French\n** German\n** Hispanic, Portuguese and Latin American Studies\n** Italian\n** Russian\n* Centre for English Language and Foundation Studies\n* Centre for Innovation\n\n=== Faculty of Engineering ===\n* School of Computer Science, Electrical and Electronic Engineering, and Engineering Mathematics\n** Computer Science\n** Electrical & Electronic Engineering\n** Engineering Mathematics\n* School of Civil, Aerospace and Mechanical Engineering\n** Aerospace Engineering\n** Civil Engineering\n** Mechanical Engineering\n\n[[File:UniversityofBristolEngineering.JPG|thumb|Faculty of Engineering Queen's Building]]\n\n=== Faculty of Life Sciences ===\n* School of Biological Sciences\n* School of Biochemistry\n* School of Cellular and Molecular Medicine\n* School of Physiology, Pharmacology and Neuroscience\n* School of Psychological Science\n\n[[File:University of Bristol, School of Chemistry.jpg|thumb|right|School of Chemistry]]\n\n=== Faculty of Science ===\n* School of Chemistry\n* School of Earth Sciences\n* School of Geographical Sciences\n* School of Mathematics\n* School of Physics\n** Interface Analysis Centre\n** Centre for Nanoscience & Quantum Information\n\n=== Faculty of Health Sciences ===\n* Bristol Dental School\n* Bristol Medical School\n** Population Health Sciences\n** Translational Health Sciences\n* Bristol Veterinary School\n* Centre for Health Sciences Education\n** Centre for Applied Anatomy\n** Master's in Teaching and Learning for Health Professionals\n\n=== Faculty of Social Sciences and Law ===\n* School of Education\n* School for Policy Studies\n* School of Economics, Finance and Management\n** Accounting and Finance\n** Centre for Market and Public Organisation\n** Economics\n** Management\n* School of Sociology, Politics and International Studies\n* University of Bristol Law School\n\n=== Academic dress ===\n{{Main|Academic dress of the University of Bristol}}\n[[File:UOB Masters hood.jpg|thumb|upright|Master's hood at the University of Bristol]]\nThe university specifies a mix of Cambridge and Oxford [[academic dress]]. For the most part, it uses Oxford-style gowns and Cambridge-style hoods, which are required to be 'university red'<ref name=\"costume\">{{cite web | title = Regulations for Academic and Official Costume | publisher = University of Bristol Regulations for Academic and Official Costume |accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/regscostume.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071126123449/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/regscostume.html |archivedate = 26 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> (see the logo at the top of the page)\n\n=== Logo and arms ===\n[[File:UniversityofBristollogo2.jpg|thumb|upright|University coat of arms]]\nIn 2004, the university unveiled its new crest. The icons in the crest are the sun for the Wills family, the dolphin for Colston, the horse for Fry and the ship-and-castle from the medieval seal of the City of Bristol, as also used in the coat of arms. The shape of the whole crest represents the open book of learning.<ref name=\"vis-ident\">{{cite web | title =  University of Bristol logo | publisher =  University of Bristol | accessdate =  2007-12-03 | url =  http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/logo.html | url-status =  dead | archiveurl =  https://web.archive.org/web/20071013010817/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/logo.html | archivedate =  13 October 2007 | df =  dmy-all }}</ref> This crest has replaced the university [[Coat of arms|arms]] shown, but the arms continue to be used where there is a specific historical or ceremonial requirement. The arms comprise:\n<center>\n''argent on a cross quadrate gules the arms of the City of Bristol between in pale and a sun in splendour (for Wills) and an open book proper, leaved and clasped or, and inscribed with the words Nisi quia Dominus, and in fesse to the sinister a dolphin embowed (for Colston), and to the dexter a horse courant (for Fry), both of the third.''\n</center>\nThe inscription on the book is the [[Latin]] opening of the 124th Psalm, ''\"If the Lord Himself had not (been on our side...)\"''.<ref name=\"arms\">{{cite web | title = The University Arms | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/arms.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927234000/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/visualidentity/arms.html | archivedate = 27 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Academic profile ==\n\n=== Admissions ===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ UCAS Admission Statistics\n!\n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|43,355\n|43,930\n|43,465\n|40,425\n|39,680\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate (%)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: B78 University of Bristol|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144926/download?token=Pkxxg1hu|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|71.3\n|69.4\n|67.3\n|70.6\n|61.8\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|5,790\n|5,530\n|5,385\n|5,165\n|4,810\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield (%)''']]\n|18.7\n|18.1\n|18.4\n|18.1\n|19.6\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|7.49\n|7.94\n|8.07\n|7.83\n|8.25\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">New [[UCAS Tariff]] system from 2016</ref>\n|n/a\n|184\n|485\n|476\n|486\n|}\nBristol had the 8th highest average entry qualification for undergraduates of any UK university in 2015, with new students averaging 485 [[UCAS Tariff|UCAS points]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards|website=Complete University Guide|title=University League Table 2018|accessdate=25 April 2017}}</ref> equivalent to just above AAAaa in [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A-level]] grades. Competition for places is high with an average 7.7 applications per place according to the 2014 Sunday Times League Tables, making it the joint 11th most competitive university in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/table/year/2014/type/derived/id/111|title=The Times and The Sunday Times - Education - Table UniversityGuide|last=HitCreative|website=st.hitcreative.com}}</ref> The university gives offers of admission to 67.3% of its applicants, the 8th lowest amongst the [[Russell Group]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Which elite universities have the highest offer rates |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2016/10/19/which-elite-universities-have-the-highest-offer-rates/|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2017 ''Times'' and ''Sunday Times'' Good University Guide, approximately 40% of Bristol's undergraduates come from independent schools.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://extras.thetimes.co.uk/gooduniversityguide/institutions/ |title=The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide 2017|work=[[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|The Good University Guide]] | location=London | accessdate=16 August 2016}}{{paywall}}</ref> In the 2016-17 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 78:5:17 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 55:45.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings and reputation===\n\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_W       = 74\n| QS_W         = 49\n| THE_W        = 87\n| LEIDEN_W     = 37\n| LINE_1       = 0\n| Complete     = 16\n| The_Guardian = 23\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 15\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Silver\n}}\nBristol is ranked in the top 10 universities in the UK in various university rankings including: QS World University Rankings, ARWU and Times Higher Education University Rankings.<ref name=\"Old school 'key to student place'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7003253.stm|title=Old school 'key to student place'|publisher=BBC |accessdate=31 January 2009 | date=20 September 2007}}</ref> Internationally, the 2020 [[QS World University Rankings]] placed Bristol at 49th overall in the world and 9th in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2020|title=QS World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|website=|publisher=Topuniversities|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> The 2020 QS World University Rankings for Graduate Employability also placed Bristol at 58th in the world and 9th in the UK in terms of reputation with employers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/employability-rankings/2020|title=Graduate Employability Rankings 2020|last=|first=|date=2019-09-10|website=Top Universities|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 December 2019}}</ref> Bristol was chosen as the ninth best university in the UK for the quality of graduates according to recruiters from the UK's major companies.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/best-uk-universities-chosen-major-employers | location=London | work=Times Higher Education | title=The best UK universities chosen by major employers | date=12 November 2015}}</ref> The [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings|Times Higher Education World University Ranking]] placed Bristol at 87th globally and 10th in the UK in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title=Times Higher Education World University Rankings 2020|last=|first=|date=|work=Times Higher Education|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> Another international ranking, the [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]] [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]], placed Bristol 64th globally and 8th in the UK in 2019.<ref name=\"AWRU 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/arwu2019.html|title=AWRU 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref> Bristol is ranked 47th in the world (and 6th in the UK) in the 2016 ''[[Round University Ranking]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roundranking.com/ranking.html|title=Round University Rankings 2016|publisher=RUR Rankings Agency|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref> The 2017 ''U.S. News & World Report'' ranks Bristol 76th in the world.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/rankings?page=8 |title=U.S. News and World Report Best Global Universities Rankings 2017 |magazine=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref> In 2019, it ranked 120th among the universities around the world by ''[[SCImago Institutions Rankings]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?sector=Higher%20educ.&country=all|title=SCImago Institutions Rankings - Higher Education - All Regions and Countries - 2019 - Overall Rank|website=www.scimagoir.com}}</ref>\n\nWithin the UK, Bristol was ranked 10th overall in ''The Sunday Times'' 10-year (1998\u20132007) average ranking of British universities based on consistent league table performance,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|title=University ranking based on performance over 10 years|work=The Times|accessdate=28 April 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080414064446/http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|archivedate=14 April 2008|year=2007|location=London|df=dmy}}</ref> and is a member of the '[[Sutton Trust#Sutton Trust 13|Sutton 13]]' of top ranked Universities in the UK. According to data published in ''[[The Times|The Sunday Times]]'', Bristol has the sixth-highest percentage of \"good honours\" of any UK university.<ref>{{cite news|title=University league table|publisher =The Sunday Time|accessdate=21 December 2014|url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/University_Guide/ | location=London | date=30 July 2014}}</ref> In the 2010 Centre for Higher Education's Development's Excellence Rankings, Bristol is one of only four UK universities (Oxford, UCL and Manchester) to be rated Excellent in all seven departments.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.excellenceranking.org/eusid/EUSID?module=Ort&do=show&id=12 |title=The Best European Universities |work=Die Zeit |date=3 November 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106004156/http://www.excellenceranking.org/eusid/EUSID?module=Ort&do=show&id=12 |archive-date=6 November 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The University of Bristol was the second most targeted university by the UK's top 100 employers, according to the Graduate Market in 2019 report produced by High Fliers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2019/january/high-fliers-report.html|title=January: University of Bristol is 2nd most-targeted university by employers {{!}} News {{!}} University of Bristol|last=Bristol|first=University of|website=www.bristol.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-03}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Geography Department, University of Bristol - geograph.org.uk - 201159.jpg|thumb|upright|left|School of Geographical Sciences]]\nThe following courses offered by the University of Bristol managed to reach top 5 in ''The Times'' ranking (2008): [[Department of Computer Science, University of Bristol|Computer Science]] (3rd); Electrical and Electronic Engineering(3rd); Civil Engineering(5th); Biological Sciences(3rd); Mathematics (3rd), and Psychology (4th). Furthermore, the [[QS World University Rankings]] place Bristol in the world's top 100 universities for all subject areas in 2011: Arts and Humanities (57th), Natural Sciences (40th), Engineering & IT (83rd), Social Sciences (65th) and Life Sciences (70th).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/university-bristol/wur |title=QS World University Subject Rankings for the University of Bristol |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110829070204/http://www.topuniversities.com/institution/university-bristol/wur |archivedate=29 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A further breakdown of the QS World University Natural Sciences Ranking shows the following: Earth Sciences (25th),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/earth |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045139/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/earth |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Mathematics (35th),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/mathematics |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045207/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/mathematics |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Environmental Sciences (39th),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/environmental-sciences|title=QS World University Rankings|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522045144/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/environmental-sciences|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Physics (41st),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/physics |title=QS World University Rankings |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522070542/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/physics |archivedate=22 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Chemistry (48th).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/chemistry|title=QS World University Rankings|accessdate=31 May 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522052050/http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2011/subject-rankings/natural-sciences/chemistry|archivedate=22 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bristol is particularly strong in the field of social sciences, particularly in economics, finance and management, and was rated fourth in the 2008 Guardian University Guide for Business and Management Studies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/efm/news/2008/16.html |title=Bristol University &#124; Bristol Ranked Fourth |publisher=Bristol.ac.uk |accessdate=28 January 2011}}</ref> In 2011, ''The Guardian'' also ranked Bristol as third in the UK for geography, just behind second place Oxford<ref>{{cite news|title=Guardian University Rankings 2011 (Geography and Environmental Studies)|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2010/jun/04/university-guide-geography-and-environmental-studies|publisher=The Guardian Newspaper|accessdate=23 April 2011|location=London|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> and ranked Bristol as 1st in the UK for Music.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2011/may/17/university-guide-music |title=University guide 2012: Music |work=The Guardian  |date= 17 May 2011|accessdate=21 January 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[File:University of Bristol buildings.JPG|thumb|Royal Fort and the Physics department]]\nIn The Complete University Guide 2013, Bristol ranked fifth for German,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=German|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 German;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> fourth for Russian,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Russian+%26+East+European+Languages|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Russian & East European Languages;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> third for mechanical and civil engineering,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Mechanical+Engineering|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Mechanical Engineering;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref> third for music<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Music|title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Music;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate= 24 January 2013|location= Bristol}}</ref> and second for drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?s=Drama%2c+Dance+%26+Cinematics |title=University Subject Tables 2013 \u2013 Drama, Dance & Cinematics;|date= 20 September 2012|accessdate=3 December 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nBristol is also known for its research strength, having 15 departments gaining the top grade of 5* in the 2001 [[Research Assessment Exercise]]. Overall, 36 out of 46 departments rated gained the top two ratings of 5 or 5*, and 76% of all the academic staff working in departments scored these top two levels.<ref>{{cite web|title=2001 Research Assessment Exercise Results |publisher=Higher Education and Research Opportunities |accessdate=21 December 2007 |url=http://195.194.167.103/Results/all/all.xls |format=xls |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070315214410/http://195.194.167.103/Results/all/all.xls |archivedate=15 March 2007 }}</ref> In terms of teaching strength, Bristol had an average Teaching Quality Assessment score of 22.05/24 before the TQA was abolished.<ref>{{cite web | title = HEFCE TQA/QAA SUBJECT REVIEW RESULTS TABLE 1993\u2013present | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/tsu/ext_quality/qaa/qaaresults.html}}</ref> Bristol's drop-out rate is also lower than the benchmark set by HEFCE of no more than 3.1%.<ref>{{cite news | title = University dropout rate |work=BBC News | accessdate =21 December 2007 | date = 19 July 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/6906012.stm}}</ref>\n\n=== Degrees ===\nBristol awards a range of [[academic degree]]s spanning bachelor's and master's degrees as well as junior doctorates and [[higher doctorate]]s. The [[post-nominal letters|postnominals]] awarded are the [[British degree abbreviations|degree abbreviations]] used commonly among British universities. The university is part of the [[Engineering Doctorate]] scheme,<ref>{{cite web | title = Engineering Doctorate Centre Details | publisher = Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council | accessdate =18 July 2006 | url=http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/PostgraduateTraining/EngineeringDoctorates/CentreDetailsAndContacts.htm |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060207094218/http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/PostgraduateTraining/EngineeringDoctorates/CentreDetailsAndContacts.htm |archivedate = 7 February 2006}}</ref> and awards the Eng. D. in [[systems engineering]], [[engineering management]], [[aerospace engineering]] and [[non-destructive evaluation]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for the Degree of Engineering Doctorate (Eng. D.) | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 August 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/engd.html}}</ref>\n\nBristol notably does not award by title any bachelor's degrees in music, which is available for study but awarded BA.(although it does award MMus and DMus), nor any degree in [[divinity]], since divinity is not available for study (students of theology are awarded a BA). Similarly, the university does not award BLitt (Bachelor of Letters), although it does award both MLitt and [[Doctor of Letters|DLitt]]. In regulations, the university does not name MD or [[Doctor of Dental Surgery|DDS]] as [[higher doctorate]]s, although they are in many universities<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for Dissertations for Doctoral and Masters Degrees... | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate=6 August 2007 | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/universitycalendar/regs/regulations/docmasters/dissregs.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20050307060331/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/universitycalendar/regs/regulations/docmasters/dissregs.html|archivedate=7 March 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref> as these degrees are normally accredited professional doctorates.\n\nThe degrees of DLitt, DSc, DEng, [[Doctor of Laws|LLD]] and DMus, whilst having regulations specifying the grounds for award,<ref>{{cite web | title = Regulations for the Degrees of Doctor of Letters, Doctor of Science, Doctor of Engineering and Doctor of Laws | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =6 August 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/dlittdscdenglld.html|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070903184022/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/regs/regulations/docmasters/dlittdscdenglld.html |archivedate = 3 September 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> are most often conferred as honorary degrees (''in honoris causa'').<ref>{{cite web | title=Honorary Graduates | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate=6 August 2007 | url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/cms/go/statutes/records/hongrads.html}}</ref> Those used most commonly are the DLitt, DSc and LLD, with the [[Master of Arts|MA]] (and occasionally the MLitt) also sometimes conferred honorarily for distinction in the local area or within the University.\n\n== Student life ==\n\n=== Students' Union ===\n[[File:070327 ukbris ubu01.jpg|thumb|right|[[University of Bristol Union]] building]]\n{{Main|University of Bristol Students' Union}}\n\nThe [[University of Bristol Students' Union]] (Bristol SU) located on Queen's Road in the Richmond Building is a founding member of the National Union of Students and is amongst the oldest [[students' union]]s in England. The union oversees three media outlets: UBTV, the Bristol University Radio Station ([[BURST]]) and the student newspaper ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]''. There is also a local branch of ''[[The Tab]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thetab.com/uk/bristol|title=The Tab - University of Bristol - the latest news, guides and comment|website=University of Bristol}}</ref> The Union is responsible for representing students' academic interests through elections of student representatives and democratic events. The Union is also responsible for the organisation of the annual Welcome Fair, the co-ordination of Bristol Student Community Action, which organises volunteering projects in the local community, and the organisation of entertainment events and over 400<ref>{{cite web | title = BSU Societies | publisher = University of Bristol Union | accessdate = 24 April 2015 | url = http://www.bristolsu.org.uk/activities/societies/atoz/ | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150904065202/http://www.bristolsu.org.uk/activities/societies/atoz/ | archivedate = 4 September 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> student groups, societies and clubs. Previous presidents have included [[Sue Lawley]] and former [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Lembit \u00d6pik]]. There is a separate union for postgraduate students, as well as an athletic union, which is a member of the [[British Universities & Colleges Sport]].<ref>{{cite web | title = BUSA Members | publisher = BUSA | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.busa.org.uk/fl/members.asp | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612212139/http://www.busa.org.uk/fl/members.asp | archivedate = 12 June 2007}}</ref> In distinction to the \"[[blue (university sport)|blues]]\" awarded for sporting excellence at Oxford and Cambridge, Bristol's most successful athletes are awarded \"reds\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Bristol Reds | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =3 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/sport/high-performance/bristol-reds.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Halls of residence ===\n{{Main|Halls of residence at the University of Bristol}}\n\n[[File:Wills Hall, University of Bristol.JPG|thumb|[[Wills Hall]]]]\n\nAccommodation for students is primarily in the central precinct of the university and two areas of Bristol: [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]] and [[Stoke Bishop]], known respectively as the West and North Villages.<ref name=\"prosp\">{{cite web | title = Accommodation Office | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =12 January 2014 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accommodation/}}</ref>\n\nIn Stoke Bishop, [[Wills Hall]] on the edge of the [[The Downs (Bristol)|Clifton Downs]] was the first to be opened, in 1929, by the then chancellor, Winston Churchill. Its original [[quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]] layout has been expanded twice, in 1962 and 1990.<ref name=\"prosp\" /> [[Churchill Hall]], named for the chancellor, followed in 1956, then [[Badock Hall]] in 1964.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Badock Hall Prospectus | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Badock/prospectus.shtml | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20050504043639/http://bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Badock/prospectus.shtml | archive-date = 4 May 2005 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> At the time of Badock Hall's establishment, some of the buildings were called [[Hiatt Baker Hall]], but two years later, Hiatt Baker moved to its own site and is now the largest hall in the university.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Hiatt Baker Hall History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/hiattbaker/history/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080607171646/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/hiattbaker/history/ | archive-date = 7 June 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The first self-catering hall in Stoke Bishop was [[University Hall (Bristol)|University Hall]], established in 1971 with expansion in 1992.<ref name=\"prosp\" />\n\n[[File:Goldney1.jpg|thumb|[[Goldney Hall]]]]\nIn Clifton, [[Goldney Hall]] was built first in the early 18th century by the wealthy merchant [[Goldney family]] and eventually became part of the university in 1956.<ref>{{cite web | title = Goldney Hall History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Goldney/history.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070707143643/http://bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Goldney/history.htm | archive-date = 7 July 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> It is a popular location for filming, with ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia (TV miniseries)|The Chronicles of Narnia]]'', ''[[The House of Eliott]]'' and ''[[Truly, Madly, Deeply]]'', as well as episodes of ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' and ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]'', being filmed there.<ref>{{cite web |title=Open day for Bristol's well-known garden |url=http://www.bris.ac.uk/Depts/Info-Office/news/archive/goldney.htm |publisher=University of Bristol |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> The [[Grotto at Goldney House|Grotto]] in the grounds is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|desc=Grotto approximately 85 metres south of Goldney House, Clifton Hill, Bristol |accessdate=21 December 2007 |num=1202104 }}</ref> [[Clifton Hill House]] is another Grade I listed building now used as student accommodation in Clifton. The original building was constructed between 1745 and 1750 by [[Isaac Ware]], and has been used by the university since its earliest days in 1909.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{NHLE|desc=Clifton Hill House and attached front walls, Clifton Hill, Bristol |accessdate=21 December 2007 |num=1280480 }}</ref> [[Manor Hall]] comprises five separate buildings, the principal of which was erected from 1927\u20131932 to the design of [[George Oatley]] following a donation from [[Henry Herbert Wills]]. Manor Hall houses the largest and most dated rooms, some dating back to the early 20th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accommodation/undergraduate/residences/manor/|title=Manor Hall {{!}} Accommodation Office {{!}} University of Bristol|last=Bristol|first=University of|website=www.bristol.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> One of its annexes, Manor House, has recently been refurbished and officially 'reopened' in 1999.<ref name=\"prosp\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = Manor Hall and Sinclair House History | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Manor/new/history.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070705113326/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/Depts/Manor/new/history.htm | archive-date = 5 July 2007 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[File:CliftonHillHouse.JPG|thumb|[[Clifton Hill House]]]]\n\nOn the central precinct sits The Hawthorns, a student house accommodating 115 undergraduate students.<ref>{{cite web | title = The Hawthorns webpage | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/studenthouses/sths/haw/facts.html | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =13 July 2011}}</ref> The house started life as a collection of villas built somewhere between 1888 and 1924<ref>Bristol Record Office: Volume 19, Folio 74 and Volume 22, Folio 34</ref> that were later converted, bit by bit, into a hotel by John Dingle.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Bristol Supplementary Planning Document Number 11 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/estates/documents/masterplan/masterplan-appendix11.pdf | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 13 July 2011 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120111155720/http://www.bristol.ac.uk/estates/documents/masterplan/masterplan-appendix11.pdf | archivedate = 11 January 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The Hawthorns also houses conferencing facilities, the staff refectory and bar, the Accommodation Office and the Student Houses Office. 33 Colston Street was opened in the city centre in October 2011 after the University acquired the property in 2009.<ref name=\"prosp\" /> Several of the residences in the central precinct are more recent and have been built and are managed by third-party organisations under exclusivity arrangements with the University. These include New Bridewell House, opened in 2016, which is in the former police HQ, it includes en-suite bedrooms and studios and is operated by Fresh Student Housing, Unite House and Chantry Court, opened in 2000 and 2003 respectively by the [[UNITE Group]],<ref>{{cite web | title = UNITE House in Bristol | publisher = UNITE Group plc | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1UNITE|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224080516/http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1UNITE |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Chantry Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/chantry.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022103531/http://bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/chantry.html | archivedate = 22 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Chantry Court in Bristol | publisher = UNITE Group plc | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1CHANT|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071224080507/http://www.unite-students.com/QuickSearch.do?propCode=BS1CHANT |archivedate = 24 December 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> as well as Dean's Court (2001, postgraduates only) and Woodland Court (2005), both run by the Dominion Housing Group.<ref>{{cite web | title = Dean's Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate = 21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/dc.html | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071022103536/http://bristol.ac.uk/accom/pgs/dc.html | archivedate = 22 October 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Woodland Court | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =21 December 2007 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/accom/woodland.html}}</ref>\n\nAll of the main halls elect groups of students to the [[Junior Common Room#Bristol|Junior Common Room]] to organise the halls social calendar for the next year. Residents of student houses, private accommodation and students living at home become members of Orbital&nbsp;\u2013 a society organising social events for students throughout the year.<ref name=\"prosp\" />\n\n== Notable people ==\n{{Main|List of University of Bristol people}}\n\n=== Academics ===\nCurrent academics at the University of Bristol include 21 fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]], 13 fellows of the [[British Academy]], 13 fellows of the [[Royal Academy of Engineering]] and 44 fellows of the [[Royal Society]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Nobel Prizes and Fellowships|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=2 October 2011|url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/distinctions}}</ref> These include, Sir [[Michael Berry (physicist)|Michael Berry]], one of the discoverers of [[quantum mechanics]]' \"[[geometric phase]]\",<ref>{{cite web | title = Michael Berry | publisher = HP Labs | accessdate =29 December 2007 | url = http://www.hpl.hp.com/news/lectures/Abstracts/MichaelBerry.htm}}</ref> [[John Rarity]] international expert on [[quantum optics]], [[quantum cryptography]] and quantum communication, [[David May (computer scientist)|David May]], computer scientist and lead architect for the [[transputer]],<ref name=whoswho>{{Who's Who | surname = MAY | othernames = Prof. (Michael) David | id = U27080 | volume = 2015 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]}} {{subscription required}}</ref> [[Mark Horton (archaeologist)|Mark Horton]], a British maritime and historical archaeologist.\n\nAcademics in computer science include, [[Dave Cliff (computer scientist)|David Cliff]], inventor of the seminal \"ZIP\" trading algorithm, [[Peter Flach]], [[Mike Fraser (computer scientist)|Mike Fraser]], Professor of Human-computer interaction, [[Julian Gough (scientist)|Julian Gough]] and  [[Nigel Smart (cryptographer)|Nigel Smart]].\n\nMarine [[ecologist]] Dr Rose Crichton is currently working at Bristol. Rose's PhD thesis on [[Gammaridea]] helped to raise awareness of the effects of climate change on marine crustaceans. Dr Crichton is director of the Bristol Fish Project.<ref>{{cite web | title = Dr Rose Crichton|publisher=Bristol Fish Project|accessdate=6 October 2019|url=https://bristolfish.org/about/core-team/dr-rose-crichton/}}</ref>\n\nPast academics of the university include, [[Patricia Broadfoot]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Gloucestershire]], [[Nigel Thrift]], Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Warwick]], and [[Wendy Larner]], Provost of [[Victoria University of Wellington]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Patricia Broadfoot |publisher=University of Gloucestershire |accessdate=29 December 2007 |url=http://www.glos.ac.uk/council/patricia-broadfoot.cfm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020005514/http://www.glos.ac.uk/council/patricia-broadfoot.cfm |archivedate=20 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = About the Vice-Chancellor | accessdate =29 December 2007 | publisher = University of Warwick | url = http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/about/management/vc|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072647/http://www2.warwick.ac.uk/about/management/vc |archivedate = 15 December 2007}}</ref> [[Anthony Epstein]], co-discoverer of the [[Epstein-Barr virus]], was Professor of [[Pathology]] at the university from 1968\u20131982,<ref>{{cite press release | title = Honorary Fellowship for Professor Sir Anthony Epstein | publisher = University of Bristol | accessdate =29 December 2007 | date = 18 July 2006 | url = http://www.bristol.ac.uk/news/2006/1030.html}}</ref> Sir [[John Lennard-Jones]], discoverer of the [[Lennard-Jones potential]] in physics<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lennard-Jones, J. E. | title = Cohesion | journal = Proceedings of the Physical Society | year = 1931 | volume = 43 | pages = 461\u2013482 | doi = 10.1088/0959-5309/43/5/301 | issue = 5|bibcode = 1931PPS....43..461L}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = H. Jones | title = Notes on Work at the University of Bristol, 1930-7 | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, Series A | year = 1931 | volume = 371 | pages = 52\u201355 | issue = 1744| doi = 10.1098/rspa.1980.0056 }}</ref> and [[Alfred Marshall]], one of the University College's principals and influential economist in the latter part of the 19th century.<ref>{{cite web | title = Alfred Marshall | publisher = Economy Professor | accessdate =29 December 2007 | url = http://www.economyprofessor.com/theorists/alfredmarshall.php}}</ref> Mathematicians and philosophers [[Rohit Parikh]] and [[Brian Rotman]] lectured in the mathematics department, and philosopher of science [[Paul Feyerabend]] taught in the Department of Philosophy.\n\nThe University of Bristol is associated with three [[Ig Nobel Prizes]], an award for unusual or trivial achievements in scientific research. Sir [[Michael Berry (physicist)|Michael Berry]] shared the award (with [[Andre Geim]], a Nobel Laureate) for using [[magnets]] to levitate a frog.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Berry | first1 = M. V. | authorlink1 = Michael Berry (physicist)| last2 = Geim | first2 = A. K. | authorlink2 = Andre Geim| title = Of flying frogs and levitrons | journal = European Journal of Physics | volume = 18 | issue = 4 | pages = 307 | year = 1997 | doi = 10.1088/0143-0807/18/4/012| url = http://www.physics.bristol.ac.uk/people/berry_mv/the_papers/Berry285.pdf|bibcode = 1997EJPh...18..307B }}</ref> Gareth Jones also shared an Ig Nobel prize for scientifically documenting [[fellatio]] in [[fruit bat]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Tan | first1 = M. | last2 = Jones | first2 = G. | last3 = Zhu | first3 = G. | last4 = Ye | first4 = J. | last5 = Hong | first5 = T. | last6 = Zhou | first6 = S. | last7 = Zhang | first7 = S. | last8 = Zhang | first8 = L. | editor1-last = Hosken | editor1-first = David | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0007595 | title = Fellatio by fruit bats prolongs copulation time | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 4 | issue = 10 | pages = e7595 | year = 2009 | pmid =  19862320| pmc =2762080 | bibcode = 2009PLoSO...4.7595T }}</ref> Dr. Len Fisher was awarded the 1999 prize for physics for calculating the optimal way to dunk a biscuit.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Fisher | first1 = L. | title = Physics takes the biscuit | journal = Nature | volume = 397 | issue = 6719 | pages = 469 | year = 1999 | doi = 10.1038/17203 | bibcode = 1999Natur.397..469F }}</ref>\n\n=== Alumni ===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:JonathanEvans.jpg|[[Jonathan Evans (MI5 officer)|Jonathan Evans]], former Head of [[MI5]]\nFile:Alastair Stewart 31.08.07.jpg|[[Alastair Stewart]], TV journalist\nFile:Derren Victor Brown.jpg|[[Derren Brown]], illusionist\nFile:Simon Pegg 01.jpg|[[Simon Pegg]], actor and writer\nFile:David Walliams.JPG|[[David Walliams]], comedian\n</gallery>\n\nBristol alumnus [[Paul Dirac]] went on to win the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1933 for his contribution to the formulation of quantum mechanics and is considered one of the most significant physicists of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Dirac (1902 - 1984) |url=https://www.physicsoftheuniverse.com/scientists_dirac.html |publisher=The Physics of the Universe |accessdate=27 August 2018}}</ref> Other notable scientists include [[Dani Rabaiotti]], an environmental scientist and science communicator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zsl.org/science/users/daniella-rabaiotti|title=Daniella Rabaiotti|website=Zoological Society of London (ZSL)|language=en|access-date=2018-04-07}}</ref> [[Eliahu Nissim]] was a Professor of Aeronautical Engineering, and the President of the [[Open University of Israel]].\n\nOther notable [[alumnus|alumni]] include writers [[Dick King-Smith]], [[Sarah Kane]], Olivier award-winning playwright [[Laura Wade]], [[Angela Carter]], [[Dorothy Simpson]], [[David Gibbins]] and [[David Nicholls (writer)|David Nicholls]], author of the novel ''[[Starter for Ten (novel)|Starter for Ten]]'', turned into a screenplay set in the University of Bristol.<ref>{{cite web|title =Starter for Ten|publisher=BBC Bristol|accessdate=21 December 2007|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/bristol/content/articles/2006/06/26/starter_feature.shtml}}</ref> [[Mark Simmons (author)|Mark Simmons]], author of business books, [[Will Hutton]], economist, author, commentator.\n\nIn entertainment and current affairs former students include, journalist and McMafia author [[Misha Glenny]], [[James Landale]], BBC News Chief Political Correspondent who founded the university independent newspaper ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]'', author and journalist [[Julie Myerson]], [[William Lewis (journalist)|William Lewis]], editor-in-chief of the Telegraph Media Group, [[Derren Brown]], illusionist, [[Sue Lawley]], Radio 4 presenter, [[Alastair Stewart]], newsreader and [[Dominic Waghorn]], [[Sky News]] US Correspondent. [[Susanna Reid]], [[ITV Breakfast]] anchor studied Politics, Philosophy and Law at the university between 1989 and 1992 and was also editor of the student newspaper, ''[[Epigram (newspaper)|Epigram]]''.\n\nIn comedy, [[Matt Lucas]] and [[David Walliams]],<ref>{{cite web | title =Notable alumni| publisher = Bristol University| accessdate =21 December 2007| url=http://www.alumni.bristol.ac.uk/NetCommunity/Page.aspx?pid=190&srcid=238}}</ref> [[Simon Pegg]], [[Chris Morris (satirist)|Chris Morris]], creator of the controversial ''[[Brass Eye]]'' and [[Jon Richardson (entertainer)|Jon Richardson]]. Other comedy stars include [[Chris Langham]], of [[The Thick of It]] fame, standup comic [[Marcus Brigstocke]] and [[Jamie Demetriou]], creator and writer of [[Stath Lets Flats]].\n\nNotable alumni from the Film and Television Production department include film directors [[Mick Jackson (director)|Mick Jackson]], [[Michael Winterbottom]], [[Marc Evans]], [[Christopher Smith (director)|Christopher Smith]], [[Alex Cox]], [[Peter Webber]] and [[Maddie Moate]].\n\nOther alumni include, [[Albert II, Prince of Monaco]], musician [[James Blunt]], former Liberal Democrat MP [[Lembit \u00d6pik]] was President of Bristol University Students' Union during his time. [[Jonathan Evans, Baron Evans of Weardale|Sir Jonathan Evans]]  former head of MI5, [[Anne McClain]], member of the 2013 NASA Astronaut Class<ref>{{YouTube|Aj6HTM33pBY}}</ref> and [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]], [[Chairperson of the African Union Commission]] from October 2012 to January 2017 amongst many others.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[CHOMBEC]]\n* [[Education in Bristol]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n*[[University of Bristol Theatre Collection]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last= Carleton |first= Don |date= 1984 |title= University for Bristol: A History in Text and Pictures |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-200-3 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Delany |first= Rosalind |date= 2002 |title= How Did This Garden Grow?: The History of the Botanic Gardens of the University of Bristol |publisher= Friends of Bristol University Botanic Garden |isbn= 0-9543504-0-5 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Crossley Evans |first= M. J. |date= 1994 |title= A History of Wills Hall University of Bristol |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-421-9 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Whittingham |first= Sarah |date= 2003 |title= Wills Memorial Building |publisher= University of Bristol |isbn= 0-86292-541-X }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|University of Bristol}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.bristol.ac.uk/}}\n* [https://www.bristolsu.org.uk/ Bristol SU] (Students' Union)\n\n{{University of Bristol|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Universities and colleges in South West England}}\n{{Education in Bristol}}\n{{Worldwide Universities Network}}\n{{Coimbra Group}}\n{{Russell Group}}\n{{CDIO}}\n}}\n{{good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bristol, University Of}}\n[[Category:University of Bristol|University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1909]]\n[[Category:Russell Group]]\n[[Category:1909 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:HSA Foundation members]]\n", "name_user": "Trivia64", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAcademic dress", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Bristol"}
{"title_page": "Cynthia Lai", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Cynthia Lai\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| native_name        = \u5c01\u8cf4\u6842\u971e\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| office1      = [[Toronto City Council]]lor for [[Scarborough North (provincial electoral district)|Ward 23 (Scarborough North)]]\n| term_start1  = December 1, 2018\n| term_end1    = \n| preceded1  = Ward Established\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = \n| residence    = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| religion     = \n| nationality  = [[Chinese-Canadian]]\n| spouse       = C. K. Fung\n| occupation   = \n}}\n\n'''Cynthia Lai''' ({{audio|help=no|Cynthialainame.ogg|Listen}}) is a [[Chinese-Canadian]] politician, who was elected to the [[Toronto City Council]] in the [[2018 Toronto municipal election|2018 municipal election]].<ref name=wins>[https://www.thestar.com/news/toronto-election/2018/10/22/subway-backer-cynthia-lai-claims-open-seat-in-ward-23-scarborough-north.html \"Subway backer Cynthia Lai claims open seat in Ward 23, Scarborough North\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 22, 2018.</ref> She represents [[Scarborough North (provincial electoral district)|Ward 23 (Scarborough North)]], which she has been a resident of.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cynthialai.com/aprg/aboutus.aspx|title=About Councillor Lai|website=www.cynthialai.com|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Lai immigrated from [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] in 1972 and has lived in [[Toronto]] ever since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cynthialai.com/aprg/aboutus.aspx|title=About Councillor Lai|website=www.cynthialai.com|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her election, Lai worked as a realtor and was president of the Toronto Real Estate Board.<ref name=wins/> \n\n==Electoral record==\n\n===2018===\n===Ward 23 Scarborough North===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:200px;text-align:left;padding-left:5px;\"| Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:88px;\" | Votes\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:95px;\" | Percentage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:150px;\"| Registration Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:500px;text-align:left;padding-left:5px;\"| Notes\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|'''[[Cynthia Lai]]'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|'''5,589'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|'''27.02%'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|May 28, 2018 \n|Endorsed by ''[[Toronto Sun]]''.<ref name=sun>{{Cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/news/local-news/toronto-sun-endorsements-for-city-council|title=Toronto Sun endorsements for city council|date=2018-10-21|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Maggie Chi\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|4,137\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|20.00%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|June 19, 2018 \n|Worked as a constituency assistant to former Councillor Chin Lee, Ward 41, for 5 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/toronto-election/2018/09/30/wide-open-scarborough-north-race-draws-diverse-array-of-candidates.html|title=Wide open Scarborough North race draws diverse array of candidates {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref> Endorsement and support from Chin Lee (former City Councillor), Glen De Baeremaeker (Deputy Mayor for Scarborough), Shaun Chen (Member of Parliament, Scarborough North), Tom Chang (President of the Brimley Forest Community Association), Gary Loughlin (President of the C.D Farqhuarson Community Association).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.maggiechi.ca/blank |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011133355/https://www.maggiechi.ca/blank |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Felicia Samuel \n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|3,702\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|17.89%\n|valign