en-seat-in-ward-23-scarborough-north.html \"Subway backer Cynthia Lai claims open seat in Ward 23, Scarborough North\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 22, 2018.</ref> She represents [[Scarborough North (provincial electoral district)|Ward 23 (Scarborough North)]], which she has been a resident of.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cynthialai.com/aprg/aboutus.aspx|title=About Councillor Lai|website=www.cynthialai.com|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref> Lai immigrated from [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] in 1972 and has lived in [[Toronto]] ever since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cynthialai.com/aprg/aboutus.aspx|title=About Councillor Lai|website=www.cynthialai.com|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\nPrior to her election, Lai worked as a realtor and was president of the [[Toronto Real Estate Board]].<ref name=wins/> \n\n==Electoral record==\n\n===2018===\n===Ward 23 Scarborough North===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:200px;text-align:left;padding-left:5px;\"| Candidate\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:88px;\" | Votes\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:95px;\" | Percentage\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:150px;\"| Registration Date\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background-color:#bfdeff;width:500px;text-align:left;padding-left:5px;\"| Notes\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|'''[[Cynthia Lai]]'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|'''5,589'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|'''27.02%'''\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|May 28, 2018 \n|Endorsed by ''[[Toronto Sun]]''.<ref name=sun>{{Cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/news/local-news/toronto-sun-endorsements-for-city-council|title=Toronto Sun endorsements for city council|date=2018-10-21|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref>\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Maggie Chi\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|4,137\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|20.00%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|June 19, 2018 \n|Worked as a constituency assistant to former Councillor Chin Lee, Ward 41, for 5 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/toronto-election/2018/09/30/wide-open-scarborough-north-race-draws-diverse-array-of-candidates.html|title=Wide open Scarborough North race draws diverse array of candidates {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref> Endorsement and support from Chin Lee (former City Councillor), Glen De Baeremaeker (Deputy Mayor for Scarborough), Shaun Chen (Member of Parliament, Scarborough North), Tom Chang (President of the Brimley Forest Community Association), Gary Loughlin (President of the C.D Farqhuarson Community Association).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.maggiechi.ca/blank |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011133355/https://www.maggiechi.ca/blank |archive-date=October 11, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Felicia Samuel \n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|3,702\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|17.89%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|July 25, 2018\n|Former provincial NDP candidate. Endorsed by Toronto & York District Labour Council,<ref name=\"tydlc\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016123439/http://www.labourcouncil.ca/uploads/8/8/6/1/8861416/endorsementlistseptember27th2018.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=2018-10-16|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref> Progress Toronto,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.progresstoronto.ca/campaign-2018-scarborough-north|title=Council Ward 23 \u2013 Scarborough North|website=Progress Toronto|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>  ''Toronto Star'',<ref name=starendorse2>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/editorials/2018/10/16/these-are-the-council-members-toronto-needs.html| title=These are the council members Toronto needs| date=October 16, 2018| work=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref> and ''NOW'' magazine.<ref name=now>{{Cite web|url=https://nowtoronto.com/api/content/2ed67d98-d23c-11e8-a0df-120e7ad5cf50/|title=Toronto Election 2018: A voter's guide to the good, bad, ugly and progressive choices for council|last=DiMatteo|first=Enzo|date=2018-10-17|website=NOW Magazine|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-02}}</ref>\n|-\n\n|valign=\"top\"|Neethan Saba\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|2,808\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|13.57%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|July 27, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|James Chow \n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1,487\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|7.19%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|May 16, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Ashwani Bhardwaj\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1,259\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|6.09%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|July 25, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Sheraz Khan\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|453\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|2.19%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|July 27, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Dameon Halstead\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|391\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1.89%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|June 12, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Mahboob Mian\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|335\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1.62%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|July 9, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Sandeep Srivastava\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|273\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1.32%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|June 26, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|valign=\"top\"|Anthony Internicola \n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|254\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"right\"|1.23%\n|valign=\"top\" align=\"center\"|May 8, 2018 \n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Toronto City Councillors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lai, Cynthia}}\n[[Category:Canadian politicians of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Toronto city councillors]]\n[[Category:Women in Ontario politics]]\n[[Category:Women municipal councillors in Canada]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Yunshui", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Toronto Real Estate Boardclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cynthia_Lai"}
{"title_page": "Lake Narach", "text_new": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Narach\n| image = Nara\u010d - 5.jpg\n| caption = Lake Narach\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Minsk Voblast|Minsk Province]]\n| coords = {{coord|54|51|09|N|26|44|59|E|region:BY_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Belarus\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Belarus\n| length = {{convert|12.8|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| area = {{convert|79.6|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|24.8|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|710|e6m3|acre.ft|abbr=out}}\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|41|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Narach''' ({{lang-be|\u041d\u0430\u0301\u0440\u0430\u0447}}, ''Nara\u010d'' {{IPA-be|\u02c8narat\u0361\u0282|pron}}; {{lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0447\u044c}}, ''Naro\u010dj''; {{lang-lt|Narutis}}, {{lang-pl|Narocz}}) is a [[lake]] in north-western [[Belarus]] ([[Myadzyel District]], [[Minsk Region]]), located in the basin of the [[Viliya]] river. It is the largest lake in Belarus (in 1921\u201339 it was the largest lake of [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]).\n\nNarach is a part of the '''Narach lake group''' (the others being [[Lake Miastra|Miastra]] ({{lang-be|\u041c\u044f\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430}}), [[Lake Batoryn|Batoryn]] ({{lang-be|\u0411\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u043d}}), Blednaje ({{lang-be|\u0411\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0435}}). It was formed about 11 thousand years ago after the [[Pleistocene]] ice ages. It has a surface area of 79.6&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, a wider length of 12.8&nbsp;km, a maximum depth of 24.8 m, average depth of 8.9 m,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/238-main-characteristics-of-the-largest-lakes-of-belarus.html |title = Main characteristics of the largest lakes. Main Geographic Characteristics of the Republic of Belarus |year = 2012 |website = Land of Ancestors |accessdate = 30 August 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130929085748/http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/238-main-characteristics-of-the-largest-lakes-of-belarus.html |archive-date = 29 September 2013 |url-status = dead }}</ref> a volume of 710 million cubic meters. The lake is surrounded with pine forests. The [[Narach River]] flows out of it.\n\nNarach is an abode of 22 genera of fish, as the [[eel]], [[Esox|pike]], [[burbot]], etc. The shore and islets are nested by different birds, as the [[mute swan]], [[fish hawk]], [[tarrock]], [[Little grebe|dabchick]].\n\n==History==\nPeople settled near the lake about 10 thousand years ago. Linguists think that its name is probably from the [[Proto-Indo-European language|Indo-European]] root *''nar''- often found in names of bodies of water (e.g., the [[Nara River|Nara]] and [[Neris]] rivers).<ref>E.M. Pospelov, ''Geograficheskie nazvaniya mira'' (Moscow: Russkie slovari, 1998), p. 283.</ref> Archaeologists have excavated many burial mounds of the [[Baltic people|Baltic]] and [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] people that lived around Narach.\n\nSince the [[Middle Ages]], the local inhabitants have lived mainly by fishing and farming. In the 19th century, the most profitable work was fishing of crayfish. In the 20th century, the [[eel]] became the main marketable fish.\n\nDuring [[World War I]], the surrounding area was a focal point of the [[Lake Naroch Offensive]] (March\u2013April 1916), an inconclusive offensive operation mounted by forces of the [[Imperial Russian Army]] against the [[German Army (German Empire)|German army]].\n\nIn 1919, German composer [[Siegfried Wagner]] set to music a poem by G\u00fcnther Holstein (1892-1931) about a military battle, called ''Nacht am Narocz'' (Night at lake Narach).\n\nIn the 1930s, the fishers of Narach rose against Polish authorities defending their right to exploit the lake.\n\nSince the 1950s, the lake has become a popular [[resort]] and [[tourism]] site, located in the [[resort town]] of [[Narach (town)|Narach]]. A [[Young Pioneer camp]] of national importance ''[[Zubryonok]]'' was located near the lake. After the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] the camp was reformed into the National Children's Recreational Camp \"[[Zubrania]]\", which is now the most important children's recreational camp in Belarus.\n\nIn 1999, the [[government of Belarus]] created the [[Narachanski National Park]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lake Naroch Offensive]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Nara\u010d Lake}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Belarus|Narach]]\n[[Category:Geography of Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:Myadzyel District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox lake\n| name = Lake Narach\n| image = Nara\u010d - 5.jpg\n| caption = Lake Narach\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Minsk Voblast|Minsk Province]]\n| coords = {{coord|54|51|09|N|26|44|59|E|region:BY_type:waterbody|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Belarus\n| type = \n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = Belarus\n| length = {{convert|12.8|km|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| area = {{convert|79.6|km2|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|24.8|m|abbr=on}}\n| volume = {{convert|710|e6m3|acre.ft|abbr=out}}\n| residence_time = \n| shore = {{convert|41|km|abbr=on}}\n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}\n'''Lake Narach''' ({{lang-be|\u041d\u0430\u0301\u0440\u0430\u0447}}, ''Nara\u010d'' {{IPA-be|\u02c8narat\u0361\u0282|pron}}; {{lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0447\u044c}}, ''Naro\u010dj''; {{lang-lt|Narutis}}, {{lang-pl|Narocz}}) is a [[lake]] in north-western [[Belarus]] ([[Myadzyel District]], [[Minsk Region]]), located in the basin of the [[Viliya]] river. It is the largest lake in Belarus (in 1921\u201339 it was the largest lake of [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]).\n\nNarach is a part of the '''Narach lake group''' (the others being [[Lake Miastra|Miastra]] ({{lang-be|\u041c\u044f\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430}}), [[Lake Batoryn|Batoryn]] ({{lang-be|\u0411\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u043d}}), Blednaje ({{lang-be|\u0411\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0435}})). It was formed about 11 thousand years ago after the [[Pleistocene]] ice ages. It has a surface area of 79.6&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, a wider length of 12.8&nbsp;km, a maximum depth of 24.8 m, average depth of 8.9 m,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/238-main-characteristics-of-the-largest-lakes-of-belarus.html |title = Main characteristics of the largest lakes. Main Geographic Characteristics of the Republic of Belarus |year = 2012 |website = Land of Ancestors |accessdate = 30 August 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130929085748/http://landofancestors.com/travel/statistics/geography/238-main-characteristics-of-the-largest-lakes-of-belarus.html |archive-date = 29 September 2013 |url-status = dead }}</ref> a volume of 710 million cubic meters. The lake is surrounded with pine forests. The [[Narach River]] flows out of it.\n\nNarach is an abode of 22 genera of fish, as the [[eel]], [[Esox|pike]], [[burbot]], etc. The shore and islets are nested by different birds, as the [[mute swan]], [[fish hawk]], [[tarrock]], [[Little grebe|dabchick]].\n\n==History==\nPeople settled near the lake about 10 thousand years ago. Linguists think that its name is probably from the [[Proto-Indo-European language|Indo-European]] root *''nar''- often found in names of bodies of water (e.g., the [[Nara River|Nara]] and [[Neris]] rivers).<ref>E.M. Pospelov, ''Geograficheskie nazvaniya mira'' (Moscow: Russkie slovari, 1998), p. 283.</ref> Archaeologists have excavated many burial mounds of the [[Baltic people|Baltic]] and [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] people that lived around Narach.\n\nSince the [[Middle Ages]], the local inhabitants have lived mainly by fishing and farming. In the 19th century, the most profitable work was fishing of crayfish. In the 20th century, the [[eel]] became the main marketable fish.\n\nDuring [[World War I]], the surrounding area was a focal point of the [[Lake Naroch Offensive]] (March\u2013April 1916), an inconclusive offensive operation mounted by forces of the [[Imperial Russian Army]] against the [[German Army (German Empire)|German army]].\n\nIn 1919, German composer [[Siegfried Wagner]] set to music a poem by G\u00fcnther Holstein (1892-1931) about a military battle, called ''Nacht am Narocz'' (Night at lake Narach).\n\nIn the 1930s, the fishers of Narach rose against Polish authorities defending their right to exploit the lake.\n\nSince the 1950s, the lake has become a popular [[resort]] and [[tourism]] site, located in the [[resort town]] of [[Narach (town)|Narach]]. A [[Young Pioneer camp]] of national importance ''[[Zubryonok]]'' was located near the lake. After the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] the camp was reformed into the National Children's Recreational Camp \"[[Zubrania]]\", which is now the most important children's recreational camp in Belarus.\n\nIn 1999, the [[government of Belarus]] created the [[Narachanski National Park]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lake Naroch Offensive]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commonscat-inline|Nara\u010d Lake}}\n\n[[Category:Lakes of Belarus|Narach]]\n[[Category:Geography of Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:Myadzyel District]]\n", "name_user": "Gian piero milanetti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Narach"}
{"title_page": "Right at Home Realty", "text_new": "{{About|the realtor|the care provider|Right at Home}}\n{{Infobox company \n| name = Right at Home Realty, Inc.\n| logo = [[File:Right At Home Realty Company Logo.png|Right at Home Realty Company Logo]]\n| type = [[Private company|Private]]\n| foundation = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario|ON]] (2004)\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, ON]]\n| key_people = Ronald E. Peddicord (Co-Founder / Chairman),Howard Drukarsh (Co-Founder / Retired)\n| industry = [[Real estate]]\n| products = Real estate brokerage services\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = 5000 (June 2019)\n| parent = \n| subsid =\n| homepage = [http://www.rightathomerealty.com www.RightAtHomeRealty.com]\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Right at Home Realty, Inc.''' (RAH) was listed in 2017 by [http://www.realtrends.com/products/rt250 Real Trends] as the [[real estate brokerage]] with the highest sales in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] (GTA), Canada (3.7% of the total, which was split among a great many brokerages).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bungol.ca/blog/popular_real_estate_brokerage_toronto_2017/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824034223/https://www.bungol.ca/blog/popular_real_estate_brokerage_toronto_2017/|archive-date=24  August 2018|title=Most Popular Real Estate Brokerage in Toronto|author=Jack|website=www.bungol.ca|access-date=2018-02-13}}</ref>  Right at Home Realty is a regional residential Real Estate Brokerage with over 5,000 sales reps that services the GTA.  The company was founded in 2004 by the late Arthur Bartram, Ronald E. Peddicord and Howard Drukarsh. RAH is a multi-office non-franchise corporate-run real estate brokerage.\n\nBased on 2017 Toronto Real Estate Board's sales statistics, Right at Home Realty Inc.'s 3.7% share made it the #1 performing Residential Real Estate Brokerage in the Greater Toronto Area for the 5th consecutive year.<ref>Source: Toronto Real Estate Board Data (January 1st to December 31st, 2016). Combined Units Sold</ref>\n\nRight at Home has ten offices in [[Don Mills]], [[Mississauga]], [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]], [[Whitby, Ontario|Whitby]], [[Vaughan]], [[Burlington, Ontario|Burlington]], [[Newmarket, Ontario|Newmarket]], Barrie, Ontario and 2 offices in Ottawa with over 5,000 brokers and salespeople.\n\nRight at Home Realty Inc. is a member of the Toronto Real Estate Board (TREB), the [http://www.omdreb.on.ca/ Oakville Milton Real Estate Board] (OMREB); the [http://www.rahb.ca/ Realtors Association of Hamilton-Burlington] (RAHB) the [http://www.durhamrealestate.org/ Durham Region Association of Realtors] (DRAR); the [http://www.boards.mls.ca/northumberland/ Northhumberland Hills Association of Realtors] (NHAB); and the [http://www.breb.org/ Brampton Real Estate Board] (BREB).\n\n==See also==\n* [http://www.reic.ca/en/home.cfm Real Estate Institute of Canada (REIC)]\n* [http://www.crea.ca/ The Canadian Real Estate Association (CREA)]\n* [http://www.orea.com/ Ontario Real Estate Association (OREA)]\n* [http://www.remonline.com/ Real Estate Magazine (REM Online)]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1295521/right-at-home-realty-brokerage-attains-the-1-spot-in-the-gta-in-just-10-years Right At Home Realty Brokerage Attains the #1 Spot in the GTA in Just Ten Years]\n* [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1299241/right-at-home-realty-donates-57-500-to-habitat-for-humanity Right At Home Realty Donates $57,500 to Habitat for Humanity]\n* [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1099547/the-home-inspection-networktm-and-right-at-home-realty-inc-announce-partnership Right At Home Realty Inc. and Dominion Lending Centres announce Partnership]\n* [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1216415/right-at-home-realty-launches-internettv-with-imagemaker360 Right At Home Realty Launches InternetTV with Imagemaker360]\n* [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1103849/right-at-home-realty-donates-55-000-to-habitat-for-humanity Right At Home Realty Dona